Claim: God exists.
Revelation through faithful practices, religious experiences, and testimony support the existence of God.
Many people have religious experiences involving God.
The fact others have personal experiences of God should be accepted as a good reason to believe God exists.
Some converts to Christianity attribute their conversion to an experience of God that they had (while still a non-believer).
Rejecting this would be like assuming a missing soldier is dead, while ignoring individual reports that he is alive.
Rejecting this would be like accepting you don't know whether or not a missing soldier is dead, regardless of reports he is alive, because he has not yet been found in either state.

There are important reasons for not being ambivalent about whether God is real or not, namely, that God is our Father, and that one's continued existence in a state of unending happiness or misery depend upon our motivation to find the true answer to this question. Honesty requires that we admit what we know and what we don't know, but discarding hope in the presence of uncertainty is unhelpful, hence the parent claim correctly reinforces the necessity of faith and hope.
Consistent application of this standard would require one to accept any and all such claims.  But we know contradictory experiences are commonly reported by adherents of different religions.
Accepting this would be like assuming fairies exist because people claim they've had a lost tooth replaced with money by the tooth fairy at night.
People are capable being tricked into thinking something is something it is not.
People are capable of lying.
The Apostles were eye witnesses to miracles, which are evidence that God exists.
There are many accounts of the Apostles witnessing miracles.

There is no contemporary or direct testimony on Jesus.  While there are records from Rome during the time he lived, there are zero contemporary references.  The gospels appear to have been written at least 70-300 years after the fact.Who would have noticed in Jesus' time?
Attempting to prove existence by means of “evidence” found within the pages of questionable texts is a circular argument that requires a leap of faith.
If "miracle" is defined as "an observed phenomenon which is not explained by current knowledge and seems to violate the laws of nature", then miracles are not evidence that a God exists.

Shows made by magicians seem to violate the laws of nature, however, they are known to use "tricks" to give the appearance of violating the laws of nature, and nothing supernatural actually happens. Spectators only "believe" the shows by willing suspension of disbelief, for entertainment purposes.
While spectators usually cannot explain what they have seen, they should not come to the conclusion that the magician has supernatural or divine powers.
We cannot asses how reliable the Apostles themselves are. People tell lies, or just are wrong sometimes, and that might be the case for them too.

There are experiential arguments for the existence of God as a universal power. Those reports come from some practitioners of Yoga, Meditation, and other spiritual practices. Even though these reports are not yet scientifically verified, the accounts are nearly identical.
The advanced and mature practitioners of religious/spiritual faiths from all over the world while disagreeing on details all see the same principles.

The experience is reproducible. The source of the experience is pure speculation. While the subjective experience is commonly felt across the world, the speculation of what causes it varies widely and tends to match preconceived notions taught by local tradition. Those interpretations contradict each other to such a great degree that one can conclude that there must not be universal source for the experience. If it was divine, then all experiencers would have the same explanation.
The practices of yoga and meditation do not require a belief in a god to be effective. Since a god is not common in all of these practices, it is not required to get the effects.

The claim is that many people all over the world have an experience of God. If some practice yoga and are atheists this is not relevant. Someone could use a microwave and not believe in radiation. Their food will still cook.

The practice of yoga was originally for the purpose of developing the ability to sit for long periods to meditate on God. The practices have many benefits for the body and mind which are useful for things other than meditating.

Atheistic practitioners of Yoga are only getting a shadow of the benefits to be had from Yoga. There are higher benefits to be had, namely developing Love for God, directly perceiving God, and loosing attraction for the dualistic pleasures of this world.
The account of a report that is not scientifically verified cannot afford a scientific impact.

The basis of empirical science rests on the assumption that only things which can be empirically verified can be taken with any certainty to be true. This assumption is circular in nature because there is no empirical way to back up this assumption.

The experience of Yoga, Meditation, etc can be easily explained by modern neurology as not being from God. The experiencer must interpret the subjective experience. Some interpret it as being from God, but that does not make it so. A person's interpretation will depend on their beliefs. So the argument is circular: a person who believes that Yoga experiences come from God, will interpret it as being from God. But it is not evidence of anything.

Altered states of consciousness including dreams, hallucinations, astral projections and other out-of-body experiences, often are of a spiritual nature or are instructive, hinting at a greater intelligence or at least the existence of something beyond the physical.

All mental states can be proven to be a function of the material operation of the brain.  There is no science suggesting there is anything supernatural going on. When a brain dies, it ceases any mental activity.

Dreams, hallucinations, astral projections and OBEs find physical expressions and can be interpreted as body phenomenons. Psychological experiences can explain and reproduce such phenomenons without involving "God".

Dreams and hallucinations can be interpreted in any way to confirm your beliefs. If you believe in 'anything', you can then twist dreams to fit within the narrative of your beliefs. Who's to say dreams don't 'actually' show that we are living in a virtual universe created by omnipotent chickens?

A self evident truth is the highest standard of establishing something to be true in epistemology. The direct experience of God is a claim of self evident truth. Plenty of people claim they have an experience of God.

The claim that an experience with God is equivalent to claiming moral values like equality and non-violence are true (i.e. real) because these claims are self evident (i.e. a claim which is of a metaphysical nature and which can not be established empirically).
A subjective experience of God is not the same type of claim as moral values. Religion and morality are not synonymous.
Religious claims and moral claims are similar in that they are both metaphysical
Religious claims and moral claims are similar in that they are both require the same kind of epistomology to establish them namely they need to be held as self-evident
Even if objective morality did exist, it is at least clear that whether it exists is debated, so to describe the truth of a moral value as "self-evident" is clearly false.
The value of equality and non-violence to a society can be empirically established.
Youth violence greatly increases the costs of health, welfare and criminal justice services; reduces productivity; and decreases the value of property.
Gun violence affects the economic health of communities.
The metrics for determining what's valuable to a society could run into some serious challenges. The same metrics might also show that eugenics is beneficial.

In this claim value is an unstated premise. Values of a society are established in a self-evident way the same way moral values are. All the above claims has done is push the problem back one step. The problem of needing a self-evident foundation upon which to build a value structure has not been removed.
All that would tell us is that it is beneficial to treat people as if they are equal. There would still be no objective sense in which equality exists.
Self evident truths are the highest in epistemology because they are the foundation upon which others truths are built.

Belief in God is produced in a way that violates no epistemic duty in believing and so is justified. Justification involves obedience to one’s epistemic duties or possession of a sound noetic structure of beliefs.

Man has a sensus divinitatis (sense of divinity) that grounds (justifies) belief in God by the appropriate circumstances making it properly basic. Alvin Plantinga speaks of sensus divinitatis as “a disposition or set of dispositions to form theistic beliefs in various circumstances or stimuli that trigger the working of this sense of divinity.”

Just as perceptual beliefs like “There is a tree” are not based on arguments from more basic beliefs but arise spontaneously in me when in the circumstances of a tree’s appearing to be there, so the belief “God exists” arises spontaneously when in appropriate circumstances, such as moments of guilt, gratitude, or awe at nature’s grandeur, as a result of the working of the sensus divinitatis.

Plantinga emphasizes that God’s existence is not inferred from such circumstances—such an argument would be manifestly inadequate—rather, the circumstances form the context in which the sensus divinitatis operates to produce a basic belief in God. Thus belief in God is not arbitrary; it is grounded by the appropriate circumstances and so is properly basic.

Insofar as more basic beliefs such as "my senses can be trusted" do not underlie one's perceptual beliefs, this is a sign of the irrationality of the human mind more than anything else, and the same is true for an imagined "sensus divinatus".

No one is born being able to recognize and name trees: this is acquired by teaching. Yet there is no teaching for the sensus divinitatis, and so we cannot be sure we correctly interpret the stimulus it supplies us.

"There is a tree" is prompted by certain visual stimuli, the proper functioning of which can be verified independent of the tree, and the belief in the tree can be corroborated by other senses, such as touching it. This is not the case with the sensus divinitatis.
The existence and proper functioning of a sensus divinitatis presumes the existence of a god to stimulate and be sensed by it. This is merely to beg the question.

The genuine existence of such a sensus divinitatis (SD) and its proper functioning lack critical validation. As such nothing distinguishes a genuine and properly-functional SD from a non-genuine or non-functional SD.

While humans clearly have some kind of disposition towards theism, or there would be no theists, to assume such disposition is correctly characterised as a sense as opposed to a collection of biases and heuristics is to beg the question.

If justification involves obedience to one's epistemic duties or possession of a sound noetic structure of beliefs, then this leads to radical relativism. If belief in any God can meet this criteria, then just any belief, it is alleged, such as Linus’ belief in the Great Pumpkin, can also be justified.

With respect to justification, we can imagine someone placed in circumstances in which belief in the Great Pumpkin would be justified for him. For example, Linus’ parents assured him of the existence of the Great Pumpkin. Yet, this doesn’t imply these beliefs are justified for normally situated adults because they would formulate de facto defeaters for their belief in the Great Pumpkin.
Belief in God is not merely justified but also warranted. Warrant is that property that converts mere true belief into knowledge when possessed in sufficient degree.

God has so constituted us that we naturally form belief in Him under certain circumstances; since the belief is thus formed by properly functioning cognitive faculties in an appropriate environment, it is warranted for us, and, insofar as our faculties are not disrupted by the noetic effects of sin, we shall believe this proposition deeply and firmly, so that we can be said, in virtue of the great warrant accruing to this belief for us, to know that God exists.”

S knows p if (1) the belief that p is produced in S by cognitive faculties that are functioning properly, (2) the cognitive environment in which p is produced is appropriate for those faculties, (3) the purpose of the module of the epistemic faculties producing the belief in question is to produce true beliefs, and (4) the objective probability of a belief’s being true, given that it is produced under those conditions, is high.
"The noetic effects of sin" is equivalent of saying to those who don't believe in God, "your God detector is broken because you are evil". This is an argument ad hominem.

Theists and atheists alike are impacted by the noetic effects of sin. The manifestation of the noetic effects of sin among theists could be different from atheists. For atheists, it may affect their belief in God but not necessarily their personal morals. For the theist, sin could keep them entrapped and committed to a way of life that God never intended for them to live. The impacts are different, but theists are subject to the effects of sin as well.

Saying "God has so constituted us that we naturally form belief in Him under certain circumstances" assumes the thesis of the entire debate and therefore can have no bearing on it. If we do not assume god exists we cannot assume god designed our faculties.

God's existence can be assumed when attempting to form a coherent epistemology. Naturalism does the same in reverse when attempting to form a coherent epistemology that wouldn't include a God (e.g. verificationism, the falsification principle). It is acceptable to ask, "if God is real, what kind of mechanisms would He have created for us to know Him?" and then work this into our epistemology.

The question of whether belief in God is warranted can’t be settled just by attending to epistemological considerations; it is at bottom not merely an epistemological dispute, but an ontological or theological dispute. It follows that there is no de jure (undermining) objection to theistic belief independent of the de facto (factual) question of whether theism is true.

Epistemic duty is self-set. How rigorous a person is when evaluating information is the task of critical thought, and that is a conscious dissection of evidence to ascertain veracity. Belief in God just means one is flexible, at least in some matters, because from scrutinizing and bias-aware epistemological purity of reason and objectivity, God cannot be found. That's why the word "faith" is required.

Plenty of people claim, and some of them sincerely believe, to have encountered (or been abducted by) extraterrestrial beings who hides from the other humans. That is not enough to know that said beings actually exist.
A self-evident conclusion is most likely an example of the fallacy begging the question.

If self-evident truth is begging the question, then not only can God not be proven, but everything else anyone could ever hope to know about anything would be subject to an infinite regress or proofs. There would be no way to prove that this material world is real and that other people exist outside of our minds.

Self-evident proof is the epistemological alternative to Quine's Web of Belief, the idea that there are no foundational or axiomatic proofs but rather an interdependent web. This web philosophy is in essence a well dressed plea for circular reasoning as an epistemological frame work. The web alternative is the one guilty of begging the question.

Direct experience, as asserted above, does not equate to logical or scientific proof in this case or even a true belief with justification.Many experienced and saw tears falling from trees and assumed they were the tears of the virgin... when they were shown that it was, in fact, defecating insects they were unmoved in their belief. Direct experience does not solve epistemology's problem of justification in this case.

In this case, repeated direct experience (observational evidence) is the source for demonstrating the insects were the cause. Thus, the parent argues this direct experience somehow invalidates direct experience as a source of justification.
A truth that is self-evident must be objectively true for anyone who considers it.
Descartes started with "I exist," as his self-evident, a priori truth. That we exist seems far more certain than God exists.
However, that Descartes exists is not self-evident to other people, and as such self-existence is self-evident but not objective.
The "self" in self-evident does not refer to an individual that is perceiving, but that truth which is perceptible by everyone.
The "self" in self-evident merely refers to the fact that a truth is evident in its own right without need for external corroboration, but this has nothing to do with whether the truth is objective.
The existence of the force we call gravity is self-evident. Everyone perceives there is something that pulls us towards the ground.

Everyone perceives that we are pulled towards the ground, but ancients who explained why things fall without invoking as-yet-undiscovered gravity, or flat-Earthers today engaging in denialism, did and do not perceive that gravity self-evidently exists. Gravity is verified by empirical science, not self-evidence.
The God experience has been reproduced in labs. We cannot trust the testimony of others at face value and even our own experiences must be subject to inquiry.

The God experience has been reproduced by shamans and hierophants from different faiths using hallucinogens and rituals for thousands of years. While they may represent genuine contact with the divine, as outsiders we can no longer reasonably place these testimonies above critique or close examination.

Replicating a God-like experience in a lab only leads to the conclusion that there may be a physical component to interactions with God. It does not follow that people are not having veridical experiences with God or the spiritual realm.

While true that we cannot eliminate the possibility of a genuine spiritual experience, it is also true that we no longer can insist on interpreting a stranger's testimony as a factual account of spiritual experience.

If further evidence or knowledge could add something we cannot claim a "highest standard". For example, direct experience of God could be further evidenced if many people plus the individual directly experience it. It could be further still if data supported it and further still if experts agreed.
Believing that other people’s experiences reinforce our own is itself a self-evident truth that must come before we consider those experiences. Thus, self-evident truths come first.
Some set of axioms are required for any system of logic or "bounded argument". This does not prove the equivalent value of two sets of axioms.

All systems of logic and belief rest on axioms ( including this statement ). The mere existence of "first" premises, principles or assumptions does not negate or prove the truth value of a system of logic or belief. Various methods such as science, themselves having axioms, are used to evaluate the fitness or truth value of systems of belief or logic based on a given context -- which, itself will contain axioms.
Believing that data (regardless of knowledge source) provides further evidence that reinforces our immediate experience is itself a self-evident truth. Thus, self-evident truths come first.

Differing sets of self-evident truths can be judged on their relative fitness in a given context. In the context of proving the existence of God to others, direct experience and testimony, by themselves, are literally and measurably less than themselves plus further evidence. Experience A is less than Experience A plus Evidence B.
God spoke to Moses "as a man speaketh to another." Exodus 33:11.
There is no archaeological or paeleological evidence to suggest Moses existed. In fact, most biblical historians do not believe he existed.
You cannot use the book stating that God exist as a proof that God exist.
This is circular reasoning. You cannot use scripture to prove itself legitimate.

You can't prove the existence of the author of a writing with the argument that it's written in the writing. It is written in the Hobbit, or there and back again that Bilbo Baggins is writing "there and back again" therefore Bilbo Baggins exists. Yet we know that Bilbo Baggins is a fictional character invented by Tolkien.

This claim is not about the Bible claiming it is true. It is about the Bible containing scientific facts and ethical principles which are ahead of their time and predictions of the future which can reasonably be explained by devine inspritation.
Bible "ahead of their times" scientific facts are useless since we needed to develop science to confirm them, also they have been debunked.
Other traditions had comparable or superior ethical principles before the Bible was compiled.
Predictions of the future can be more reasonably explained by post events edits, and anyway have been debunked.
God the Father and Jesus Christ visited Joseph Smith. First Vision

Joseph Smith was a well known charlatan for his time, and ended up being murdered by his own followers after it was revealed he was deceiving them.  There's no evidence that the Book of Mormon is anything other than fiction.Joseph Smith
A religious person claiming that they had a religious experience is not proof of anything other than that person's religiousness.

If we apply the same principle (personal experience is not evidence) to materialism we run into the same problem as when applied to theism. If personal experience is not evidence then there is no way to prove that the material world exists. Extreme skeptism about human experience has unintended consequences as it devastates any conceivable epistemological foundation.
This does not provide an explanation for atheists who have religious experiences.

An atheist who has a compelling religious experience would no longer be an atheist, so by this standard no account of personal revelation would be valid no matter how trustworthy or reliable. It's like a flat-earther denying all orbital photographs of the Earth's curve that weren't taken by a fellow flat-earther.

The above claim is predicated on a bias world view (materialism) which filters evidence (anything indicating a metaphysical reality) according to its bias and then claims there is no evidence to contradict the bias. It's therefore guilty of begging the question.

People of all religions claim to have had religious experiences that pertain to their belief systems. This suggests that religious experiences are psychological or social phenomena, rather than genuine experiences of a particular god.

Evangelical Christians claim to have experienced the presence of Jesus. Catholics claim to have have experienced the Virgin Mary or a saint. Muslims claim to have had a religious experience with Allah. Buddhists with Buddha and Hindus with Krishna or another deity and so on and so on.
Many people have experiences which they interpret as involving God. But these may be misinterpretations of experiences which don't actually involve and God.
Some people have religious experiences of the absence of God. If the same standard applies in these cases, these would serve as evidence for atheism.

Anecdotal evidence is the least reliable kind of evidence. This means experiences (in this context with god) have little to no value when it comes to proving whether a proposition (the existance of god) is true or false.
The fact that memories are faulty means that recollection of experiences can not be trusted at face value, hence the unreliability of anecdotal evidence.
Lighter and more complete theories than "God" can explain extraordinary phenomenons.

For example, Lourdes is regarded as a sanctified site for many Catholics where miraculous healing would appear, but in fact, there are no more cancer healings in this site than there are spontaneous unexplained cancer healing in any other place.
See Les miracles, Lourdes et les probabilités (French), quote: "We can say that with 67 healings in slightly more than 150 years, results are not more impressive in Lourdes that in hospitals."
Individual experiences are not sufficient evidence as people are able to experience things that do not match reality.
People have had similar experiences regarding e.g. pagan gods and nature spirits, so unless we accept that all of these exist we cannot use this as proof of God's existence.

Such experiences do not necessarily validate God specifically. They could validate any of numerous other things. The individual might only interpret the experience as religious as a result of confirmation bias.

Lack of validation is no indication of the opposite. Even the scientific method is not interested in validation, only falsification and partial support, which is offered by personal religious experiences.

The scientific method definitely cares about validation precisely because so many scientific observations are of effects with only statistical results.   The more independent trials validating the result the more unlikely the negative is. What you are observing is a publication bias caused by journals so aren't interested in publishing results like "Yes, relativistic effects have been demonstrated yet again", etc.
The evidence in favor of different religions differs wildly. Thus, there is reason to believe one religion is correct and the others are wrong.
Religions that have been present for a longer period of time have tradition on their side, which newer religions lack.
Human societies had the tradition of not granting people equal rights, but the West abandoned that practice as being wrong. Thus, something being a tradition is thus not of importance.

Tradition carries no weight in arguments, as something being assumed in the past is not sufficient reason to believe it is true. Neither is the fact that something was done in the past evidence that it is the best option. In fact, history is littered with examples of erroneous traditions.

It can be true that "something being assumed in the past is not sufficient reason to believe it is true," while at the same time being also true that "tradition carries weight in arguments."

This is because though tradition is not a sufficient reason for belief, it can be an important part of a set of reasons, and often is a necessary condition for belief.
If there are a set of reasons something was believed in the past, the reasons themselves should be presented, instead of the fact that they were believed in the past.

If a true God would not allow his religion to die, then it is necessarily the case that all the myriad pagan religions which have died off are false, and one of the currently existent religions must be true.
There is no reason for us to belive that a true God would not allow his religion to die and, as it stands, it is a mere speculation.
Most religions have a "free will" notion which would not be possible if God "would not allow" his religion to die as that would be violation of the free will.
This is merely to punt to something beyond religious experience, making the argument from religious experience itself moot.

Difference in the strength of the evidence is reason to believe that some are more likely than others to be true, if at least one religion is true. It is not reason enough to go the further steps to believe one specific religion is in fact true.

It is perfectly coherent to believe that most religions simply have an incomplete or different experience or understanding of the same God, so it's not necessary to reject every doctrine of their belief or declare that they're entirely wrong. This belief is called inclusivism.
God may have revealed Himself in different ways to suit different cultures, and to help them with their specific spiritual journey.
That would in fact be what a God who was good as defined by the classical definition would do. We know that problems are very different and require different approaches and solutions.

A god that reveals himself in such ways as to support contradictory conceptions of god would be making himself seem incompatibly different to different people. This constitutes deception and thus wouldn't be something a good and loving God would do.

Prior to modern archeology, many cultures discovered dinosaur bones and called them dragons. The fact that they were wrong about many of the attributes of dinosaurs doesn't mean we have to completely reject their experience of fossils.

There are many competing interpretations of quantum mechanics, but the fact that only one of them can be entirely right doesn't mean that we are forced to reject all of them, or to reject quantum theory itself.
The different interpretations of QM make the same predictions about what we'd observe in the world. The same cannot be said of religions.
By saying many/all religions have a flawed/incomplete/different understanding of the same god it brings humanity no closer to understanding God.
That is effectively stating that either polytheists or monotheists are wrong, as to why, is irrelevant. Both cannot be right at the same time.
In order to know God, one must believe that God exists while engaging in faithful practice.
Kialo discurssion:     One should believe that God exists, even if they are not sure it's true.

The Catechism of the Catholic Church (#47) declares that "the one true God, our Creator and Lord, can be known with certainty from his works, by the natural light of human reason (cf. Vatican Council I, can. 2 § 1: DS 3026)."
This is circular reasoning.  An institution that depends upon the existence of god produces literature that self-verifies its own claims.

According to Protagoras, "Man is the measure of all things" and, therefore, "For those that believe god exists, he exists; for those that do not believe god exists, he does not exist." Subjectivity entails uncertainty and, therefore, no support can be given.
If subjectivity entails uncertainty, then no special support can be given to the mere human Protagoras, and the argument that we cannot support a notion from philosophy defeats itself.

A person can come to know God exists by learning about his will and then practicing it for a period of time. If what you have learned and implemented is true, God will communicate it to you, and by this you will know that God exists.
Jesus says 'my sheep hear my voice', so the believers who hear Jesus' voice can confirm that Jesus exists.
The Bible is fallible, demonstrably incorrectand demonstrably changed. There is no independent evidence that Jesus said any such thing.

This is a circular argument resting on the hearer accurately identifying the source of the voice. If person A snuck up behind person B and whispered in their ear "I am Jesus talking to you" it would NOT be evidence of Jesus' existence. The hearer might think it is from Jesus, but that does not make it so.
This process can be replicated with contradictory definitions of "God" from different religions.
This relies on subjective experiences. When a person affirms that God is communicating with him/her we don't have any mean to verify if that is true.

At it's core, this argument claims "God exists because the Bible says that God exists and the Bible is the word of God." This is a blatant fallacy, begging the question. Using statements from a Christian text that presupposes the existence of God as "proof" of God's existence is circular logic.

"Using statements from a Christian text that presupposes the existence of God as 'proof' of God's existence is circular logic" is only true if the trust in the Christian text is warranted exclusively by its claims to be God's word. Most Christian scholars evaluate the trustworthiness of the Bible as they do any other text, including the use of textual criticism.

Such circular logic is valid, but the "proof" from the parent claim would be considered independent in its source (i.e from God). This is because the teachings/words themselves are not evidence of God but rather the consequences of it.
There are pragmatic reasons to believe in the existence of God.
Many people believe in God. To them it seems it exists.
Many people also believe in faeries,  which is why we have to temper the opinion of the many with the wisdom of the few according to Aristotle.
Given any particular religion in 2017, there are at least twice as many non-followers as followers in the world. Would that mean that God mostly does not exist?
The fact that many people believe something says nothing about the truth value of that thing. To presuppose so is the fallacy of argumentum ad populum.
Believing in something doesn't mean it exists.

Adopting a similar philosophy of people with whom you can benefit by association is a time-honored practice.

Although this doesn't necessarily contribute to any material evidence that such beliefs are true.
Pragmatism is irrelevant to philosophy and truth. There are many inconvenient truths.
Illusions can have pragmatic reasons. Convenience doesn't support the veracity of the argument.
There are pragmatic reasons not to believe in God as well.

One can eat whatever one wants (beef is forbidden in the major branches of Hinduism, meat in general in some branches, pork in Islam and Judaism), whenever one wants (Ramadan in Islam, Lent in Christianity), unlike many religions.

Such reasons include not having to follow set-in-stone rituals that use up one's time and energy (e.g. prayer five times a day for islam, shabbath for judaism, church on sunday for christianism, and many others )
Many people enjoy rituals such as prayer.

People don't have to feel guilty for normal behaviours such as (but not restricted to) masturbation or out-of-wedlock-sex; indeed religions tend to shame such practices whereas they are actually normal and healthy. The guilt that such activities bring can prevents people from doing them, or cause mental distress when people do.

There are no empirical proofs or conclusive logical-philosophical demonstrations of the existence of God. God is only known in faith. You can never 'prove' the nature of that experience to those without faith, as by definition that experience is personal.
Faith and belief are cognitive functions the holder possess because of the inability to explain super complex ideas and sensations beyond the mental maturity of the holder.

Empirical (or scientific) proofs presuppose purely material phenomena, which, given that God is immaterial, means that there could never, even in principle, be a purely empirical proof of the existence of God.

If God is pure actuality, then he cannot be material (physical), for matter always and necessarily contains an admixture of potentiality.

(In fact, traditional Aristotelian understanding of matter is that it is pure potentiality, but agreement with this idea is not necessary for the statement about God to be true.)

The God claim and any possible proof of it is metaphysical therefore it may never be proven by experimentation, fixing it outside the knowable. This means that to believe in God one will always have to make a very large series of assumptions, which leaves the believer open to a wealth of inaccuracies. To not believe must be the default.

Metaphysical means neither "beyond experimentation" nor "outside the knowable". It means beyond sensual. Senses are the common platform on which science is founded. This only means that objectivity of metaphysical cannot be verified by senses. But in religion there are also experiments, knowledge and the sharing of knowledge. Difference is in spiritual knowledge being subjective and beyond senses. Not a series,but a single assumption on "where all this came from" or "what is my purpose" will do.

It is an error to presume that only that which is measurable can be shown to exist. The abstract number "1" exists. Yet we cannot measure the number 1 itself. Thus, although we may not have a way to measure a god, it does not necessarily follow that there is no reason to believe a god exists.
Qualia are another existing feature of reality that cannot be measured.
The number 1 has been tested. A god's existence has not been tested.
1 can be defined as "a singular". Singulars exist. The term "1" is therefore measurable and testable.
No physical test can be created to prove the existence of an abstract entity. The number 1 has not been empirically shown to exist in its own right. It can be logically demonstrated to exist, though.
1 is a measurement. It does not require measurement. God is not a measurement and therefore should be measurable.
The concept of "1" is used to comprehend measurements. The concept exists. But the concept itself cannot be measured.
Measurements are standardized. A god is not.
The classical definition of God is fairly standardized.
Morality can't be precisely measured in terms of gods.
Knowledge can't be precisely measured in terms of gods.
Time can't be precisely measured in terms of gods.
Power can't be precisely measured in terms of gods.
Science is not the only source of human knowledge. Indeed “science is the only source of knowledge” is not a scientific claim and therefore undermines itself.

Science is not a source of knowledge, it is simply one way to structure and interpret the information before our senses.  Knowledge can be accumulated from data that we collect, and we can use science to analyze the data.  Yes, there are non-scientific methods of data analysis, but those methods have not been proven effective.

The date of New Testament books is debated by historians, with some evidence that they were written fairly early, and some portions such as the creed in 1 Corinthians being reliably and uncontroversially dated to within a few years of Pentecost.

Many secular historians date the book of Mark to after 70 AD because it contains a prophecy of the destruction of the Second Temple, which occurred that year. However, this assumes not only that Jesus couldn't have made a correct prophecy, but also that it couldn't simply be apocalyptic language echoing the earlier destruction of the temple.

Atheist historian Maurice Casey argues that Mark was written in the AD 40's by correlating Mark 13:14 with the Caligula crisis when the emperor threatened to set up his statue in the Temple, proposing that Mark’s translations of Aramaic sources was still unrefined, and insisting that Mark assumes Torah observance before major debates on the issue (e.g. Jerusalem Council).

Many secular historians argue that Mark must have been the first Gospel to be written, since it is the shortest, and later Gospels were based on it. However, this idea is not universally accepted, with many arguing that Matthew came before Mark.

Most evidence of "human intuition" being unreliable covers only the first two cases.

Even if our observable Universe is finite and came to exist at time zero: A) we know nothing and will probably continue to know nothing of what caused its existence (lack of explanation is better than any explanation in the total absence of evidence); and B) the hypothesis that beyond this Universe are other universes, potentially infinite in number and space-time, cannot be falsified.
The universe could have been the result of a spontaneous event.
The existence of something that has a beginning or is contingent, but yet does not have a cause has never been observed.
No event can be truly "spontaneous", in the sense of lacking a cause. Even if they seem random, events are necessarily the result of their surroundings and of some external action.
Events definitionally refer to objects, spatiotemporal contexts, and causal relationships. An event cannot occur without a cause.
Per se causal chains cannot regress to infinity, as opposed to per accidens causal chains.
Even if it is true that causal chains cannot regress infinitely, assuming that the first cause is God is begging the question.

A causal chain can regress to infinity just as it can continue onward to infinity, provided that no change in the given direction of time starts from or results in something which is incapable of accumulating change, and provided the environment involved doesn't reach a stage in the given direction of time which permanently prohibits the accumulation of change in that temporal direction.

"per accidens" (or linear) causal chains can indeed regress to infinity.

However, there is another kind of causal chain. This kind of causal chain cannot, by its very nature, regress to infinity. "Per se" (or hierarchical) causal chains are ones where each link has its causal power instrumentally, not inherently. Per se causal chains occur simultaneously, all at once.

To bring "time" into the discussion is to discuss per accidens causal chains, which are not a part of the proof.
Infinite causal chains are possible in an infinite universe.

Only "per accidens" chains may regress to infinity. (These are also occasionally referred to as linear chains.)

"Per se" chains may not regress to infinity, regardless of the infinitude (or lack thereof) of the universe. (These are also occasionally referred to as hierarchical chains.)

Per se causal chains are composed of a principal cause, and a series of subsequent instrumental causes. An instrumental cause is one that derives whatever causal power it has from something else. In Aquinas’ famous example, the stick that the hand uses to push the stone has no power to push the stone on its own, but derives its stone-moving power from the hand, which uses it as an “instrument.” A principal cause is one that does have its causal power inherently.
Objects do not need to obtain their causal power from the action of another object as though causal power were some kind of object itself which passes on from one entity to another.
Causal language describes the way in which objects in a temporal distribution relate to each other.
A temporal distribution can vary in either temporal direction infinitely and be an infinite causal chain so long as causal relations continue to hold in either direction.

If the assumption that spontaneous events were impossible was valid, every event would need a cause, meaning there could be no first event. It has already been assumed/shown in the proof from composition, that there must be a first event. Therefore spontaneous event, at least in the context of this discussion, must be possible.
In the context of the cosmological arguments, first events don't lack a cause. Instead, they are caused by an external entity, which is itself causeless.

If an external entity is causeless, it must be spontaneous, therefore making the external entity's existence a spontaneous event. Since a spontaneous event is necessary, to create this entity, there is no reason to believe the entity causing event would be any more likely then a universe creating event.
The law of causality works within the universe, where time exists.
Causes and effects are events in the universe. They occur at a given time, in a given place. There is no event where and when 'The universe began to exist'.

Cosmologists who consider multiverse theory assume that laws of causality still hold outside of our universe in the larger multiverse. In other words, they see no reason to offer a defense of the laws of causality when moving to a contexts where the laws of physics might be entirely different. This is suggestive that we all intuitively think of the law of causality as a metaphysical principle that applies to any physical reality and not just to our particular universe.
Any 'physical reality' would have matter and hence time. This confirms the claim that causality works within the universe, where time exists.

"Multiverse theory" is ill-specified. The many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics - the most prominent theory of a multiverse - implies universes with identical physical laws, so causality would obviously be present but not in a sense for which this argument would be relevant.
'Beginning' is a human definition, there is no objective nature to this term. As the definition is subjective in nature saying the universe 'began' is not specific enough to be useful.
A person could define them-self as beginning at the time of birth, conception, or the development of the ovum within their maternal parent.
For example it could be defined that the universe began at the big bang, or at the point that time is measurable (post plank time).

The definition A5 is not preferable to the following alternative definition: x comes into being between times A and B iff x exists at time B and x does not exist at time A. By this definition, the universe did not come into existence, as there is no time A at which the universe did not exist. Moreover, on this definition, "if X comes into existence, x has a cause" is more plausible than on A5. Thus, we should reject A5 in favor of the above.

Using the above linked definition of 'begins to exist', the universe did not begin to exist. Time exists within the universe (as a direction in spacetime), and not the other way around. Therefore it doesn't make sense to say 'The universe exists at time t.'
This assumes a B-theory of time and would be undermined on an A-Theory of time
The phrase "begins to exist" cannot be adequately defined such that it applies to the universe but not to God (see Bobier 2013 or this blog summarizing the paper)
X's being is a tensed fact defined in terms of x becoming in a temporal sense. This is circular as 'temporal becoming' is the same as 'beginning'.

A theist could allow God to be temporally prior to the universe (i.e. time exists before the universe), which would cause the article's objection to BTE2 ("X begins to exist at T1 iff (i) X exists at T1 and (ii) there is no time prior to T1 at which X exists"), to fail.
Kialo discurssion:     The existence of a transcendent Creator is demonstrated through the Kalam argument.
The universe began to exist ("began to exist" defined here at definition A5)
The evidence in cosmology is best explained by Big Bang theory, which implies that our observable universe began to exist
Naive extrapolation of the Big Bang theory back in time implies a singularity in the past for our universe

Big Bang theory is based on theories of physics that do not apply at the energy scales attained during the earliest moments of the universe (e.g. Planck time). Therefore the retrodictions of Big Bang theory all the way to a singularity are not reliable.
If the retrodictions of Big Bang theory are considered unreliable because time is modified, we have no plausible reason to believe physics changes so dramatically as to avoid a beginning
The Borde-Guth-Vilenkin theorem shows that any physically plausible model of the universe which is, on average, expanding throughout its lifetime, most plausibly has a beginning.
When accounting for quantum phenomena the universe is predicted to have had no beginning.
The Lamda Cold Dark Matter Model describes a beginning to the universe due to quantum phenomena.

The class of cosmologies satisfying Borde-Guth-Vilenkin are not limited to inflating universes. Of particular interest is
the recycling scenario  in which each comoving region
goes through a succession of inflationary and thermalized
epochs.

In some versions of the cyclic model the brane spacetimes
are everywhere expanding, so this theorem immediately
implies the existence of a past boundary at which boundary conditions must be imposed.

In other versions, there are brief periods of contraction, but the net result of each cycle is an expansion. For null geodesics each cycle is identical to the others, except for the overall normalization of the affine parameter. Thus, as long as Hav > 0 for a null geodesic when averaged over one cycle, then Hav > 0 for any number of cycles, and this theorem would imply that the geodesic is incomplete.
If the retrodictions of Big Bang theory are considered unreliable because time breaks down completely, then one still has a universe which begins to exist
There is no sense in which the Plank era can be said to 'precede' the classical universe and so our universe still has a beginning

Currently, no physical model exists for explaining how our classical universe, which has a well-defined notion of time, could emerge from or be causally connected to a Planck era in which time has completely broken down (Deltete & Guy 1996). So this Planck era is indistinguishable from an independent universe, leaving our universe with a beginning
If our universe was infinitely old it would have undergone heat death long ago, and it hasn't.
Our universe would not be heat dead if it undergoes a cycle that restores it to a state of low entropy.

Without an external source of energy, such a cycle would lose energy after every iteration, like a basketball losing energy after every bounce unless it is being dribbled.

After a long, but finite number of cycles, the universe would indeed suffer heat death. In an infinitely old universe, this would have happened an infinitely long time ago.

Our universe would not be heat dead if it didn't have activity for an infinitely long period of time (ie. by being quantum mechanically infinitesimally probable to suffer any change during it's infinitely long initial stage).
"Infinitely long" implies that time was existent during this time, which is philosophically impossible.
This ignores Brownian motion. If the assertion is that even Brownian motion did not happen, then it appears that the universe was already in heat death.
There is at least one cosmological model that does not hold that the universe began to exist and is better supported by current evidence.
Steady state models do not hold that the universe began to exist.
The Gott-Li model (Closed Timelike Curves) does not hold that the universe began to exist.
If there is a cosmological model of a universe with an infinite past, that is better supported by current evidence, it would replace the Big Bang as the mainstream theory.
Multiverse theories fail by every philosophical measure.

Multiverse theories have low explanatory power: P1. A perfectly random system is more likely to produce simpler results than more complex ones P2. There are simpler possible universes than ours which contain conscious beings P3. We should expect to find ourselves in the most common situation that produces observers (Copernican principle) C. Under multiverse theories, our existence in this universe is unlikely
By contrast to the multiverse theory, a conscious creator could have many valid reasons to create a more complex universe like our own.
The complexity/size of the universe may have been intended specifically to add weight to the teleological argument and bring more people to belief.
The complexity/size of the universe results in great beauty, which a perfect creator would prefer.
A creator would prefer a beautiful, densely inhabited universe more.
There may be any number of reasons why an arbitrarily large number of inhabitants is not preferable to the creator.
Any reason why God would not value a large number of inhabitants works equally well for God not valuing any inhabitants.
"I want the inhabitants to have an arbitrary large and unchallenged space to develop during eons" is a reason that works for valuing a single source of inhabitants and not for zero inhabitants.
It is possible that a simpler/smaller universe would result in fewer saved souls or overall less moral goodness in the world.
An omnipotent being could save all souls if it wanted to, so it does not make sense that adding more would decrease the number of souls saved.
Salvation requires free choice by the saved. It is definitionally impossible to force a creature to freely choose something, so God would not be able to do this.

Classical theists do not believe that omnipotence was ever meant to include logical impossibilities. There is no thing which God cannot do, and logical contradictions are not truly things but inconsistent bugs in language.
God also constrains himself with his own attributes. That is, his love cannot invalidate his justice, his justice invalidate his grace, and his grace invalidate his requirement of righteousness.

Justice and Grace and (arguably) love are specifically Christian claims on the nature of God that are not necessarily entailed by the classical theist conception of Pure Act that is omniscient, omnipotent, and benevolent.

Omnipotence is the quality of having unlimited power, not the ability to do anything. There are some actions which God may be unable to do, but not due to a lack of power - and so they don't contradict His omnipotence.
One might consider logically incompatible actions such as creating a round square, or a married bachelor, as not within the grasp of omnipotence, as they by definition cannot exist.

The universe, by virtue of containing all possible actors, can do anything that is possible, knows everything that is knowable, therefore, under this line of reasoning, the universe is God, and since whatever God is is good, that's the last point checked off. Since the universe is not God, something we've assumed must be wrong, omnipotence without agency, or God being morality seem like the most likely candidates.
There is no place, other then outside of space and time, that the universe could exist, every where, and when is part of the universe.
Power and ability are related, and therefore an unlimited amount of power means an unlimited ability.

Quoting from the cited link, "The term omnipotent has been used to connote a number of different positions. These positions include, but are not limited to, the following:

1. A deity is able to do anything that it chooses to do."

If God was not able to eliminate some of the suffering that is happening in today's word, because it would be impossible for him to do so, that implies that the suffering must be necessary. Given that some suffering is really unnecessary, this seems illogical in itself.
An omni-benevolent, omniscient and omnipotent God would never have created a world where 30-75% of all fertilized soul-imbued eggs are being miscarried.

Unbaptized babies might very well not go to heaven. "The Catholic Catechism says infants might be saved without baptism, but stops short of affirming that all will be—though John Paul II, in his EvangeliumVitae, implies that unborn children would be."
The lack of clarity in the positions of one (of hundreds) of religions does nothing to disprove the existence of God.
Job 33:4, it states: “The spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.”, so the soul is not imparted until the first breath.
As the giver of life, God has the prerogative to take life at any time in whatever manner he chooses.
Not all classical theists believe that unborn children have souls or can experience pain.
An omni-benevolent, omniscient and omnipotent God would never have created a world where terrible things like famine and starvation exist.
In a sense, none of the Abrahamic religions say that that world is the one God created: human evil was a later edit on God's creative work.

This is an appeal to emotion. Humans may find it hard to imagine a reason for such an event, but our justifiable horror at such an event does not constitute evidence that God could not, would not, or should not have allowed it to happen.

The alternative would be for God to incessantly meddle in every single action we take that does not contribute to a Good exactly as He demands and requires. We could not avoid becoming whimpering childlike mortals, in any case.

This not a problem if reincarnation exists because God could be giving lessons and karma to souls who have done bad things in previous lives. In other words, they are not only little babies if they are souls starting off again in a new body.
Ian Stevenson has done comprehensive research pointing towards reincarnation.
Many religious traditions believe in reincarnation, and if they don't they often used to at some point in their development, or had off shoots that did.
That suffering baby could be little baby Hitler.

This explanation implies God uses cruel and unusual punishment that would be regarded as an unconscionable atrocity if it were carried out by a human justice system, and so is itself an argument against a God with the three "omnis".

On a theoretical level the above claim can be defeated because it's theoretically possible that a greater evil would be done by not allowing evil. On a practical level what this translates to is the fact that sometimes pain and suffering are necessary in order to prevent a greater evil.

Unfortunately many people don't take good instruction, don't learn from the mistakes of others, and often, even when faced with negative consequences, don't learn the folly of their ways. For such stubborn and slow learners pain and suffering can be the only thing that will teach them.

If a person causes suffering to others what they need to learn is compassion. Compassion is best learned through first hand suffering. Think of suffering in a future birth for actions committed now like cosmic sensitivity training.
An example of this is going to the dentist. The dentist causes some pain in order to prevent a worse pain.

This explanation abrogates free will; if a child is born into a family situation where he will be abused as punishment for sins in a past life, then his abuser cannot have free will in choosing whether to abuse him.
The above premise is false. It's possible for God to arrange for someone who chooses to do something bad to someone to do it to someone who has that coming as part of their karma.

It's also possible for someone who wants to do something bad to someone to be unable to do it. This is consistent with the theological view that God only allows those to be abused who have some lesson to learn from the experience.

An omni-benevolent, omniscient and omnipotent God would never have created a world where billions of people never had the chance to follow his religion and ascend to heaven, because they lived in places that had never heard of the Bible.
It is entirely possible that he has some other plan that will allow them to learn of it and accept it or not.
An omni-benevolent, omniscient and omnipotent God would never have created a world where extremely sick babies are being born, just to have them suffer for a couple of hours before dying.
If God wanted to bring them to heaven, he could have other means than letting them perish on Earth before bringing them to him.
They did not come to Earth by their own volition, but were made by two adults, so this cannot be attributed to babies' free will.

The vast majority of infant mortality occurs in underdeveloped countries due to poor health care and low resources. In the modern world there is plenty of resources to take care of all of humanity. As such, infant mortality is largely due to negligence by humans, rather than by God.
An all powerful, all good god would both want and be able to prevent such suffering, no matter the cause.

God's responsibility is not absolved by merely providing humanity "enough" resources for human negligence to be a partial cause. If you leave a baby with someone who you know is criminally negligent, you have some responsibility when that baby dies.
An omni-benevolent, omniscient and omnipotent God would never have created a world where more than six million Jews had to die in the Holocaust.
He would if he felt that mankind should be allowed to have free will.
It is equally likely that God created a world where people had free will, even if they used it foolishly or for evil. The alternative would be God forcing all people to do good.
Even were that true, the fact that God is not omni-benevolent does not imply that He does not exist. Many of the Gods worshipped throughout history have not been omni-benevolent.
The idea that the greatest good is the reduction or complete avoidance of suffering is not true. There are greater goods that result from suffering. For example: perseverance and sacrifice.

Neither perseverance, nor sacrifice are valuable on their own, they are only valuable as a means to an end. For example, we don't go around killing ourselves to promote the good of sacrifice, nor do we compel other too.

We are not in a position to know whether particular sufferings are unnecessary from God's position because our understanding of the vast web of causes and effects of particular sufferings could not reasonably be expected to measure up to an all-knowing God's.

If God's morality is beyond our comprehension, even given our imperfect being, we must act on the information that we have, because it is the only information we have, and thus what God wanted us to see. If we see God's morality as subjective, it is God's will that we interpret it as such.

It is circular reasoning to assume our limited view and reasoning is God's will for our understanding of eternal truth... but our limited view and reasoning is precisely what prevents us from fully understanding eternal truths.

It is tautological to assume we know God's will without basis. This can be remedied either by denying God's existence, or assuming he desires us to know what we do. A third option does not readily present itself, so we should assume what we can deduce.
It is generally accepted that God sets the rules for the universe. If God sets the rules for what is paradoxical and what is not, then God can change the rules if God is so inclined.
Omnipotence is sometimes defined as "maximal power," which includes the ability to do anything possible, but does not include the ability to do anything impossible or paradoxical.

"A stone that can't be lifted by an omnipotent being" isn't a thing that God can't create because it's not a thing, only a series of words that have been put in a certain order. This only defeats God's omnipotence in the same way as His inability to create a married bachelor.
Logic and order in the universe follow from the logic and order of the Creator. While He might be able to create such a rock by His omnipotence, being consistent, it is unlikely He would.

Not only due to being consistent, logically it may also be due to have an ever-increasing potency. If perfection of God is a dynamic concept, then His potency is not fixed at some point, but is always striving towards infinity. Then it would be possible for Him to create with His maximum, and at the next moment He might as well exceed that maximum.
To affirm even the theoretical possibility that God "might" be able to do logical inconsistencies makes the concept of God a contradiction.
An example of such inconsistency would be considered a "miracle". Generally such are thought to be consistent with the concept of "theistic god".

It is reasonable to assume an omnipotent God could refashion the laws of nature and logic to suite such a hypothetical. So to suggest that he "might" is not necessarily a contradiction to the notion of God.

Logic cannot be hacked. 2+2 is always 4, some principles must be followed. As far as we know, there is no example when logic goes bananas. Logic may be a limited tool, which cannot grasp the reality in total, but is an accurate one. We must follow this rule in order to have a meaningful debate, unless we are shown how exactly laws of logic can be refashioned in some possible reality and what are the consequences of that intervention, meaning change in any parameter may  be logically compensated.
an omniscient God that would be able to know that a bigger universe would mean less saved souls would be able to direct the universe in such a way that more souls were saved.
Since God isn't limited in time, resources, or motivation, He would have no reason to prefer a simpler/smaller universe, and so simple created universes are no more likely than more complex ones.
There is no reason God would make things unnecessarily complex, especially without taking full advantage of what has been created, of the two possibilities, simpler makes more sense.
The complexity/size of the universe may have been intended to show the smallness and fragility of human life, encouraging humility.
There is no need for such a Universe to achieve that effect. Plenty of mundane, earthly experiences encourage humility much more easily than exploring the cosmos.
A huge inhabited universe would do this better, as there would be more life, more civilizations to show just how insignificant the individual was.

Insignificance of the entire human race may be preferred, to encourage humans to seek fulfillment in a larger purpose, rather than individual insignificance which can be remedied by economic or governmental power.
More sentient life in the universe does not necessarily require more human life.
The bigger things are the harder they are for someone to control through personal power in any form.
The universe looks complex to us because we are a part of it, and one can't accurately, and completely model something they are a part of
One doesn't need a complete or fully accurate model of something in order to judge its complexity.

If our brains were so simple that we could understand them, we would be so simple that we could not understand them, because this is an example of something trying to model itself. Any model that we could make would need to necessarily be quite crude, because an accurate one would need to be all encompassing, and anything we want to model that can model itself needs to be able to do other things.
This statement isn't true in all possible worlds. In a universe with different laws, much simpler intelligent systems are conceivably possible.

Suppose a computer has a total of N possible states. Suppose there is something outside of the computer in the universe, so the universe has at least N+1 possible states. With zero overhead, each state of the computer can correspond to a state of the universe, but since the universe has more states than the computer, some states of the universe will map to the same state of the computer, in which case the simulation will not be able to distinguish between them.
This doesn't show that the universe is not complex or that simpler, consciousness-producing universes cannot exist.
A simpler model that allows for sentient beings has not been presented.
A Boltzmann Brain type universe allows for sentient beings and is simpler than the multiverse.
Just because there are simpler "possible" universes than ours does not mean that the universe is all that complicated. The rules guiding this universe are relatively simple.

Multiverse models are not required to be completely random in the universes they generate. They can, in principle, have motivated constraints on the types of universes generated within the multiverse which would lead to universes like ours being among the most probable.

Multiverse theories are unfalsifiable, since it is impossible by definition for a causally disconnected universe to interact with our own. Theism is at least possibly falsifiable, since God would be able to interact with the universe.

Most multiverse models allow for causal interaction between universes. At the very least there is interaction between our universe and the universe within/from which our universe arose. Depending on this process, various marks might be left on our universe to hint at what came before. No such evidence has been observed allowing us to falsify various multiverse models.

The multiverse theory predicts that the vacuum energy is probably nearly as far from zero as possible for a universe capable of supporting sentient life, whereas a single finely-tuned universe ought to have it at exactly zero; this constitutes a testable prediction.
There is no reason to assume that a creator would be compelled to make the vacuum energy zero.

Multiverse theories have low explanatory scope, since they don't explain any data other than the fine-tuning of the universe. In contrast, theism explains the existence of the universe and of objective morality, as well as many miracle claims and subjective experiences.
The multiverse theory can be treated as part of a larger philosophy of naturalism that also aims to explain all things theism attempts to explain. Then they would have the same explanatory scope.

Multiverse theories are ad hoc, since the existence of causally disconnected universes isn't very plausibly supported outside of its use as an answer to fine-tuning. Theism is supported by other arguments, as well as by the subjective experiences of many.
See the Pros for the head claim of this debate (i.e. God exists)

Multiverse theories build on principles of cosmology developed and verified while explaining various phenomena within our universe. Therefore, extending these ideas to explain the phenomena of fine-tuning and the origin of our universe is motivated hypothesis building as opposed to pure ad hoc stipulation.
Max Tegmark's mathematical universe hypothesis gives a philosophical framework for the nature of existence that implies a form of multiverse.
It's not clear that consciousness can be simulated by purely mathematical processes.
Quantum mechanics has shown that consciousness isn't describable by purely physical processes.
The Chinese room argument holds that simulating consciousness within non-conscious systems is impossible.

The Chinese room argument is a hypothetical scenario, and merely purports to show how the illusion of consciousness may not be actual consciousness, not that creating, or even simulating consciousness is impossible
By Occam's Razor (parsimony) there would be no need for the additional entity of conscious experience to explain the behavior of the machine or Room.
There is no explanation for the behavior in the scenario, simple or otherwise.

The Chinese room thought experiment demonstrates an entity that is incapable of performing a task, speaking Chinese, can have components added that allow it to appear to perform this task. It extends this argument to say the same is true of computers that appear conscious. However, this ignores that the thing between the first entity, and the audience, is itself an entity. And this entity as a whole can perform this task, thus could be considered conscious.
This assumes the existence of God is supported by other arguments (see Cons for the head claim of this debate (i.e. God exists) as well as those underneath the Pros for the head claim)
Multiverse theories are very unparsimonious, since they posit a bafflingly large number of entire universes that cannot be observed. Theism only proposes a single extra entity.

This assumes parsimony concerns limiting the number of entities as opposed to the number of types of entities. God would represent a significantly distinct class of entities not present in naturalism. Many people's intuitions may consider this less parsimonious than adding more universes like our own.
Cosmologists propose a beginning for the current timeline of the universe, not for the universe as a whole.

The current timeline of the universe is defined as events which occurred since the rapid expansion. It is not known if the universe as a whole extend beyond this point. The current timeline is the universe as we know it today, whereas the universe as a whole may possibly extend past that point.
The universe's expansion requires a cause. Otherwise it would have stayed in its state.
The "compact universe" before its expansion still needs a cause for its existance.
It is unclear that there is a meaningful distinction between "current timeline of the universe" and "the universe as a whole."

The Big Bang Theory postulates the earliest know periods of our observable universe however "Physicists are undecided whether this means the universe began from a singularity, or that current knowledge is insufficient to describe the universe at that time." As such arguing that our universe began, when prevailing science does not claim it, is unsound.
Even if the age of the universe is finite (which we do not know), that would not suggest or support in any way the existence of a god.
The argument uses misleading language, as 'began to exist' does not mean what one would think it does.
A universe (or temporally ordered series of universes) that did not begin to exist is philosophically incoherent because it implies the concrete existence of an actual infinity

The possibility of an actual infinity leads to absurdities as various thought experiments can illuminate for any sincere inquirer (e.g. Hilbert’s Hotel, Infinite Library, Benardete’s Big Read, various supertasks)

The examples, if they cannot be resolved, only exclude certain kinds of actual infinities and cannot be generalized to the type of infinity that an eternal past is or the types of infinity entailed by an eternal past, if it entails any other infinities at all.

Zeno's paradox has been demonstrated fallacious (and ends up not being paradoxical at all) - as the sum of the infinitesimal quantities add up to a finite quantity disproving it's solution and achieving a solution which is perfectly compatible with our every day experience.
Zeno assumes an infinite number of tasks cannot be completed in a finite amount of time. This assumption is false (supertasks).
Zeno’s paradox shows that there really isn’t an infinite number of spaces between two points.

Thompson's Lamp has a solution: the lamp is on or off randomly (with a probability of 50%) after being on and off at the same time (via being turned on and off infinitely fast - ie. simultaneously). Thus this paradox is one of either lack of information or erasure of information, and can have a logical solution while assuming the existence of infinities.

Galileo's paradox poses no issue with infinities, it just shows that they are unquantifiable (which is perfectly in line with the meaning of infinite). It also shows that some infinities are faster moving/growing than others (ie. someone who runs forever will always be ahead of someone who walks forever), which is compatible with our experience and with the definition of infinity.
The Grand Hotel "paradox" is provably true, therefore not illogical (and therefore only paradoxical in the sense of being counter-intuitive).

A thought experiment is not a stand-alone argument. An informative articulation of the source of the absurdity must occur (e.g. formulate into a deductive argument) instead of simply relying on vague gut reactions to a story
Paradoxical ideas about actual infinities stem from their counter-intuitive nature and not from any actual/physical impossibility.

These thought experiments are often paired with such articulations of the source. For example, one thing illustrated by the Hilbert's Hotel paradox is the following deductive argument: (1) If an actual infinity is possible, then set A being a proper subset of set B does not imply A is smaller than B; (2) A being a proper subset of B does imply A is smaller than B; (3) Therefore an actual infinity is not possible

The Ross–Littlewood paradox has various solutions depending on the exact variant, but it has perfectly consistent solutions (one for each variant or the problem) when we turn to physics. It is therefore not a problem with infinities.

After adding infinite objects  we will have infinite objects. After adding 2 objects and subtracting one over and over for an infinite time, we have infinite objects. After adding n objects, if we add and subtract an equal number of objects we end up with n objects. Thus all conclusions are self consistent and the paradox resides in equivocating different physical actions under the same abstract concept, which leads to the erring assertion that their outcomes should be the same.

An actual infinity is metaphysically absurd because its mathematical validity requires accepting the non-obvious axiom of infinity and rejecting the mundane notion of proper subsets having a smaller cardinality
The concept of all natural numbers (0,1,2,...) requires the axiom of infinity for its definition.

The concept of natural numbers as a collection (e.g. set, category, etc..) does require the axiom of infinity but such a collection is only of interest to pure mathematics. It finds no application in science or applied mathematics, which only needs a finite but arbitrarily large set of natural numbers plus notions like limits for calculus, which do not require the axiom of infinity.
Nature has no reason to care what seems absurd to humans.

A Cambridge property is a property of a substance or entity which is in some sense extrinsic, usually relational.

Bob growing a beard is a real change, because it involves the acquisition of a real property.
But for Bob to become shorter than Tom, merely because Tom has grown and Bob has stayed the same, is a Cambridge change, because it involves the acquisition of a mere Cambridge property.
