A meter stick on the other hand is useful precisely because it idealizes a standard for measurement.
Humans often idealize behaviors, situations and objects and those idealizations don't need to (and perhaps never actually do) correspond to reality.

Morality is not a list of rules, but a standard of behavior. Any standard is something by which another thing is measured, and must idealize the quality which it measures. Therefore, the moral standard must idealize the quality of behavior, which implies a person.

You cannot measure the length of a line using color; rather, the standard used must have length. "24 blue" is meaningless with regard to the length of a line. "24 inches" is meaningful because the standard idealizes the quality of length.
A standard is not subject to being measured in terms of the quality that it idealizes. In other words, it is illogical to say a meter is not a meter. It must be a meter by definiton.

All attempts to generalize morality into uncontroversial and exceptionless broad rules have failed to match perfectly with our moral judgments. As such it seems likely that morality isn't simplifiable or reducible to general axia, and requires situational judgments. Therefore, if morality is objective, it must be contained in an external mind able to make such judgments - and such a mind would be considered God.
Situational judgments are made by the minds of people, thus do not require God.

If morality had to match human moral judgements perfectly, then where humans disagree on ethical dilemmas, it would have to match both sides of the disagreement at once and thus be self-contradictory. Thus, if there is an objective morality, it does not conform to human moral judgements, and thus could be composed of exceptionless broad rules with no need to be contained in a mind.
"It is wrong to torture small children for fun" is an uncontroversial and exceptionless broad rule.
A utility monster could torture small children for fun and be morally justified.

Selection (via survival) favors a kind of morality that indicates as prescriptive certain norms and values: a moral framework which exists independently of any deities and independently of whether survival is right or not outside of said framework.
Selection via survival cannot ground several of our strongly held moral principles.
Selection via survival cannot explain why punching someone in the face for fun, even if the damage isn't severe enough to impact someone's survival, is wrong.

Selection via survival cannot explain why celibacy is more permissible than murdering an infant. Both result in an individual not contributing offspring to the population, which has a negative effect on the reproductive fitness of the population.

Kialo discurssion:    2
 Morality is objective.

In order for morality to be objective, its source must also be objective and unchanging. The universe and all of its contents are contingent and therefore not objective. So it follows that the moral law-giver must be transcendent and necessary.
If morality is objective, it may exist without a source; there is no need to postulate another separate thing which is in turn sourceless, and call that separate thing God.

Morality may not have "objective truth." For example, controversial issues such as abortion and ethical dilemmas such as trolley problems and Singer's drowning child demonstrate that humans greatly disagree on certain moral issues.
Disagreement on an issue does not indicate that the reality of the subject is not objective.

Moral issues are often complex being comprised of multiple differing principles all in tension with one another, therefore disagreement is to be expected as we struggle to come to mature understandings of how objective moral truths apply in specific cases.

The claim that objective moral truths exist and that we can perceive these truths does not require or imply that our perceptions are perfect. Disagreements surrounding moral issues can be attributed to failings in perceptions of objective moral truths.

People in different roles in society have different moral obligations. A doctor is expected to treat all patients equally, where as a police officer is expected to discriminate. A mother is commended for favoring her child while a school teacher would be condemned for showing favoritism upon the same child.
Sometimes there may be more than one correct way to navigate moral dilemmas. For example, there are multiple ways to engineer a bridge which is stable and a similar thing can be true of moral issues.
If moral judgements have objective truth, that truth may stand independently, without need for "justification".
There are ontological implications for the existence of objective moral truth and they are fatal for naturalism because moral truths indicate a metaphysical layer of reality.
The epistemology employed to perceive and prove the existence of moral truths (self-evidence) can, with the same validity and epistemic strength, be applied to God's existence.

Moral truths are perceived differently by people according to their level of consciousness. In lower states of consciousness criminal actions are considered acceptable and in higher states of consciousness upstanding behavior is given primary importance. The same can be true of perceptions of theological truths. Someone needs to have a certain maturity of consciousness in order to perceive God's existence.
While people experience altered states of consciousness, such as dreams, or the effects of meditation or certain drugs, there are not "higher" or "lower" "levels" of consciousness.
The existence of a metaphysical reality and the subsequent death of makes the existence of God plausible.
Naturalism and monotheism are not the only metaphysical views, so if naturalism were false that would not necessarily mean God exists.
Morality can't be transcendent, because different moral standards apply to different historical contexts.
Cultural relativism states that the morality of an action is determined solely by its cultural contexts.
Cultural relativism is supported by moral disagreements between cultures.
Widespread disagreement in morality undermines the idea of "universal morality".
Universal morality isn't required for the moral argument to hold, only that moral statements have truth value and things are objectively right or wrong.
Morality can have objective truth even if no one knows of it.

Disagreement in morality often derives from factual, not moral, error. For instance, witch hunts were once conducted on the erroneous assumption that witches could have negative effects on others and the world.

While this is true, ethical disagreements can be elicited with thought experiments in which the facts of the matter are given and not in dispute, so factual disagreement can only explain some specific cases, and not moral disagreement on the whole.
The contentious issue of abortion demonstrates disagreement in morality.

The fact that people might disagree on a further point does not mean that originally they felt the same inclination towards agreeing with (or disagreeing with) that moral point. It could be (and probably often is) that a person convinces himself/herself of a particular moral point, thereby then finding evidential arguments for their holding of that moral view.

Most general statements on morality are universally agreed upon by healthy societies. For instance, unjust murder is always considered to be wrong, as is thievery. Even if morality on the whole isn't universal, these general statements still require explanation.
Humans all have many similar traits, it is therefore coherent that humans would also share many the same relative morals.

Morality must be something more than shared human opinion. In 18th-19th century America, slavery was widely considered to be moral. If morality is merely "shared relative morals", then in their time and place, slavery was in fact, moral. Yet we rightly consider those persons today to have been morally flawed, even in their own time.

That we consider people in the past who endorsed slavery to have been wrong is itself nothing more than shared human opinion. That our opinions are not overruled by the opinions of long-dead others who we see as moral monsters, is no evidence that our opinions are more than opinions.
Disagreement about a concept "A" is warranted if and only if A actually exists. Therefore moral disagreement supports, rather than undermines, the idea that objective morality exists.

If each individual has a subjective morality, but that morality has rules for what other people should do, then disagreement when those perspectives clash is entirely warranted regardless of whether any such perspective has "objective" value.
That disagreement exists does not mean the disagreement is actually warranted; two people arguing over "A" need only believe that A exists, and they may be wrong.
Scientific disagreement is also everywhere, but it doesn't follow from this that the outside world doesn't follow reasonable rules, only that some people are mistaken about scientific truths.

Scientific claims rely on observable, verifiable evidence. Moralistic claims rely on relativistic interpretation based on cultural references. Science is objective, whereas morality is subjective. 

The outside world, and its rules, are neither all reasonable nor all unreasonable. It's a mixture of both. Filled with both objective scientific truths and a mix of subjective and often conflicting moralities, it follows that people would have trouble reconciling scientific truths and their faith.

Under cultural relativism, the moral framework decided on by a culture is true, and anyone who defies it is morally wrong. However, we agree that certain figures such as Martin Luther King acted morally, even though they defied the moral framework of the culture they lived in. This is known as the reformer's dilemma.

The divide between cultures isn't clear or well-defined - as such, the decision of which cultural moral framework to follow would depend on overarching moral rules. Those rules separating cultures cannot themselves be decided by any culture, and as such, at least some objective moral standards would have to exist.

Different moral standards did not apply to different historical contexts. Even in the historical context of the 1850s where slavery was legal and widely accepted in the U.S., we are just as right in condemning slaveholders then as we are in condemning modern traffickers.

If God is morality, then God can not choose what they do, as they must always do what is moral, and thus lacks libertarian free will, and is merely a force of the universe. As such, God would not be omnipotent, as they could not choose.

Since God under this definition would be just a force, we could manipulate, and control them, as we do other forces, which would ultimately make us more powerful then God. If we can be more powerful then God, God can not be Omnipotent.

We don't manipulate or control other forces. For instance, we can only predict and work around gravity and electromagnetism, not change them - this kind of utilization certainly doesn't imply that we are more powerful than these forces.
We can defy gravity, or harness it for our own ends, gravity in turn can only gravitate. We are thus the stronger.

In order to utilize God in a way similar to electromagnetism He would have to be completely predictable in His actions. Lacking libertarian free will doesn't mean that something is completely predictable.
Basic quantum events are fundamentally unpredictable, but don't have "free will" in any meaningful sense.
Since God is outside the universe and, at least to some extent, unknowable, it would be impossible to predict His actions even if He was unfree.
A force doesn't have to be perfectly understood to be utilized, we were using compasses many years before we discovered electromagnetism.
God in this instance is definite by the rules of an absolute morality, which is by it's nature perfectly predictable if you know the rules.
It is do in no small part to morality that out civilization has grown so expansive, so if God is morality, then we are already using God to our ends.
Not all things that lack libertarian free will are "just a force".
Even if He lacked libertarian free will, God could still think and act (even if those thoughts and actions are determined), making Him a conscious agent and thus greater than a force.
If those thoughts and actions are all predetermined, then God would still be nothing more then an animal, or a machine.

Not all things that lack libertarian free will are forces, some are objects, animals, or machines, but as morality is an ever-present entity that acts upon us, it, and thus, under this definition, God, must be a force.

If God's nature is identical to morality, then God is not compelled by anything, since morality is simply defined as "what God would do." Under this definition, the statement is "God must always do what God would do," which isn't a compulsion, only a tautology.
An inability to contradict His own nature does not count against God's omnipotence.

Free will only implies the freedom for one to act based on one's nature, not the freedom to defy one's nature. If perfect morality is a part of God's nature, it isn't necessary or expected that He be able to defy it.
If we ignore the first sentence, then I agree that it is not valid to expect from one aspect of God's perfection to deny other perfection. That is a contradiction in logic, not in God.

People have the ability to do things they were not instructed to do, or even instructed not to do, and that are against their best interest, not due to a mistake, not even only for a greater good, but simply because they can, an action that would require them to have libertarian free will. When we read the story of Pandora's box, or Eve, and the Apple, we don't blink an eye, we empathise with the characters, because it's not outlandish, it is the natural result of a creature with free will.
The text of Genesis doesn't claim that the tree of knowledge was intended as a test of free will.
The "tree as test" interpretation of the story, along with a similar one of Pandora's box, is somewhat popular.
One example of free will making mistakes, doesn't show that making mistakes is a necessary requirement for free will.
Everyone makes mistakes, so even with only one example, the evidence is in favor of the necessity.
Freedom, the legal interpretation of free will, has long been referred to as the ability to make one's own mistakes.
The legal interpretation of free will is irrelevant.
the legal definition is tied to the actual definition, what one says tells us a lot about what the other says.
Following commands is not free will, one's nature is a form of command, therefore, if one is only capable of following their nature, they do not have free will.
Free will is only contradicted when one is constrained by commands external to oneself. One's nature is internal to oneself, and so following it doesn't contradict free will.
My brain commands my fingers to move to type this sentence. I wouldn't be more free if my fingers didn't follow that command - in fact, I'd be less free, since I wouldn't be able to act upon my will.
If one's finger acted independent of oneself, they would be less free, but their finger would be more free, the part is not the whole, and the whole is not the part.

A computer holds many commands within itself, and acts upon the majority of them without external stimulation of any kind, but a computer does not have free will. As such, even internal commands are not sufficient to define free will.

Freedom to defy one's nature is logically impossible, because an agent's decisions are necessarily the result of its nature. An agent couldn't decide to defy their nature, because that decision would itself be following its nature.
According to Arthur Schopenhauer, "Man can do what he wills but he cannot will what he wills."
People do consciously change their nature, alcoholics work hard to recover from their addiction, and so can racists, it's not easy, but it can be done.
People can consciously change their thoughts and desires, but they cannot change their nature consciously. Their nature is what allows them to make the decision to change their thoughts/desires.

All observed creatures with free will (humans) have dual natures, which at least in part contradict each other, and can not universally be followed in all instances. For example, one's economic self interest, against moral behavior.

The conflict between desire for wealth and desire to behave morally is an example of contradicting desires, not contradicting natures. One's nature is what allows one to choose between conflicting desires.

A person's nature isn't any of their desires, in the same way that a sheet of piano music isn't any of the keys on the piano. Instead, the nature is how someone chooses between their desires - and without it, no such choice could be made.
The same individual in the same situation may very well make different choices, all factors equal.
Different choices being made in the same scenario doesn't demonstrate that a free agent contradicting their own nature is possible.
If beings have a "nature" that proscribes certain actions and limits what they can freely choose, even making such choice logicallyimpossible, this amounts to a refutation of free will.
God under this definition loses not only the ability to defy his nature, but the ability to determine it.
God's nature is determined by necessity. He must be the way He is, otherwise He would not be God, leaving no room for modification.
If God's nature is determined by necessity, an act that does not allow them to be omnipotent, then God, as defined in this discussion, can not exist.
In order to change one's nature, one would have to defy one's nature first. The change would, by definition, oppose the agent's nature.
If changing one's nature is defying it, then libertarian free will exists, as being able to defy one's nature must be possible, as people do change their nature as they grow.
People's nature may change, but this change is not due to a conscious decision to change their nature.

A change must be internal, or external. The change here is clearly not external, so it must be internal. Since the change is internal, the nature changed itself. It has previously been assumed that a nature could not change itself, and that to do so it would have to defy itself. Since the nature would, under these assumptions, defy itself, free will must exist.
To contradict one's nature is an ability. The lack of such an ability is a limit to God's power and therefore 'counts against' His omnipotence.
If whatever God does is arbitrary defined as good, then morality is arbitrary, and no more valid then what any random individual does as the bases of what should be done.

Good is not defined as what God does, it's defined as what's in his nature. This makes the concept of good an objective and unchanging fact about the universe and therefore no more arbitrary than phenomena like gravity and magnetism.
God cannot ground objective moral values.
There is no logical reason why God's commands/nature, not the commands/nature of other beings, ground objective moral values. (infidels.org)
God alone has the omniscience necessary to truly know what is best for his creation, unlike other beings.
Unlike other beings, God created the universe and its inhabitants with a purpose in mind, and this purpose was to do things in accordance with his nature.
There is no logical reason why being created in the image of God means that humans are objectively valuable (infidels.org).
If God is the basis of objective morality, then it follows that God himself is objectively valuable. This means that any attempt to harm anything of God's, including his image, is wrong.
Rationality itself is a sufficient source.
Without values, rationality only deals with what is, whereas morality is concerned with what ought to be/what we ought to do. It isn't possible to derive "ought"s solely from "is"s.
Natural law, is a body of philosophical thought that derives ought (at least partially) from is.

All ethics is concerned partially with what is, using "is"s to supplement "ought"s and create more specific or complex "ought"s. However, no ethical system can successfully reach "ought"s without at least one axiomatic "ought" as its basis.
Secular conceptions of natural law still rely on axiomatic "ought"s - for instance, that one ought not infringe upon another's rights.

Natural law is a system that has done great harm to the world, by hindering the rights of women, trans individuals, and homosexuals, repeatedly come up with false conclusions, like that women should have no autonomy, and homosexuals are evil, and that is based on a false interpretation of reality, that things were created with a purpose instead of evolving to adapt to the world. It is by every measure a failed moral system. As such, it has not derived real 'oughts'.
we have to use rationality to determine what values deserve to be valued.
Economics, as an example, derives what ought to be from what is valuable, and possible.

Economics relies on a presupposition of value (i.e. that property is valuable). The field itself is concerned only with how best to obtain what is already considered to be valuable, but doesn't compel anyone to give personal value to property.
Some people - such as hermits and communists - don't consider property valuable nearly as much as others.
All people consider property valuable, even hermits, and communists. Those groups just treat possession differently.
Economics only requires that each individual actor values something, not necessarily that they want the same things, or value them the same.
This is still a presupposition of value, so economics fails to produce "ought"s with no presupposed "ought"s.
Value to the individual is objective, they have a need, and the thing they want can sait it, so this is an is, not an ought.
Morality was observed before it was studied, those observations are the 'is's upon which we built our systems.
Morality being built upon prior observations of morality is circular - it attempts to ground morality in itself.
It was seen, then it was studied, once we saw it, we moved to figure out why it was, and how it worked, the observations are the starting point of moral studies, but not the bases of it.
Observations of what humans think is moral do not indicate that those humans are correct. The fact that I think it is good to exercise does not prove that it is good to exercise.
If morality was not observable, we would not know that it exists.
That morality exists, and that morality should be followed are two different statements.
Definitionally, morality is the means to determine what one should do. The statement "one should follow morality" is equivalent to "one should do what one should do," which is tautologically true.

morality: a doctrine or system of moral conduct
moral: sanctioned by or operative on one's conscience or ethical judgment
neither of these definitions disallow someone from acting upon another measure of what they should do, like their
self interest, or says that doing one is preferable to the other.
In order for morality to be observed it must first exist. If morality exists, then the moral arguments hold true.
The existence of morality is only one of the assumptions needed for the moral arguments to prove the existence of God.

If morality is based solely upon an observation of what humans think is moral, then moral progress would be impossible, because it would never be possible to be more moral than what is currently thought to be moral.
We started with what we saw of morality, and built upon it, just as we did with science, learning it's in's and outs, and applying them to the world around us.
The classical definition of God historically includes Divine Simplicity.
Divine Simplicity is rejected by general Theism's philosophical proponents.

Dr. William Lane Craig (renowned theologian and philosopher on religion) rejects Divine Simplicity: "...[T]he doctrine of divine simplicity is one that has no biblical support at all and, in my opinion, has no good philosophical arguments in its favor. Moreover, it faces very formidable objections." See his full response.
Divine Simplicity is a technical concession that God cannot exist as defined under Classical Theism.
Divine Simplicity requires that God is inexpressible. In other words, any definition given (e.g. that of Classical Theism) must be insufficient to describe God.
The theory of Divine Simplicity is an example of moving the goalposts.

Divine Simplicity differentiates "good" as it pertains to God from "good" as is (or can be) defined and understood by humans. See Divine Simplicity: "...God's attributes can only be spoken of by analogy."
The Euthyphro dilemma is not avoided by equivocating "God" with "Good" (i.e. morality).

Supposing "God" and "Good" are synonyms and also that there remain actions which are morally right or morally wrong for a person to do, the provision of synonyms only tells us about the qualities of God, but has yet to provide any insight whatsoever into distinguishing actions which are morally right from those that are morally wrong. Note the ironic resemblance of this problem to that in the Euthyphro itself (Euthyphro's third definition of "piety").

Supposing "God" and "Good" were synonyms, it would be impossible for a person to be (or do) Good in this sense without that person necessarily also being God. In other words, there would be no function in discussing "the moral capacity of human beings" since Good is reserved by (and indistinguishable from) God.

Embodiment of a characteristic is distinct from being the cause of it. Regardless of whether or not God embodies what is right, this concept of what is right can and does exist independently of God. Thus, there is no distinct proof for the existence of God based on the existence of morality. Ultimately, then moral arguments for God still fail.
It is impossible to know a priori whether an omnipotent and omnibenevolent God could co-exist with evil.

To rule out a prior the compatibility of divine omnipotence, divine omnibenevolence, and real evil, one would need to prove that there are in principle no justifiable reasons for God to permit evil to exist. To know this would require knowing all possible outcomes of evil in the world, knowledge which no human has or can have.
It's impossible to say with any acceptable certainty that the state of the world isn't justified from God's perspective.

Any given "evil" circumstance has results that can continue to affect other circumstances long after, and far away from, the original circumstance. Chaos theory shows that accurately predicting, and therefore judging the weight of, these consequences is far beyond the scope of human intelligence.
These consequences are not beyond the scope of God's intelligence. And a kind explanation from God is not beyond the scope of human intelligence.

If God is omnipotent then God can do anything. If God can do anything, then good does not have to come from evil unless God decides that it must be the case. If God is omnibenevolent, God would not allow evil. Therefore, God would not require evil for good.
It may not be possible, even in principle, to have a physical reality with good and without evil.
There is no reason that an all powerful god would have to utilize chaotic systems to realize a certain outcome.
We cannot know what God is thinking.
We can if He choose to share.

Moral standards should be acceptable, for making a sensible claim. If God bothered to give us moral standards, then He should have also told us why He violates them. Jesus taught by example and by explanation. God should explain the contradiction, why is He not the way He was supposed to be. Suspicious silence about Himself, while being vocal about human moral  issues raise a reasonable doubt, that there is no any justification at all.

There is a way and it is called a free will. Free will is not a valid argument against the classical problem of theodicy, since nobody will wish an evil to himself. But in dharmic religions there is a concept of karma, which means that reactions to our actions are delayed. The purpose is to educate us about what is good and evil, by a personal experience of what is favorable and what is not. Karma explains why is there evil alongside with loving God.
If the purpose of suffering is to educate us then an omnipotent God could have just created us with that education in the first place, thereby avoiding the need for anyone to suffer.
Free will does not justify the ability to execute the will to cause harm, just like free will does not grant the ability to fly (unaided) to those who want to fly.
There are many forms of suffering that cannot be attributed to karma. Terrible things happen to even the most innocent and good people.

Dharmic religions also have the concept of "Brahman"... the ultimate reality in the universe. According to Chandogya Upanishad 3.14.1, "This whole universe is Brahman. In tranquility, let one worship It, as Tajjalan (that from which he came forth, as that into which he will be dissolved, as that in which he breathes)."

If all is Brahman, evil and good are essentially identical. Karma cannot explain how to differentiate between two identical things.

According to the doctrine of Karma, all evil that happens to us is brought upon us by our own past evils.

This cannot describe how the first evil was done to us, before we had performed an evil deed. It requires an infinite regress of past lives, or a non-karmic evil to start the chain of karma, which denies the premise that all evil is the result of past evil.
There is no reason they are mutually exclusive.

If a set of claims is consistent, then any subset of that set is also consistent. The following set of claims is consistent: (1) God exists, (2) God has a good reason for allowing evil, (3) Evil exists. Therefore the set comprising (1) and (3) is consistent and there is no incompatibility here.

This "consistency strategy" would fail only if (2) were logically impossible. However, that doesn't seem to be the case. For example, even if the free will defence doesn't provide God's *actual* reasons for allowing evil, it does provide a *possible* reason, and that is all the consistency strategy requires to show there is no logical contradiction between (1) and (3).
A good and able God would both want and be able to stop evil.
We don't always do everything that we want to do and are able to do. Sometimes doing those things is incompatible with other things we want.
The Inductive Problem of Evil makes it likely that God does not exist.

The Epicurean Paradox: If God is willing to prevent evil, but is not able to then he is not omnipotent.
If he is able, but not willing  then he is malevolent.
If he is both able and willing then whence cometh evil.
If he is neither able nor willing then why call him God? Epicurus
God may be able and willing to stop evil, and may in fact be doing so in His own time and in His own way for reasons of His own.

If someone whose pronouns don't have capital letters on them decides to stop evil "in his own time" and "in his own way" while people are dying who could be saved by a prompt and direct intervention that he would be capable of, that would not be considered good.
The Epicurean paradox is concerned with the prevention (and not the termination) of evil.
According to the standard christian doctrine of hell, God does not even terminate evil, ever.
According to scripture God is able and willing, but refrains from doing so, because that would mean God would have to eradicate all mankind. Gid allows evil to exist so we can exist and be saved.
Some goods may only be actualizable by allowing the possibility of evil.
Love, to truly exist, must be given freely. It cannot be forced from someone. To permit love to exist, one must allow for it to be withheld.

Evil is anthropocentrically ill-defined and hugely subjective; things that we think are natural Evils to us (like diseases, natural disasters and death itself) serves themselves as Good to the world, abiding by the scientific laws that govern them.

God should not change the science of the world specifically for us; if the whole of Creation is good (Genesis 1:31) then God doesn't owe his sustenance to us, but equally to everything in His Creation, all of which are products of His designed Science.

We can interrogate the concept of an omnibenevolent God without granting the divine command theory of morality, and hence we can discard the idea that "the whole of creation is good" and recognise that e.g. the smallpox virus was not good and did not deserve to exist.
The Epicurean argument does not assume that some things are objectively evil. A subjective concept of evil is enough to make the argument work.
The epicurean paradox has a hidden assumption that God can create a world where people have a free will that is without evil. Free Will.
It is not true that an omnipotent, omnibenevolent God must always and at all times remove all evil.
The idea that god follows utilitarian theory is let down by babies and infants dying of medical conditions, such as cancer, where there is no societal benefit.

If the Christian God exists, Heaven exists. Therefore, babies and infants dying would then go to heaven, which is a great benefit for them. One must perceive all sides of a given situation before pronouncing judgement.
Impassibility in the classical definition of God takes care of the problem of evil.

If we add to our picture of a powerful being watching people suffer and die in countless ways when He could easily step in to help, the fact that that being is also completely apathetic about the whole affair, that does not make that being seem less immoral.

If God is obliged to maximize the total surplus of goodness over bad, then God might be obliged to realize every possible world or state in which there is more good than bad, which includes worlds with a considerable amount of evil.

Being omnibenevolent (or all-good) is not equivalent to 'being obliged to maximize the total surplus of goodness over bad'. 
The problem of evil is an argument against an all-good god.
God could make duplicates of the best world or state without causing as much suffering.
Even if worlds were duplicated, it does not maximize goodness unless all net-positive worlds are realized.
If God were to prevent Evil, this would disrupt the laws of cause and effect, and cause greater unimaginable harms.
The claim that preventing evil would disrupt cause and effect is unsubstantiated.
This doesn't satisfactorily challenge the problem of evil. If god chooses not to prevent all evil, then he is not all good or not all powerful, no matter his reasoning.
If evil were prevented, nothing could be harmful (by definition).

Moral realism is required for the "problem of evil" to exist, but is also incompatible with atheism. Therefore, the problem of evil is self-defeating and can be argued to actually provide evidence of God's existence.

The problem of evil highlights a contradiction in a theistic and moral realist worldview; one need not actually believe evil is objectively real to posit it, only that certain things would be objectively evil if there was such a thing.

The problem of evil can be phrased as follows: if God exists, moral realism is true. If moral realism is true, genuine evil exists. If genuine evil exists, then God doesn't exist. Thus, if God exists, God doesn't exist. It follows that God doesn't exist.

Atheism and moral realism are compatible therefore the "problem of evil" still persists. Moral realism can be observed in nature through the intuition that some actions are intrinsically and universally wrong, without appealing to God.

The description of the problem of evil leaves out all self-determining life besides God. If humans are created in God's image, that includes self determination and free will. For God to 'do away with all sin' requires limits to be placed on self determination, essentially changing life from 'created in God's image' to 'automatons obeying the will of God'.

"Self-determination" and free will are illusions. All human behaviour emerges, ultimately out of things that were not "determined" or chosen by the human themselves. 

Genetics, upbringing, brain chemistry, literally the entire universe, is not chosen, they are determined by something preceding the "self" on every single occasion. 

This, doesn't change by the way with a "soul", you also don't choose your soul.
The world in which all people freely choose to avoid sin is a possible world, hence a world God could have created. That God didn't create it militates against the existence of God.

This condition is already set by classical theism's definition of God. An omniscient, omnipotent being must necessarily be the only morally responsible agent in existence. The freedom of other beings to exist or do anything at all is contingent upon the approval (or ignorance) of the one who can make and unmake at will.

This argument is self-defeating. If an inability to sin places limits on free will, then God has no free will. Hence he should be able to create humans without it too. If instead an inability to sin does not limit free will, then God should be able to create humans with free will and without sin.
This ignores 'natural evil' where natural disasters etc cause huge amounts of suffering.
Then it is to have created us in his image, even to the point of allowing us our own self determination, that is the problem, for doing so enabled all the suffering there is in the world.

There is a distinction between a perfect agent and a perfect automaton. It is supposed that in heaven, humans will all maintain their free will while simultaneously being free of evil. God could have created humanity like that in the first place. In other words, rather than creating humans that can't sin, God could have created humans that won't sin.
The concept of evil only works if God does exist to define right and wrong. Without that, it's only an opinion.
Evil is a problem for atheism as well, because it is not clear what an atheist's moral basis for calling something evil is in a purely physical world.

Another problem related to this is how humans are surprised by pain or feel it doesn't fit, in an age and world were pain is a common certainty: even some young children are only a bit upset to see animals torn apart by other animals, but are annoyed at minor injustice like littering. We would not expect this from a car: we know it fails in good time. But we often apply perfect standards to moral issues. To me this indicates a desire not explained by natural selection without a perfect guide.

If anybody expects others to act perfectly moral at times, this belief will either be quickly corrected by experience, excepting others as who they are because they either can't afford not to, or because they morally realize they can't do anything about it, or they will become a monster, seeing corruption everywhere but in themselves, and generally act like Judge Claude Frodo from the Hunchback of Notre damn, because even major moral failing are everywhere.
Being surprised by pain is a matter of not being used to it.
People have more empathy for people, because we are more used to people's expressions and also because understanding other people is evolutionarily advantageous.
Understanding other people's pain and identifying (even feeling) that pain drives us to help members of our populations, directly increasing the chances of survival.
A car doesn't have feelings like me. I do have feelings and I do feel pain, which can be fully explained by evolution.
The fact that people presuppose evil exists in the acceptance of using it to refute a particular god suggests that they presuppose an objective moral arbitration, which requires a god.
Kant's moral dignity, social contract, utilitarianism, and virtue ethics; these are just some moral theories that we have come up with that don't require a god.
Kant's moral theory explicitly necessitates practical belief in god.
You can accept most of Kant's theory without agreeing that it necessitates a belief in god.

The mere existence of theories about morality does not imply their correctness and applicability to the real world. Although these views might govern the morality of a possible world, they do not account for morality in the real one.
Moral theories do not make a claim to the authority of their ideas of morality. They merely suggest possible explanations to behavior that is already observable and operative in the world.
At least some of our morals are rooted in some goal, or valuable concept of value.

Opposition to a subjective goal is not an example of objective evil. The existence of activity which opposes some person's subjective goals would in no way be considered evidence for the non-existence of a classical theistic god.
There is no evidence to support the assumption that all forms of morality that don't really on God are subjective.
The existence of morality doesn't imply an objective or absolute morality. Subjective morality is still morality.
Evil is defined as that which goes against humanity by humanists who do not necessarily believe in a god.

Humanists do not have the moral authority to make such a distinction.
If morality is defined by man himself, then man himself is free to rewrite the rules of morality as he pleases, whether he cares for social contracts, utilitarianism, or any other social theory or not.
Humanism is not defined by man himself. It is defined by a rational exploration of what hurts and helps humanity. It exists independent of any given mind.

Those who claim to be acting morally without reason do so without authority, but Utilitarianism is based on reason, social contract is based on reason, Kant's work is based on reason, these systems, and many more draw there authority form the reason, and logic on which they were built.
The existence of evil does not require a moral law beyond man, simply morals.
Even devoid of some system, someone can believe things right, or wrong, which in turn would mean there are good, and evil.
A Universal position held by all men, (such as "murder is wrong"), suggests a Universal Mind.
Atheism does not have a problem in defining evil. Empathy - which enables us to determine how we would feel about the experience - can be used to evaluate actions as good and bad.
In addition to atheists, many religions also derive a sense of morality from the same basic impulse - empathy - which is why these religions are similar to each other.

Empathy may be useful to discover the moral state of an action, but it does not provide an ontological basis for evil. It may explain what is evil, but it seems inadequate to explain why an action is evil.

Evil can be defined in terms of threats and degradation of human wellbeing. In the problem of evil. If you're enduring something avoidable and unpleasant, that is evil. 

Compare this to pain. Some people enjoy pain. So it's not suffering. It's actually thrilling or stimulating. Such people might not enjoy ice-cream. Thus being made eat some would be a low degree of suffering. It an objective description of subjective experience.

God doesn't define evil or suffering, our experience does.

Indeed, it might just be an "opinion." Many atheists do not accept an objective moral standard. However, classical theists generally subscribe to such a standard, and this can still be used against them in an argument by contradiction.
Good and evil don't actually exist beyond the conceptual, therefore God can still exist in a post-moral view.
That suffering exists is not part of the definition of God, and thus it cannot be applied to whether the definition is internally consistent.
Providing that suffering is bad, we could conclude, that allowing for suffering God created world which is not perfect; and while he is, he should have done a perfect one.
The Christian God created homosexuality, and yet simultaneously calls for its lethal punishment.
There is no evidence that homosexuality, which some consider a sin, represents an expression of free will.
It is theoretically possible that homosexuality arose via evolution-linked changes to genetic structure, which could be considered a deviation from God.

This still presents a contradiction, as only God would be able to create evolution, or the means of its existence. Either God is not in charge of God's plan, or God is still on the hook for creating people in a way they condemn.
Verses condemning homosexuality are misinterpreted and do not actually call for discrimination.

Leviticus 20:13
13 If a man also lie with mankind, as he lieth with a woman, both of them have committed an abomination: they shall surely be put to death; their blood shall be upon them.

Not much to misinterpret there.
God may have created the universe but the Bible indicates that people later might have deviated from God's vision through free will.

Initially, according to the Bible, there was no sin or death in God's creation. When Satan fell (fuller discussion) he tempted Eve to trespass the law of God by eating the fruit from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil. Eve offered this fruit to her husband Adam and he knowingly committed sin. Therefore, sin entered the world and death by sin. God gave man a free will and man brought evil into the world by improperly using that free will.
In Matthew 9:11-12 Jesus implies within his cultural context that some people are born homosexual.
This could be due to evil coming into world after it's creation.

Nothing in the Bible suggests that the physical nature of humans have been modified from the original design by God. Hence the biological nature of homosexuality, which is backed by a huge scientific consensus, is the will of God.Diversity in human sexuality (2015 meta-study by the Academy of Science of South Africa)
The alleged inconsistency depends on an unproven assumption: that a perfect God could not have any good reason to allow sin for a while.
God allowing sin for a short time is valuable because it means that people in Heaven will be able to appreciate God more, knowing what he freed them from.

Similar to the video game false analogy to life, sins being as gameplay obstacles that makes the game enjoyable. The use of obstacles in the game does not make the game developper perfect or imperfect.

Omnipotence is inherently contradictory. Either an all-powerful being cannot create a stone so heavy that the being cannot lift it, or if such a stone is created it is an object the being isn't powerful enough to lift. In either case the being's power is limited.
Black holes are examples of objects that are impossible to lift.
This argument can be resolved by noting that God has not created this stone he supposedly could not lift.

That God has not created such a stone is also consistent with God not existing, which would be perfectly consistent with the "stone so heavy..." argument against the possibility of an omnipotent being, so this objection does nothing.

But in this particular branch of the discussion, the atheist is arguing for the non-existence of God from the paradox of omnipotence. This is an attempted resolution of that paradox not, in this branch, an argument for the existence of God.

The answer to your conundrum is that there is a way for him to do anything, the contradictions exist because we as finite beings cannot grasp the complexities and magnitude of any reality outside of our space-and-time existence.
The Stone Paradox is ineffective against a Leibniz-Ross formulation of omnipotence. Omnipotence defined as "the ability to do anything" is not accepted by all Christian theologians.
This argument could be resolved by noting that a rock could be in a position where it can not be lifted, like in orbit.
Time and space are relative, so despite the fact that it was in orbit, it could be "lifted" from a relative position.
God cannot be all powerful because he can't prove his own nonexistence.
If God was all-powerful and therefore could prove his own nonexistence, and his proof would be correct and realistic, he would not exist. This is a contradiction.

It is not necessary for the proof that God actually performs any illogical actions. If God is able to perform illogical actions, then these must be consistent. Even if God never actually does such actions. By Compactness theorem, If they are consistent with the universe then assuming their occurrence cannot cause contradiction.

Clearly the abilities of an all-powerful being would be limited, if he cannot do such illogical action. The definition of "all-powerful" would reject such limitation by definition, at least in their most strong form. Therefore all-powerful entities that can perform all, even absurd, kinds of illogical actions cannot exist. Hence, a God that is in such sense all-powerful does not exist.
It has not been shown that an all-powerful being can do illogical tasks, such as proving their own non-existence.
By definition of all-powerful, a being is not all-powerful, if there exists tasks which the being is unable to perform.
There is no singular prescriptive definition of "all-powerful" from which to argue "by definition".

There is no requirement for 'singular' for the definition of all-powerful. Many different definitions of all-powerful all satisfy the principle that to be all-powerful, an entity must be able to perform any actions.
Because logically incoherent tasks are logically incoherent, they do not exist.
Even if an all-powerful being can do illogical tasks, it does not follow that He would do illogical tasks.
The God of classical theism is not simply an all-powerful being, but He is also the source of morality and cannot lie.
It has not been shown that an omnibenevolent being could lie by proving their non-existence when they actually exist.
The claim is about whether all-powerful entities can do certain contradictory actions. The claim is not about omnibenevolence, which is unrelated.

Only omnipotence of God is needed to prove the contradiction. Omnibenevolence cannot avoid this problem because every notion of God that assumes God is omnipotent would be subject to same proof by contradiction.

The claim is about the God of classical theism, who is omni-benevolent and cannot lie. If the grandparent claim imagines that God can lie, then it fails because it addresses a straw man god, not the God of classical theism.

The argument begs the question by assuming the conclusion. "If God... could prove his own nonexistence, and his proof [is] correct... he would not exist."

Of course if he correctly proves that he does not exist, he would not exist!

No the claim does not assume its conclusion. Just because certain proofs exist doesn't mean the reality agrees with the proof. Nor does it mean the proof is correct. But due to that, each step of the proof must be explicitly stated and justified.
That the proof is correct is a given in the grandparent claim.
Actually that part had to be explicitly assumed, otherwise the claim would not be sufficiently justified. But this is not in any way circular.

Given that God's omnipotence permits him to do logically incoherent things like "correctly prove his own non-existence", existing despite having correctly proven his own non-existence is also within his power.
Existing despite having correctly proven his own non-existence would be contradictory according to "principle of explosion" and "Modus ponens".
God could decide to invalidate the principle of explosion and modus ponens if he chose to (although he would never do this because he wants a reasonable universe).
An all-good God would not lie, and therefore would never attempt to prove his own nonexistence.
All powerful God might be able to prove false statements. This is contradictory. By principle of explosion, this would allow him to prove any statements.

"His Omnipotence means power to do all that is [possible], not to do the [impossible].... meaningless combinations of words do not suddenly acquire meaning simply because we prefix to them the two other words 'God can.'... It is no more possible for God than for the weakest of his creatures to carry out both of two mutually exclusive alternatives; not because his power meets an obstacle, but because nonsense remains nonsense even when we talk it about God." -- C.S. Lewis, The Problem of Pain
Omniscience, omnipotence and omnibenevolence are mutually exclusive.
An omnipotent being would be able to create something "unknowable", even if just a 'secret'. This contradicts omniscience.

There is no contradiction here. You are just missing the next logical step. If God can create something unknown, he can also expand him self to know it. It's like the question if God is all powerful can he create something so heavy that he himself cannot lift it. Again the answer is yes he can, but then in the next moment he can expand his strength to be able to lift it.
The above claim is a logical fallacy. Similar fallacies would include an omnipotent being creating a situation where he had no power, or an omniscient being knowing what he does not know.

An omnipotent being would be able to rewrite the way logic works in the universe to eliminate any contradiction with omniscience. But that's not necessary unless God has a reason to create something unknowable.
Theodicy problem can only be solved by ignoring one of the three "omni"

Reincarnation solves the problem of evil as people could be suffering reactions to actitivities they perfmormed in previous life times. To solve the problem of evil this reactions would need to be for the purpose of correcting the mentality and conciousness of the person.

For example most bad mentalities some how or other cause others to suffer. Suffering is a good teacher of compassion as we can understand from the common line "I don't want anyone else to suffer the way I did". Therfore suffering can be a kind of cosmic sensitivity training.

The problem of evil can also be compared to children whose loving parents are strict and sometimes enforce discipline. Such children often feel wronged by their parents. When they mature and grow up they can see that their parents were in fact doing what was best for them but they were unable to see it at the time.
This is not true. The assumption of this claim this that the way the world operates now is faulty as it permits evil. It's logically possible that by not allowing evil a greater evil would be done.
God's omnibenevolence can be taken for granted.
God has unlimited knowledge to determine his own goodness eternally, and he has unlimited power to become absolutely good eternally, therefore God is absolutely good.
The human concept of "good" does not apply to God.

God is not subject to any external standard of morality. As the ultimate metaphysical reality and the creator of all things created, His character and behavior is the very standard of morality by which all actions by moral agents are judged to be good or evil. 

Therefore, God is not technically "good", as that phrasing implies that He conforms to an external standard of goodness. Rather, He is Goodness Personified.
The human concept of "good" is conditioned by our limited knowledge of, and limited power over our environment, therefore fallacious when applied to the absolute.

Yet God passed his word/law onto his people, and by following that law/those words he deems them "good" enough to achieve eternal salvation. God, in the hypothetical of him existing, created us and our understanding of "good".
A necessary being cannot "become". God, as a necessary being, is fully actualized, has no potentiality, and cannot change.
God decides what is good, therefore God's goodness is uncontestable.
God does not decide what is good. This is one horn of the Euthyphro dilemma, and would make good and evil arbitrary.

Everything is arbitrary to the ultimate God. Primary principles of omniscience, omnipotence and omnipresence ensure that. However, God doesn't change (immutability), and this results in the definition of an absolute point of moral reference.

Morality being arbitrary to God, even in principle, regardless of whether he chooses to make arbitrary changes, render morality arbitrary. If some "objective morality" truly exists, it must be beyond the possibility of such changes.
His creation subjects great suffering onto other aspects of his creation. Sometimes it's their sole means of survival.

Fiction writers are not considered evil for creating misery for their fictional characters to deliver experiences to the existent readers. Therefore, God would also not be evil for creating misery for his existent creatures to deliver experiences to his own transcendent perception.
God's (if he existed) creations aren't fictional, they/we actually exist.
God's omnibenevolence can be exaggerated.
A maximally-great being would be the greatest possible good; therefore, it is impossible to conceive of any greater good. This allows no possibility of exaggeration.
It is not contradictory to be all powerful, all knowing, and perfectly good. One is about ability to act, one is about ability to know, and one is about moral evaluation of actions or character.

Having abilities to act does not restrict knowledge or constitute moral flaws, having abilities to know does not restrict abilities to act or constitute moral flaws, and while moral goodness may lead one to not act some way, it does not make one unable to act in any way or know anything. No contradiction

This inadvertently minimises the claim by leaving out the omni aspect.
'Having abilities to act' is an imperfect claim that falls short of omnipotence.
Omnipotence restricts knowledge and restricts moral perfection.
Being able to perform anything means one cannot know what they are incapable of performing (reduction in knowledge), it also means they are less morally perfect than a being incapable of evil (reduction in moral perfection).
The interaction between the three generates contradiction.

It is coherent and consistent to be perfectly good. It means, at least, that all actions performed by the perfectly good thing are morally permissible. All these concepts are clear and coherent, and being so for every action is not any more incoherent than doing good in some single action.
To presume perfect good is to presume a complete picture of morality is known, which it is not, and this is not a problem that can be skirted by the bald assertion of perfection.

A question to highlight the competing tensions within omnipotence.
Is god perfectly just or perfectly merciful?
Being just means individuals get what they deserve.
Being merciful means leniency is shown.
Any increase in justice decreases mercy, and the converse.
It cannot logically be both.

Any moral reasoning comes from a compilation of traditions. As the word, from latin <<mores>> means "A set of norms or customs derived from generally accepted practices rather than written laws" An omniscient, eternal entity can have no morality, nor set of customs compiled through practice.
This definition of morals does not however apply in the case that God exists. According to Christianity, objective morality is defined by God, not people or "generally accepted practices".

The contradiction comes from the interaction between two or more omni characteristics. If you have perfect ability to act a realm of knowledge is restricted (knowledge about your limitations to act), also your moral character is reduced (you are less morally perfect than something incapable of evil). This contradiction can be expressed from the perspective of any omni claim.
Add another omni such as omni-present same contradictions. One omni, logically consistent. Two or more, inconsistent.
A being with omnipotence would not be limited by logic. It would be capable of things that are logically contradictory.

Making moral judgements or evaluations about God based on human understanding would be irrelevant since God would be the only instance that would have full knowledge and control over objective moral code. Also it would be quite likely that moral guidelines that apply to humans would not be intended to apply to God.
A being that is both omniscient and omnipotent would not be lacking knowledge about their limits, but rather would have a perfect knowledge that they have no limits.

Assuming morality of "good" and "evil" behaviors exists, an entity possessing complete knowledge must be be immoral, not just moral-good as knowledge of experience of only good would be incomplete knowledge.
This presents a misunderstanding of omniscience. Omniscience is typically defined as "knowing every true fact". This does not require experiential knowledge of immorality.

There is no direct logical contradiction here. A square circle is an incoherent statement because the words contradict one another. The words, all good, all powerful and all knowing do not contradict one another.
Theodicy makes omniscience, omnipotence and omnibenevolence mutually exclusive

Any combination of two of the "omni" words are logically consistent, even according to Theodocy therefore none of them are "mutually exclusive." However, adding the third "omni" to the mix does create a logical paradox.

Theodicy is actually a different subject. The claim made above was that the three qualities contradict one another. Theodicy or the problem of evil of addresses the claim that the 3 qualities are incompatible with the world we observe. Mutually exclusive and not commensurate with the world we live in are 2 very different claims, therefore it remains that the 3 qualities are not mutually exclusive.
Any two of these "omni" words will contradict the remaining one.

Because we have no full concept and no experience of these terms, perhaps they could actually be contingent on each other. 'Knowing all' may require 'all-power', and 'omnibenevolence' could be decided upon by the entity that fits this description.
A better understanding of God's omnipotent nature is that: God can do anything that can be done, and that anything that can be done cannot be limited to my understanding of it.
Anything that God can't do isn't problematic as the only things that God cannot do are acts contrary to his nature.
Omnipotence is a matter of having the power to do anything, whether or not one chooses to use that power. God's desire to do an act is irrelevant when considering his ability to do an act.

If you claim that omnipotence is the ability to do anything within one's nature, any human could claim to be omnipotent. Can't lift a rock? No problem. It simply wasn't within the nature of the person to be that strong. Of course, one could argue that every being, including the classical gods, are omnipotent, but that rather defeats the purpose.
This is not a contradiction in the definition of God, rather in (some of) the theological systems devised to support certain religions. God is not the same as religion.
Examples of things that God cannot do are logically nonsensical and meaningless (e.g. make a square circle).
The definition of omnipotence doesn't have to include the ability to do things that are logically incoherent in and of themselves.
If a square circle is illogical and meaningless, then so is God. as his very nature (outside space & time) is also logically nonsensical and meaningless.
This is a non-sequitur. Square circles are impossible because the two terms are mutually exclusive.  The claim that God exists outside of space and time has no inherent contradiction.
Many things exist outside of space and time - numbers, for example, or pieces of music, stories, abstract properties.

The definition of God as absolutely good is contradictory because 'goodness' is relative to one's moral views and there cannot exist a person or character that would seem good to every sentient being.
Any interpretation of a God's actions would have to be made by humans, who are fallible. No person would be truly privy to the mind of God.

Human interpretation is, however, the filter through which we perceive everything. To dismiss such human ability is to dismiss - among everything else - the very possibility of knowing whether God exists and also whether God does not exist.
The concept of relative morality is incoherent.
Relative morality cannot explain why, in the absence of an objective morality, one would even have a moral sense to begin with.
It is generally understood that taste is subjective, and yet "relative taste" cannot explain why humans have a sense of taste to begin with; this does not make "relative taste" incoherent.
Empathy for others can explain having a moral sense - even in the absence of an objective morality.
Relative morality cannot explain why any person would ever consider something that they did to be immoral or wrong.
If one's subjective moral opinion is the ultimate arbiter of morality, then when a person believes they have done something "wrong" or "immoral", they have only violated their own internal standard.

When a consistent moral relativist believes they have done something immoral, they can only mean that they have violated their own internal code. This raises the question of why they would ever believe any action (especially their own action) to be immoral to begin with. The value of a moral code that can only apply to oneself is questionable in the extreme. It is of little value to believe that oneself should behave in a given manner, while not holding others to any standard at all.

One needs no more reason to find one's own actions immoral than to dislike the taste of something one eats. In both cases, one might hypothetically be better off if one could simply choose to have a different preference, and not feel guilty/disgusted, but neither morality nor taste work that way.
Given subjective, relative morality, one's moral standard cannot be applied to anyone other than oneself. To do so would be to assert that said morality is objective and universal.

Humans make subjective judgements about things and people outside of themselves all the time, everywhere. Morality being subjective does not mean one cannot make judgments applying one's morality to other people.

If morality is relative, then each person gets to decide what is moral. However, this renders each of us incapable of saying what is moral or immoral for someone else. Such a morality is incapable of informing us of how we should treat others--yet, how to correctly interpersonal relationships is a huge part of our moral framework.

Subjective morality does not prevent us from saying what is moral or immoral for someone else, it just makes that a subjective judgement rather than a judgement of what we subjectively believe to be objectively morally correct.
Maybe if the definition was rephrased – god being the absolute good, not being absolutely good – one would not run into a relativistic aporia.
Seeming good and being good are two different things. I personally feel most vegetables taste awful, though I know for a fact they're good for me.
Goodness, as described with regards to the nature of God, is not subject to what some other agent thinks is morally good.

The good suggested by classical theism is the creator of the universe, and as such, would be an objective arbiter of morality unlike entities within the created universe which would only have a subjective view.
There is no reason why creating the universe would make one an "objective" arbiter of morality rather than just another subjective moral viewpoint, albeit one with tremendous power.
What "seems good to every sentient being" is not the same as "absolutely good".

This is the precise reason why absolutely good doesn't exist. A calamity for humans is very good for the animals that they would consume. Also, a destroyer of the solar system could spurn the creation of another with other life forms. For them, the destroyer is a good thing.
If you claim that the only "good" that matters is the "good" of humans (for example), absolute good could exist in that sense.

There can be an objective reason to say that the "good" of humanity is the ultimate good if we consider that humans are the only known creatures capable of reason. Since reason is the only way for the universe to know itself (as discussed by Carl Sagan), the fact that only humans possess it can justify a special status among living beings.

For a sentient being to recognize that some things are "good" and some are "evil" implies a recognition of a moral standard by which to distinguish between the two. Only God's nature is sufficient to be that standard.
Morals are, to at least some extent, evolutionary. As such, no standard is required.
God would be complete, therefore not evolutionary. The whole spectrum of possible evolutions of morals would be contained in God.

One of the ways in which the classical definition is incoherent is that it attempts to define God in a non-spiritual manner, as nothing more than an all powerful being, bearing no relationship to the spiritual aspect of God that is consistent in all common conception of God.

The concept of God is generally predicated on belief that following arbitrary tenets can ingratiate you to the being and it would then create and/or improve your afterlife. Without that supernatural promise you have a self-help group instead of a religion and the banal instead of the divine.

God cannot be all-powerful and completely good, since bad things exist (suffering, pain, war, famine). Either God is completely good and not all-powerful or all-powerful and neutral/not completely good. In which case, the classical God definition does not apply and thus God does not exist.

Since God is the defined as highest good, He would not allow any evil to exist in His works, unless His omnipotence and goodness were such as to bring good even out of evil. Therefore, incidental claims of evil on behalf of God represent an incomplete analysis, and therefore do not prove God is not good.
Accusing God of being evil because of an evil act is akin to accusing a bear of committing murder when killing a fish because God, like bears, is not a moral agent.

We do not think of bears as murderers because we think that they lack free will to decide what action to take, and they lack the comprehension of the meaning and consequenses of their actions. If god should be considered the same as bears, that would mean he doesn't have free will, or he doesn't understand his actions, which would make him either not omnipotent or not omniscient (or both).

If God is omnipotent (all-powerful) and omniscient (all-knowing), then God could have created a reality in which pain, suffering and evil were not possible. Therefore, God is responsible for the existence of all pain, suffering and evil.
Isaiah 45:7 in the King James Version reads, “I form the light, and create darkness: I make peace, and create evil: I the Lord do all these things.” This makes God a moral agent of both yin and yang.

Even if God were in some sense the source of good and evil, whether by creating and sustaining the agents who participate in moral law or by shaping the circumstances under which good and evil acts are perpetrated, this still does not entail that God is a moral agent.
The Bible clearly portrays God as a moral agent. Think 1 Samuel 15:3 or just think about Hell.
The use of "evil" in the King James Version is archaic; most modern translations render the word as "calamity" or "destruction". So, this passage is not specifically discussing moral evil (or good).
This points to the fact that the Bible is either unclear, or that it needs to be read in ancient Hebrew, Greek, and Aramaic.
The context of the passage shows that God created both yin and yang. God therefore created both good and evil, as well as calamity and destruction.
If judgments of moral quality cannot be predicated of God's acts, it is difficult to conceive of how God could be a morally good being.
God, in his wisdom, may have morally sufficient reasons for permitting evil.
Even if we in our limited understanding cannot comprehend God's reasons, is impossible to deductively demonstrate the impossibility of God having any morally sufficient reasons for permitting evil.

Even if one critically evaluates every theodicy (divine justification) proposed by philosophers, it is always logically possible for other theodicies to exist beyond the catalogue of human speculation.
This speaks to the unfalsifiability of the claim. If unfalsifiability can defeat an argument, then it is a defeator for the claim that God exists.
If God had a morally sufficient reason for permitting evil, then he permits evil, which is not pure good. It is good and evil with reason; therefore, God is not all good.
To put it simply, that's a big maybe. Whatever those reasons, they would be entirely irrelevant to the well-being of sentient life and so fly in the face of anything of actual moral value.

Transcendent means "independent of the material universe", and immanent "manifested in the material world". Manifesting in the material world means one isn't independent of it, being independent of the material universe prevents from manifesting in it. Meaning those two qualities are incompatible.

The incompatibility only exists if God's manifestation in the universe is permanent. In fact, God only manifested in the physical creation of everything at the beginning of the universe, and has maintained a transcendent relationship with creation since.

If the fourth dimension is space-time, then a god-like being would only need to exist in a dimension we can not comprehend, like the fifth dimension, to be considered a god to beings in the third dimension.

This is a particularly rarefied and purposely unusual definition of transcendent -- transcendence is a quality or set of qualities which "go beyond" some baseline. In philosophy, transcendence conveys the basic ground concept from the word's literal meaning (from Latin), of climbing or going beyond. Thus transcendence is not a trait which excludes a being from being in other modes, it actually requires multiple modes of being.

Transcendence in this sense-- being simultaneously capable of subjecting oneself to physical laws (to allow immanence) and also capable of being free of the same--is an explicit contradiction within a single definition. This makes it an unworkable definition by which to define a thing (i.e. God).

The Transcendence of God implies an additional set of laws beyond the Natural Laws which are capable of defining this capacity. This contradicts the definition of Natural Law, which is itself universal, precluding a set of laws which is a super set of itself or disjoint from it. God's Transcendence is contradictory by definition, requiring a set of laws greater than the universal set to define it.
Ralph Waldo Emerson, father of Transcendentalism, often wrote on the transcendent nature of both God and humans.

A king can visit a jail without becoming bound by the jail. Over and above this the king can exert influence over the jail. In a similar way God can visit the material world while remaining aloof from it.
A physical analog would be that a person can blow on water, exerting influence on the state of said water without becoming the water.
A unidirectional "influence" is in direct conflict with Newton's third law of motion: For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.
Newton's laws apply within the physical realm but there is no reason to assume they apply between the physical and spiritual realms.

A jail is indifferent as to who it detains. Absent all but their status, a king is no more able to leave a jail than a subject. In the same way, a god cannot be both manifest in a material universe and also completely independent of it.

In Christianity, God is knowable on intimate terms... we can call him "Abba Father". This is less true in Judaism, and blasphemous in Islam, in which God is considered to be so "other" to man that he is practically incomprehensible.

Kialo discurssion:     Religion has been a good thing for humankind.

The two ideas in this statement are not linked. Solely because there is wide debate on a topic does not mean that the entire topic is invalid. Many aspects of politics are hotly debated, but this does not mean that the freedom for anyone to murder without punishment is any less wrong.

Religious leaders and this so called "Subversion" are their choices as individual leaders which are fundamentally people still. God is Immutable and also God is able to change any aspect of Creation.Creation is an aspect of God's will or in other words:creation is one of God's artworks painted with the crayons of life and death.

The tone of many religious texts is inconsistent, simultaneously stating that God is a perfect being, and yet requiring that God is praised. A perfect being would not need praise.

If God responds to prayer, then this undermines his transcendence (total independence from all else).

"In religion, transcendence refers to the aspect of a god's nature and power which is wholly independent of the material universe, beyond all physical laws." (en.wikipedia.org) This implies being wholly independent of humans.
If immaterial souls exist that are not subject to physical laws, God could interact with these immaterial souls without violating his transcendence according to this definition.

The use of anthropomorphisms regarding God is a common practice throughout the Bible, probably used metaphorically to help readers understand some of God's actions and attributes, rather than as a literal description of God's nature.
The apparent definition of God negates God as an existent being.  If God is the creator of all things, then God cannot be in the same category of the things created.

God created time. It's like saying a relational human is self-contradictory just because they created unfeeling robots.

If God is assumed to be the universe itself (an oft repeated claim in religious and spiritual documents), then at the instant of the big bang, there was nothing but God - the physical and metaphysical laws that govern everything we know - and an enormous amount of energy. In classical theism, God is not the creator of all things simpliciter, but of all contingent things.

Reality isn't a "thing" per se, but only a metaphysical concept - the property of being real. As has been stated, God could not create reality while also being real, so there's no contradiction in saying that God did not create reality.

God isn't in the same category of created things (contingent). By definition, God is eternal and necesary.

As Isaiah 45:9 says, "Does the clay say to the potter, ‘What are you making?’"
The only person who can rightfully play God, is God.

What people say, when not backed by adequate reason, is not a sufficient reason to do things, as people say things like that a mirror being broken containing one's reflection is bad luck, or will damage one's soul.
Power is not authority.

Us making a sentient sandwich is not analogous to the  supremacy of God's power in creating us.

Saying 'God is a special case, we can't hold them to the same standard' is the logical fallacy of special pleading.
