It is logically impossible for God to be omnipresent and having been there when there was nothing yet. The quality of God would have to include both 'existing' and 'not existing' simultaneously, therefore God is simply non-existent.

God's higher property beyond existence is probably unfathomable to the human mind. Existence is therefore an unadequate term to use when talking about God.

This is based on the assumption that God is part of the universe, rather than separate from it. That is a logical fallacy in and of itself, since it would result in causa sui.
Our incapable minds are insufficient to comprehend the wonders of God, and just because we don’t understand something does not mean that it is false.

The only testifiable and shareable piece of evidence for God's existence are words and books made of these words.
A lot of claims in, for example, Bible have been proven as false, such as the existence of global flood at some point in our history, the age of the Earth and the Universe and so on.

While it is certainly true that our incapability to understand something does not make it false, there exist simpler explanations and theories for God's (non)existence than assuming some mystical ways in which to exist and not exist makes sense, which we can then just label wonders of God and be done with it.

When "there was nothing yet", there was no place in the universe for God to be. Omnipresence is the quality of being at all places at all times. It is not inconsistent with omnipresence to say that God is not in a location that does not exist.
The logical inconsistencies of Classical Theism could simply be the result of faulty reasoning, in such a case God could still exist.
Not having a consistent definition of an object or phenomenon doesn't mean that it doesn't exist, reality exists independently of out concepts and definitions. A better definition may be possible.

It is coherent to conjoin logically independent individually coherent properties.
For example, while a square circle is contradictory, it is not incoherent. We know what a square circle is like: It is square, and it is circular. Nothing can be such, but we understand what it would take for something to be such.
Hence, the classical definition of God is not incoherent.
Some phenomena modeled in Quantum Mechanics are logically inconsistent, yet they still exist. This shows that contradiction of a phenomena has no negative impact to the reality of phenomena.
Dual particle nature is not an inherent contradiction, only an apparent one, demanding elaboration of theory not abandoning of it.
Likewise, God contradiction is just apparent one, demanding elaboration of theology.

The problem is not with QM theory, but with human mind being unable to cope with the practical results. With QM, physics knocked on the doors of metaphysics. "If someone says 'I understand QM', then that one does not know what QM is." There is an inherent contradiction in human mental abilities. And it did not arise from contradictory concepts, or ideas but due to real life facts.
We do not in fact have any notion as to what would be required to make something both square and circular, as one property necessarily excludes the other by definition.

Each holy text of the 3 major monotheistic religions gives its own definition of God. Not having a consistent definition of an object or phenomenon prevents claims about its existence from having any impact or meaning.

First, there is no consistent definition of a spin in quantum physics, but that does not mean that it does not exist. Next, does it mean that if there is a consistent definition, then a defined object must exist. Then I will define a four-legged pink unicorn, etc...
Truth claims that cannot be falsified by evidence, or truth claims that are self-contradictory are false. Thus, an internally inconsistent definition of something does mean that thing does not exist.

I define God as a force that cannot be defined. That being is  conceivable, in spite of not possessing the attribute that you want to imply upon Him. God's infinite existence can be discussed - even proven - without defining that existence with the kind of precision reserved for humanly-knowable, finite objects. This logic necessarily concedes that he cannot exist as hitherto defined under classical theism. While allowing some version of "God" to exist, it must necessarily be different from that described by Classical Theism.
An inconsistent definition does not allow for a rational discussion.
A truly transcendent thing has no way of making contact with the material world. Any method by which contact is made cannot transcend material interaction.

There is no clear classical definition of God, because the attributes of God are not well defined.
The attributes of God were clearly defined in the parameters of this discussion. No other attributes are relevant to this discussion.
All of the attributes of God have a proper definition.

Omniscience means that God possesses knowledge of all possible and actual states.
Omnibenevolence cannot be properly defined because goodness cannot be objectively defined.
The conclusion "God cannot in principle exist" does not follow from the premise "The 'classical' definition of God is contradictory or incoherent".
There may be other definitions which are not contradictory or incoherent.
If the definition of 'God' used for the purposes of this debate is contradictory or incoherent, then for the purposes of this debate God does not exist.
Suggesting something could exist does not support that it does.
One could also suggest that fairies and unicorns could exist. Evidence proving they exist is vital for belief.
Suggesting that something could exist weakens the arguments claiming it can not exist.
If we cannot reasonably establish a definition of all powerful, all knowing, and all good, we cannot establish that God in the classical sense exists.
If he does not exist in the classical sense, God could be an antagonist to be avoided or fought against.
The existence of a concept is not dependent on our ability to define it. At best, this would imply that we cannot know whether God exists, which is not the same as implying that God does not exist.
It means that the word God has no definition, and is therefore meaningless.

An argument for faulty reasoning within Classical Theism actually begins to discredit the resulting theistic claim that a God exists through degrading the reasoning capabilities of those responsible for Classical Theism.

Per wikipedia definition, most monotheists agree on three qualities of God: all-knowing, all-capable and completely good. Qualities attributed to god in Classical theism are a superset of these, and considering this superset faulty does by no means discredit (mono)theism as a whole.
"Faulty reasoning" is proposed as an "alternate pathway" defeater and is not intended to be taken as fact supported by evidence, but only to show that the claim it counters is not necessarily true.
This has yet to be demonstrated in Islam. Islam maintains a definitional framework for Allah that encompasses all his attributes without contradiction.
The same applies to the Christian God. The Bible maintains a consistent definition of him, and there isn't a single flaw or contradiction found in the Christian God's nature throughout the Bible.

The logical contradiction offered by the traditional definition of God does not prevent its existence.

The various paradoxical assertions with the classical attributes of God can't be relied upon to negate the claim of God's existence, since the prime feature of God is that its existence does not rely upon logic.
One cannot beat out an argument which argues that the object it supports to exist transcends beyond all human reasoning.

Apparent contradictions in classical theism may appear from translation difficulties.
Possible contradictions in classical theism may appear from transcription difficulties and errors introduced over centuries of existence.

The source ideas for classical theism - the Bible, the works of Plato, Aristotle, etc - had already existed in documented form for centuries before the classical period. The oldest Bible, for example, is from 330-360 AD. The multiple rounds of transcription and retranscription that preserved those source documents over the thousands of years to today are likely to have introduced errors/ caused loss of subtlety in the original conceptions.
The oldest document of the Bible is the Septuagint with fragments dating back to 300BCE. (Of course consisting only of the Old Testament as the events of the New Testament have not yet happened).

The Septuagint is itself the translation into Greek of a number of earlier texts in Hebrew. While there are fragments of (Hebrew) Biblical text dating back to 300 BC (and before), the oldest complete Bible (compared to the book in its current form) would probably be one containing both Old and New Testament - hence the date of 300 AD. In either case, an older Bible makes an even stronger case for transmission/ transcription errors.

The original domcuments of the Bible were transcribed in several different locations, by several different monasteries, each with detailed systems in place to ensure as accurate a transcription as possible. An error made in one transcription did not infect the others due to their isolation. Therefore, we can cross examine these documents to identify and eliminate errors.thebibleproject.com

Comparing multiple independent transcripts does help with scribal error, but it does not guarantee *perfect* transmission. Another possible problem comes from the choice of certain sources as more authoritative than others. The Masoretic Text, for instance, is considered the source book for the Hebrew Tanakh (Bible). Though there may be good reason to choose that source as more correct than others, this also ensures that errors/ interpretations in the Text itself become part of future canon.

One apparent contradiction in classical theism is that of a theistic God changing its mind. God, per Plato, is changeless because a) nothing can change God, and b) God would not change, because it is already perfect. Parts of the Bible, like God repenting the creation of humanity, therefore seem to contradict theism. The problem might exist because today's Bible carries an edited version of the source documents of the Old Testament. 'Repent' might not carry the subtleties of the original text.
An omnipotent God should be able to keep the record of itself clear enough for it to be not contradictory.

Meaning that belief in the "present" definition is wrong, and since the "true" definition has been lost, there's no way to prove or disprove the existence of this definition, but surely proves that the present definition doesn't exist.

The ideas within classical theism come from a number of thinkers, including those as far back as Plato and Aristotle. These ideas were not developed in English, and even in their native languages, were reliant on the context of their times for the subtleties of meaning involved. The version of theism we’re debating, off Wiki, is already a compressed version of a complicated concept developed in multiple languages and over several centuries. It would be more extraordinary if there were no errors.

In theory, a perfect God would be capable of communicating to man in such a way that all possible translations of the original message would still be accurate. In other words, He could make the "word of God" fool-proof; a message so utterly perfect, no man could ever misconstrue or spoil it.

If the definition of God used for the purpose of this debate is contradictory due to translation issues, that would still mean that, per the definition of God used in this debate, the definition of God is contradictory and so He does not exist.
If God exists, then they are incomprehensible to the human mind, so claims to the non-existence of God based on a lack of comprehension or coherence are invalid.
While the terms used to define the God of classical theism may be inconsistent, it does not follow that the referent is inconsistent. It simply means the terms used to describe God should be refined.

The Anselmian Perfect Being Theology approach to the concept of God is to understand the various attributes of God in the manner which makes for the maximal *possible* greatness. If the alleged contradictions cannot be otherwise resolved, then the attributes should be re-described to give the maximal possible greatness. Thus the paradoxes are resolved but God remains "that being than which a greater cannot be conceived".
Refining the classical definition of God would amount to denying that God, as classically defined, exists.
The definition(s) is all we have in this case, and some may argue it's all we can get. Therefore it's sensible to argue about what we have.
Need for refinement of a definition does not necessarily imply lack of accuracy, but could suggest lack of precision.
Refinement in this case could mean reducing ambiguity, thereby improving coherency.
Just because something may have created the universe doesn't mean the force that did knows about humans or Earth in any way. Seeing the number of objects in space, it is incredibly unlikely.
Being the ultimate cause of everything that has a cause would be omnipotence in the purest form.

Omnipotence is generally defined as "having unlimited power and potential; being able to bring about (effortlessly) any possible state of affairs." This seems incompatible with being an "unmoved mover" or "pure actuality"
Pure actuality, by definition, would have no potentials, and hence no powers. It couldn't do/be anything other than what it in fact did/was.
Being able to cause the cosmos to exist is not the same as being able to do anything. Whatever can cause the cosmos to exist may not be able to do other things, such as communicate with humans.
There is an extensive amount of evidence suggesting the cause of the universe fits the properties of the classical God, as gathered by Aquinas in the Summa Contra Gentiles.
Possible causes of the universe other than God are extremely unlikely.
To accept one particular claim on the grounds that other claims appear unlikely is a false dichotomy (there may be other claims we have not evaluated) and a shifting of the burden of proof.
God as a cause of the creation of the universe is at least as extremely unlikely as any other of the extremely unlikely causes.
Since some of the properties of a classical God are met, this argument can be considered to constitute evidence for classical theism.

The law of entropy indicates that the cause of the universe must be infinite and completely lacking entropy.  If God's entropy is 0 and he is infinite than he must necessarily be good at least to the extent that entropy is defined as lack of order or chaos.

There's no reason to believe the second law of thermodynamics matters in respect to metaphysical claims. It doesn't even necessarily affect all physical claims because we still haven't figured out how the laws of pshysics worked during the beginning of the universe.
Saying something could be the answer does not make it more likely then other scenarios.
The law of entropy does not require the universe be infinite, or to lack entropy at the beginning.
Free will exists within the universe, and can only be caused by another free will. Thus the thing which caused the universe had free will, and must be an intelligent being.
The assumption that things must come from things like them is false, as the rocks, and sticks that start a fire are not hot.
There is no objective evidence for the existence of free will in the universe, thus free will does not exist.

If there is an Unmoved Mover at the root of all change in the universe, then that means every potentiality which is actualized, or even could be actualized is fundamentally derivative of that Mover. To be able to actualize every possible potentiality is just what it means to be "omnipotent."

If there is not an Unmoved Mover at the root of all change in the universe, then that means no potentiality which is actualized, or even could be actualized is fundamentally derivative of such an Unmoved Mover. No such Unmoved Mover has been demonstrated to exist, let alone to exist and be omnipotent. If an Unmoved Mover does not exist, then it can have no direct effect on the real world and is therefore not omnipotent in reality.
This kind of "omnipotence" need only be in place at the time of the universe's creation, and does not need to be an active force, making the Unmoved Mover a deistic God, rather than theistic.
The Unmoved Mover is outside of time (eternal), therefore it is present before the begining of time and has no end.
The Unmoved Mover is not proved by reference to a chronological beginning of the world, but rather a hierarchical "beginning" of the world, which is here and now, at every moment of time in action.

In fact, Aquinas considered that reason alone could not prove that the world had a beginning. Aristotle considered that the universe had always existed, yet he made a similar first-way argument for the existence of God.

The ability to actualize is distinct from actualization. The ability to actualize requires decision making power, whereas intelligence is not required for actualization. The ultimate cause of the universe only requires actualization.

If evil is a privation of good, then a thing that has no flaw is perfectly good by definition. The Unmoved Mover is Pure Act (containing no potentiality) and therefore is the perfect realization of its own essence. But if it is perfectly good, then it is "omni-benevolent."

"Caring about the wellbeing of humans," as the God of classical theism (particularly Abrahamic religions) is described to, in no way relates to lacking privations: it is something that must be added on to the description. Otherwise, God could be like that described by Aristotle or Spinoza (which care nothing about humans, if they can be said to care at all).
If evil is just a privation of good, then nothing is wrong. It could only be properly called "less good". This would mean that murder, rape, etc, are not wrong, they are simply less good.
Nothing is purely 100% totally "wrong" in this sense, because everything that exists, no matter how corrupted it be, still exists, and existence itself is good.
If things can only exist on different gradations of goodness, then rape and murder must be inherently good in some way. The fact that they exist does not make them good.

Evil has not been established to be accurately described as a mere lack of good. For example, if donating a billion dollars to a specific charity were good, failing to make that donation would not mean you are evil.

The words "evil" and "wrong" still have meaning in the context of the privation view of evil. "Wrong" would refer to some action which corrupts the good. And evil could refer to a state of affairs strongly contrary to the good. But thinking of things as "less good" is in fact a more precise characterization, as it contains the privation aspect of evil, where the simple word "evil" can be misunderstood to imply a separately existing standard or entity by which evil is measured.
If evil is contrary to "the good" then it cannot be considered a privation. It must be its own idea.
There is no reason to assume that good is the natural state that evil is a privation from.
Flawlessness does not necessitate moral goodness.

Flawlessness by definition necessitates moral goodness. For if a thing was not morally good, how could that thing be flawless? Its lack of moral goodness would be a flaw. But if it truly is flawless, then it is necessarily morally good.
There are no mentions of moral goodness in the definition for flawlessness. Furthermore, morally neutral things can be considered flawless.
Intelligence is suggested by the incredibly precise conditions found in the universe that allow life to exist.
The Kalam cosmological argument doesn't claim God is omnibenevolent.

Any entity able to cause the universe's existence would be transcendent, necessary, enormously powerful, and rational (because an irrational abstract ideal has no creative power). Such an entity would rightfully be called God.

Any argument that refers to the "cause" of the universe is circular. A cause by its very nature precedes whatever it has caused. The universe, by definition, is all of spacetime. Since all of time is a part of the universe, it is logically impossible for anything to precede it.
It is impossible for any contingent thing to have preceded the universe.
God is by definition necesary.
A cause need not be chronologically prior to its effect, but must be ontologically prior to its effect.

Our best scientific evidence indicates that time came into existence. The cause for this event, commonly known as the "Big Bang" must necessarily have existed prior to creation, but obviously could not have existed chronologically prior (at a point in time prior) to time.
While the space-time of our Universe may have come into existence in the very earliest moments of the Big Bang, this doesn't foreclose an earlier system that had or continues to have its own time.

The math that predicted black holes also predicts white holes. The birth of our Universe seems to fit the description of a white hole. Rather than intense gravity, it has intense cosmological force. It is one-way out, rather than one-way in. Black holes in one Universe may be white holes in another.
The Bord-Guth-Vilenkin theory applies as well to a "bubble" multiverse.
If that were true then time would go back infinitely which it does not. There is a clear cut beginning.
The principle of causation is not a physical law.

The principle of causation only states that causes are at least partially responsible for effects, and effects are at least partially dependent on causes. It isn't necessary that time be involved whatsoever.

Imagine a ball colliding with a sheet of fabric. When the ball impacts with the fabric it creates a dent in it - but the dent appears at the exact same time as the impact. However, despite no time difference between the cause and effect, we still know which is which.

The difference between "enormously powerful" and "omnipotent" is, as the difference between any finite number and infinity, infinite, so it is not reasonable to equate the two; if God is defined as omnipotent, this being is not necessarily God.
God's necessity is an assumption. It cannot be proven.
The world in which literally nothing exists is a possible world. If that is true, then there cannot be any necessary beings.
If accepted, this would only show that God is necessary when the universe exists, so God, in this case, is only as necessary as the universe is.
God's necessity in the contingency argument is a premise which is defended separately, unrelated to the existence of the universe.

While an intelligent cause may exist without a particular effect, an effect cannot exist without a cause. DaVinci would have existed had he not painted the Mona Lisa; the Mona Lisa could not have existed without DaVinci.

The "necessity" referred to in the contingency argument is modal necessity, meaning that God's nonexistence would be logically impossible - not that God is "necessary" to explain some data. Equating the two commits the fallacy of equivocation.
The contingency argument is self-defeating since it implies that God must also have a sufficient reason to exist.
The Principle of Sufficient Reason suggests that everything requires a sufficient reason for its existence, but says nothing about whether this reason is internal or external to the thing itself.
It is circular reasoning to claim that something's existence is the reason for its existence.
If God could be the sufficient reason for his own existence, so could the universe be it's own reason for existence.
The universe requires a necessary cause whose nonexistence would be impossible. The universe itself is known to not be necessary, and its nonexistense is entirely conceivable.
There is no reason to assume God's nonexistence is impossible.

Although it is describable as an empty point in space with nothing, not even space, on all sides, minus the point, an actual conception of it's non-existence, and actual conception of nothing, is at the very least quite hard.
God exists by the necessity of His own nature.
This is yet another formulation of the argument in sequential fashion.
No proof is offered in this link unless we assume the nature of humans to be an arbitrarily defined philosophical entity; something which is virtually impossible to test scientifically or verify
This is another formulation of Aquinas' First Way.

The universe is considered a thermodynamic closed system, i.e. nothing exists 'outside' of it per se. This means it cannot be affected by something not in the system. If God exists, he should exist solely and wholly in the universe, not without.
God, as defined in this debate, is transcendant, not contained by the universe.

Given that we don't know anything about the pre-Planck singularity (i.e. when our observable Universe allegedly emerged), the Prime Mover is a worse argument than to simply say "we don't know" violating the Occam's razor principle by imposing new complex constructs.
An "Unmoved Mover" (aka a being of Pure Actuality) is not the same thing as God.

Jesus, in Christianity, is God, in a meaningful and literal sense. However, Jesus had potentialities (e.g. the potential to be born, to age, to speak, to eat, to be crucified, etc.). Thus the God of Christianity couldn't be an Unmoved Mover.
The Unmoved Mover and the First Cause describe a deistic god, not a classical theistic God.

According to classical theism, God is the "absolutely metaphysically ultimate being". If a being is a First Cause, this this the same thing as being metaphysically ultimate, therefore the First Cause is God.

The claim defines "absolutely metaphysically ultimate being" as simply the first cause. While the link defines classical theism differently by adding personhood and multiple attributes to the first cause that hasn't been demonstrated. Using the two interchangebly is a fallacy of equivocation.

It is not necessary for a single line of evidence to completely describe all features of God. It is enough to say that the evidence supports the existence of a being that meets the classical existence of God. Other lines of evidence may supply more information of God's other attributes.

In order for there to be multiple unmoved movers (composed of Pure Act), there must be some differentiating feature that one mover has and the others lack.
There can only be a differentiating feature if there is some unactualized potential one mover has.

But this defeats the definition of the unmoved mover as pure act, with no potentiality whatsoever.

Thus, if there is an unmoved mover, by definition, there must only be one. (Oneness being a classical attribute of God)
There is no reason to assume that any of the other non-composite entities need to be pure act (Unmoved movers).
By definition, an Unmoved Mover, First Cause or Necessary Being must be pure act.
There is no need for there to be a differentiating feature beyond it not being the same one.

Two things can only be distinct if they have some feature which differentiates them. Even two theoretically identical apples are different in that they are not in the same location, and are not composed of the exact same atoms. There must be at least one differentiating feature.
If God is everywhere then location does not matter. If God is immaterial then atoms don't factor into the differentiation.
This is an issue of semantics. Call it God, call it Great Green Arkleseizure, we are talking about the same thing.
The Unmoved Mover is by definition the the ultimate cause of the existence of things, and whatever else God is supposed to be, He is the ultimate cause of things.
Whatever is the ultimate cause of things (assuming there is such a thing) need not have the other properties attributed to God (e.g. omniscience, omnibenevolence, (trinity))

This involves "change" and "motion" are used as a mere synonym for "coming into existence"/actualization. Since some things do not exist, this entails the Unmoved mover is not perfect, not omnipotent, or both. Therefore, the Unmoved mover is not God.
Reality is not divided by Act and Potency.
The fact that a semantic distinction can be made between actuality and potentiality does not imply anything but our own creativity.
The distinction between act and potency is not merely semantic, but is a real feature of the world.
If there were no Potency, change could not occur, and if there were no Act, then nothing would exist.
If everything that exists is changing, then potency and act need not be distinguished. We have yet to observe anything that exists without being in a constant state of change.

The very first of the famous Twenty Four Thomistic Theses is: “Potency and Act divide being in such a way that whatever is, is either pure act, or of necessity it is composed of potency and act as primary and intrinsic principles.”
The postulation of Act and Potency as real features of the universe is a claim which is impossible to verify scientifically.

The scientific method itself presupposes the existence of Act and Potency as real features of the world. Since these notions are implicit in the business of science, it is intrinsically impossible to scientifically verify their existence.
Since science is not the only source of truth, it is not necessary to verify the distinction between Act and Potency, if the distinction can be verified in another way.
The distinction between Act and Potency can be verified deductively, following from the fact of existence, and the fact that change occurs in reality.
Science is the only source for verified metaphysical truth.

Science cannot verify the truth of mathematics. Science presupposes the truth of mathematics in order to function. But mathematics contains verified truth, so science cannot be the only valid source for truth.
Mathematics can not verify metaphysical truths, only model scientific truth.

This can be said to be true, but it can be taken as a defense of Theism. A metaphysical science would for example make use of deductive reasoning or a descending process of acquiring knowledge, meaning taking claims from a religion that make logical sense and then following the procedure prescribed by the religion and discovering if the promised results come.
Scienctific reasoning can be applied to metaphysical realms and could corroborate spiritual and religious claims.
This is false. Science assumes a metaphysics which allows it to operate. Even the very notion of causation is a metaphysical posit.
It is false that philosophy has given up metaphysical concepts. They are still a fundamental part of modern philosophical discussion.
Act and Potency as metaphysical notions are built on an archaic understanding of physics and therefore only exist today as metaphors with no rationale.

If one accepts that the universe came into existence, then to argue it must have been caused assumes that the current laws of the universe were the same at the time of creation. We know that the physical laws break down at a certain point, so it is conceivable that the cause/effect principle did not apply at the beginning.

The argument from change (properly understood) makes no claim about the historical creation of the universe. This would be a "per accidens" causal chain, which can, in theory, extend backwards forever. The argument depends on a "per se" causal chain which is present at every distinct moment of existence. Thus the "physical laws" are irrelevant to the validity of the argument.

The argument is inductive, as it assumes all changes have causes from our experience, which is bound by the natural laws. That being said, these laws many not apply on the quantum level or at the beginning of the universe.
This relies on the false notion that nothing can be reduced to act except by what is already in act.

This premise would require that when a hydrogen balloon is lit by a match to produce H2O, one of the three causes (oxygen, hydrogen, or fire), would necessarily have the actuality of water, but this is absurd.

There does not necessarily need to be an unmoved mover to explain efficient motion in the world. The world could be explained by circular causes.  For example, A cause B, B caused C, C caused D, and D caused A.  Reality could be structured that acts of potency change into acts of actuality in a circular fashion, hence an unmoved mover would not be necessary to explain original physical motion.

Such a structure of reality seems to require an infinitely-old universe with an infinite regression of causes and events. Such a regression is logically impossible, and stands at odds with scientific evidence for a finite universe.
The argument doesn't negate the possibility of multiple unmoved movers.
This series of "unmoved movers" would, as a whole comprise the single set we would understand as a classical theistic god.
There is no need to resort to God to explain the changes we see, as a chain of mundane causes could stretch back into infinity.

Time is a measure of change - without time, there is no change. As such, it does not make sense to discuss a cause that brought the universe and time into existence, since the universe going from potential to actual entails change.

Change does not require time to pass. Change in the broad sense meant here means only "actualization of potential." If there were no time, but only one moment of existence for our world, that moment would still require the actualization of the potential for existence in all the myriad things of this world. Thus, each and every distinct moment of time, and not any collection of moments, represents "change" in the relevant sense.
An instance in time is analagous to a picture. Change occurs over subsequent instances, much like a series of photos can demonstrate change in the setting.

While temporal change is a valid kind of change, it is not the (only) kind of change meant by the proof from change. As stated in the proof, all that is meant by "change" is "actualization of potential." Temporal change is a subset of the kind of change meant here.

A potential cannot become actual without the passing of time. This follows because a potential isn't actual, and while it can *become* actual this must temporally follow the state where it hasn't yet been actualized. It is impossible for there to be no temporal distinction between a potential and an actuality, because such a thing would imply the potential and the actuality are the same thing (which they by definition aren't). Therefore there must be passing of time for change to happen.

Change is a "an act or process through which something becomes different." Acts and processes ential time; indeed, Aristotle recognized that time is a measure of change. To speak about a moment of "existence" without time is nonsensical, as nothing has been demonstrated to exist outside of time.
Aquinas's conclusion only uses the word god as an end point. There is no justification for its use in his argument.
The neo-platonic model claims that God, a being that is all-powerful, all-knowing, and exists outside of time and space, is absolutely simple. This is contradictory.

All that is meant by "absolutely simple" is that God is without parts. The being of God is identical to the "attributes" of God. In other words, such characteristics as omnipresence, goodness, truth, eternity, etc. are identical to God's being. There is no contradiction inherent here.
An absolutely simple being is of necessity pure actuality (as opposed to potentiality) and thus is necessarily all-powerful, all-knowing, immaterial, etc.
Then an absolutely simple thing is anything that is, by definition, itself. This can be literally anything, making the argument pointless.
Anything that is composed of potentiality and actuality is not simple. Which is (nearly) everything you interact with on a daily basis.
Electrons, photons, quarks, and gluons also fit the provided definition of absolute simplicity.
Even the elementary subatomic particles may not be simple, but may be composed of simpler things, such as strings.
Then those simpler things are not composite.
The parts of even the most fundamental material components of the universe, such as elementary particles, are still composed of at least two metaphysical parts: potentiality and actuality.
Changeability implies composition of the metaphysical parts: act and potency. Composition is contrary to the definition of simplicity.

If Composition is contrary to simplicity and changeability means composition, then any description of god changing in any way is proof that god is not simple. God becoming his own son, or creating new laws at any point, for instance, point to god being changeable. Therefore, many descriptions of a god are changeable and cannot be considered simple.

Whether the descriptions of a particular religion compromise the simplicity of God is another debate entirely, since the God of classical theism could exist even if this or that theistic religion presents an incoherent picture of that God.

In orthodox Christian theology, the Incarnation does not represent a change in God's Divine Essence but rather a hypostatic union of Jesus' changeable, human nature with the unchangeable divine nature.

“We do not conceive the mode of conjunction to be according to addition (i.e. change)”; just as in the union of man with God, nothing is added to God by the grace of adoption, but what is divine is united to man; hence, not God but man is perfected.
God's creating a new (moral) law does not entail a change in God's essence, but rather an addition to the content of revelation granted to humanity.

The particles are actual to the extent that any given particle is really present, but they are potential to the extent that any given particle could be in a different location, or energy state, or really could be changed in any way.
The definition of simple that was provided says nothing about not being changeable.
Potentiality and actuality are metaphysical attributes and hence fall under the provided definition.
Many descriptions of God can be split into smaller parts.
Brahman in Hinduism is split into smaller gods.
If Brahman can be split, he is not simple, ergo he is not the God of classical theism.
This description of a god meets the criteria for the definition of a god under the classical theistic definition. Therefore, it is fair to discuss.
In Catholicism, the Holy Trinity is composed of the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.

Whether the Trinitarian description of God compromises the absolute simplicity of God is another debate entirely. This debate is about the classical theistic conception of God, which is not exclusive to the Catholic Church.

When we talk about a human's power, or his intellect, we are talking about actually different things. But precisely because God is noncomposite (lacking distinct parts), we cannot apply these terms in exactly the same sense. We must apply them in an analogical sense. (as opposed to a univocal or equivocal sense. see also)

Under an analogical use of language describing God, the many descriptions of Him fail to be split into smaller parts, as they all remain descriptions of the same thing.

Equivocal Term: A term that has a variety of different meanings. An associate equivocal term has completely different intentions once it’s used. For instance, the term “Chihuahua” will signify (a) a breed of dog; (b) a state of Mexico.

Univocal Term: A term that has only one meaning. That is, it signifies only one thought, and therefore corresponds to only one definition. Words mean the same thing even when applied in different contexts, for example, black shoes, black hair, black car.
Analogous Term: A term that is supposed to convey one or additional similar characteristics that exist between two ideas.
Premises 2 and 3 of the Analogous terms are unsupported.
While the statement "God is omnipotent" does not mean the same thing as "God is omniscient", it doesn't follow that they are not statements about the same one reality.
Gottlob Frege distinguished between the 'sense' of an expression and its 'reference'.

"The evening star" does not have the same sense as "the morning star", but both expressions refer to one and the same thing--namely, the planet Venus. Similarly for descriptions of God. (from p 77 of 5 Proofs of the Existence of God)
A description of an entity is not the entity itself.
This claim directly misunderstands the parent claim by conflating "attributes" with "identity".

By definition, I am identical to myself. However, I am not identical to my attributes (i.e. I am not identical to my intellect, my risibility, my arm, or my being in Los Angeles at 12:25 AM: these are aspects of material or metaphysical composition that entail I am not simple).
"God is, by definition, himself" and "God's being/essence and God's attributes are metaphysically identical" are different statements.

God's being or essence is identical to his attributes. That is, God's omniscience, goodness, omnipotence, etc. are not metaphysical components of God, but they are different ways that we as finite beings analogically speak of one and the same fundamental reality.
To define God this way can be refuted - or allows Him to be refuted - by the mere logical possibility of a non-God being with any of God's supposed attributes.
There is no reason to believe a single being existed over a number of beings.
It could be that omnipotence is very hard to obtain so that there is only one omnipotent being in existence.

Per the definition used in this debate, God is timeless and immutable. He cannot have "obtained" omnipotence at some point in the past, so this is not relevant as a defence of the God we're debating the existence of.

The Kalam argument is question begging as it must assume God exists to define the notion 'begins to exist'. This is because 'begins to exist' is defined such that only God falls into the category of things that never begin to exist.
Premise 2 of "The universe began to exist." positions the universe in one of the two categories established by premise 1.
This is functionally identical to saying "The universe is not God".
It is entirely possible that the cosmos (or the multiverse) is not caused
"Anything that begins to exist has a cause." Assumes two categories of things. Things that begin and have a cause, and things that do not begin to exist and do not have a cause.

If God is the only thing which exists in the category of 'things which do no begin to exist' then the initial premise is functionally identical to saying "Everything except God begins and must have a cause."

There are physical entities, that would fall into the category of things that never begin to exist if they existed: a steady state universe, an eternally inflating multiverse, a closed time-like loop universe

Premise 3 ("If the Universe has a cause, the best candidate for that cause is the God of classical theism") shows that out of all theological and philosophical entities that do not begin to exist, that the God of classical theism is the best candidate. This still leaves open several possible candidates for which type of theist God exists

Premise 2 indicates it is not assumed only God is in the category of things that do not begin to exist. The goal of the premise is to provide reasons for the claim that out of all possible cosmological models that do not imply a universe which begins to exist, none of them can in fact exist (reasons for this provided elsewhere)
There are metaphysical entities that would fall into the category of things that never began to exist if they existed such as abstract entities

There are theological entities of various religions that would fall into the category of things that never began to exist if they existed: multiple gods, a monotheistic or trinitarian God, impersonal forces such as Chaos or Order
The fact that the things of our everyday experience are composite, or composed of more than one distinct part, eventually leads to the conclusion that God exists.
A composite thing exists at any moment only insofar as its parts are combined at that moment.
This composition of parts requires a concurrent cause. (It requires some outside thing or things to cause the parts to be combined.)
Any composite thing has a cause of its existence at any moment during which it exists.
Each of the things of our experience has a cause at any moment during which it exists. (Everything we see is being caused as we see it)
If the cause of a composite thing's existence at any moment is itself composite, then it will in turn require a cause of its own existence at that moment.
The regress of causes this entails is hierarchical in nature (a per se causal chain), and such a regress must therefore have a first member.

Only something absolutely simple or non-composite could in principle be the first member of such a series.

So, the existence of each of the things of our experience presupposes an absolutely simple or non-composite cause.
God is this absolutely simple or non-composite cause of all composite things.
No justification is given as to why the argument determines that the non-composite entity is God.

To define a God of classical theology to be basically the simplest thing imaginable is to define away everything that defines it as a God according to classical theology. There are no known mechanisms by which an unchanging nondescript simple thing with no moving parts can accomplish anything at all. That's not a God. It's more like an infinitesimal neutrino field without even a neutrino. Basically as close to nothing as anything can be. You might as well say God is nothing.

Divine Simplicity implies many of the other features of God:
There can be only one absolutely simple thing. The absolutely simple thing must be unchanging (no potentiality). Something devoid of potentiality must inherently be immaterial, for material implies potential. Thus already we have Oneness, Unchanging, Immateriality, all common features of the classical definition of God.
Divine Simplicity does not imply smallness. It actually implies immateriality which makes the concept of physical size inapplicable.
To be absolutely simple is a very different thing from nothing. Existence is absolutely contrary to non-existence. There are no "gradations" of existence. Something either exists or it does not.

There are zero scientifically validated examples of a thinking entity which is more simple than a hydrogen atom, which is a complex composite of subatomic particles. Therefore it would be ludicrous to assume from that claim that one could logically conclude such a hypothetical first cause to be capable of thought. Therefore, it could not be a God, at least in the classical theology sense.

God is immaterial. Science confines its study and its methods to only what portions of the material world are measurable. Therefore the lack of "scientifically validated examples" is irrelevant. It is like expecting a yardstick to be able to gauge what something sounds like. Science is the wrong tool for the job of analyzing God. Science is the right tool for analyzing His creation.
If there is no way to measure a god then there is no reason to believe a god exists.

Such a causal chain is not a chain of caused existence but of cause change.  Change happens. Change accumulates. When change accumulates, that is called evolution. Evolution does not require a starting point but merely something in which change can accumulate.

No God required.
This argument is fallacious because it assumes a single first cause instead of multiple first causes.
Ockham's razor implies that one should not unnecessarily multiply causes.

Such claims of composites needing a cause of existence are unsubstantiated.

Changing or retaining a given form will not make something cease to exist, so claims of needing moment to moment causes of existence are nonsensical.

It is not unsubstantiated to say that composite things require a cause. In fact, the whole argument from composition purports to show why they need such a cause, and why that cause must be simple and non-composite. It will not do to merely declare the argument to be unsubstantiated without pointing out a flaw in the premise, or in the reasoning from point to point.

Some parts of nature are very interactive and some parts of nature are very stable, but continuation of existence does not require an unchanging form. Just because something changes enough that humans might choose different labels or descriptions for it does not mean that anything ceased to exist. Composite things form and break down. These are well understood natural events, not mysterious supernatural events.
The argument from composition does not talk about things forming or breaking down, whether "naturally" or supernaturally. It only depends on one instant of any single composite entity existing.
It is a red herring to mention "unchanging form" in the context of the argument from composition, because that argument makes no mention of "unchanging form."
No moment to moment cause of existence is needed for a stable composite to continue existing. Both the formation of and stability of composites are well understood natural phenomena.

To the extent that a "stable composite" depends for its existence on the continued action of the laws of nature, that composite is caused from moment to moment by they continued action of the laws of nature. Thus a moment to moment cause is present in every physical composite object.
Consider the example of a simple stone at rest. The stone is a composite of many molecules, all of which are held together by the continually acting laws of chemistry.

The laws of nature do not act, continually or otherwise. That e.g. force equals mass times acceleration, is a truth that is and remains true, not an action of anything on anything or a thing that acts on anything.

The evolution of a composite is merely the result of the composite accumulating changes and is a well understood process which does not require existence to be caused at each moment in time. Anything which changes has its former state and the change as the causes of its new state. No moment to moment cause of existence is needed for a composite to change or to be in its current state.
The cause is merely the absence of anything decomposing it. Absent such a decomposing cause, things will persist as they are.
Not all composites require concurrent causes.
No composite entity can be named which does not require a concurrent cause or series of causes to hold it together. Thus, all composites require concurrent causes.
The universe is a named entity which does not require a concurrent cause.
It isn't known with certainty that the universe has no concurrent cause. Such a cause may exist and be called God.
This sentence required non-concurrent keystrokes to be typed.

The cause of non-concurrent keystrokes is a concurrent brain state including an idea, the desire to communicate it, a plan for how to communicate it using a keyboard, and an intention to complete the plan.

Such composites can naturally form, naturally evolve, and naturally break down, but have no existence separate from their parts, so it is merely their current state and not their current existence which depends upon their current combination of parts.

A composite can change and accumulate changes without ceasing to exist and therefore does not depend upon its combination of parts at any given moment for its existence but rather depends on its evolution for its current state.

Subatomic particles form composites, including more complex subatomic particles, as well as composites known as atoms, due to natural affinities caused by natural forces according to the natural laws of physics.

These "natural forces" or "laws of physics" would then be the (intermediate) cause which keeps composite entities together. If the laws themselves are in some way composite, then they too require a cause. If they are not composite, then they are absolutely simple, which has been argued elsewhere to equate to God.
Natural causes are still natural causes regardless of whether they are composite natural causes or non-composite natural causes.

Simply because it has been claimed elsewhere that God is absolutely simple and implied that God is the only such being, does not mean that anything absolutely simple has been shown elsewhere to equate to God. Claims are neither proof nor evidence. They are claims.
The argument presupposes that something non-composite and immaterial can cause something material to come into existence.

The argument does not "presuppose" that something non-composite and immaterial can cause something material to come into existence, but rather the argument (purports to) shows that something non-composite and immaterial can cause something material.

The difference is in assuming as a premise or in accepting as a conclusion.

Composition is a mental abstraction. No composition can be said to be 'caused' by anything because it is not an event. Things may become stuck together or even amalgamated into something new but seeing them as a composite is a mental shift, not a change in the real world.

Changes can accumulate within a complex environment of interacting atoms and molecules. If chemicals accumulating are inorganic, then this is an example of inorganic evolution. If they are organic, then this is an example of organic evolution. If they are molecules which carry mutable information inherited by any biological organism, this accumulation of inherited change is an example of biological evolution. This explains how composites form naturally, not supernaturally.

Despite the numerous experiments, and even assuming the conditions in which they were preformed matched the conditions of the early earth (rather than favoring positive results), they all failed to produce life out of lifeless matter.

Composite things are not "caused by" simpler things, but "composed of" simpler things. For example, if a human being produces a teardrop, that teardrop is composed of things which are smaller and simpler than itself but it was certainly not caused by something simpler than itself. The claim made effectively argues that God is simple and practically powerless but that there are lots of him from which to make stuff. That's not the God of classical theology.

The argument from composition does not claim that God is "practically powerless," or that there are "lots of him." The argument in fact claims that the God of classical theism, who is absolutely simple, omnipotent, and one (singular), exists.
The claim made from an argument doesn't protect the argument from alternate or additional implications in it's structure.
The argument does not claim that composite objects are caused by simpler things, but that they are caused by simple parts being held together by some thing or things outside of the composite object.
Then that claim would disagree with physics, since the forces which hold such composites together are carried by the parts.
Max Tegmark's 'Mathematical Universe' argues that the foundational 'component' of composite things is mathematics, not God.
The proof from composition states that composite things are caused by, not composed of, God.
The universe and everything in it is part of an infinite cycle of probabilistic events.
This God is improbable when one considers the possibility of endless rising and fallings of forms and events from a quantum field.
Appealing to infinity is less parsimonious than appealing to a simple, unembodied mind (God). Therefore, it is an inferior explanation.
The language of disembodied minds is hugely problematic. It maybe an article of faith but it poses more questions than it lays to rest.
Unless examples are given of the insurmountable problems to the idea of a mind without a body, this objection amounts to nothing more than an argument from personal incredulity

Regardless of the questions that remain, 'disembodied minds' have less problems conceptually than for example 'infinite regresses' and 'uncaused contingent facts' do. Therefore, it is the superior explanation.

Cosmological arguments arrive at a God that is not shown to be necessary. One could posit any sufficient entity and it would be just as valid. Universe creating pixies that disappear after creating the cosmos are just as sufficient.
The Aristotelian argument from the Act/Potency divide does in fact show that a god meeting the formal definition of God, is necessary.
The Kalam cosmological argument commits the composition fallacy.

The fallacy would be to infer ‘The universe has a cause’ from the observation that everything in the universe seems to be caused by something else. But the question is whether ‘Everything that begins to exist has a cause’ (1st premise of the KCA) is more plausible than its negation. It has to be taken on blind faith that there could be uncaused finite entities, such as the uncaused universe. By no means would this assertion be more plausible than ‘God created the Heavens and the Earth’.

Cosmological argumentation is speculation in the entire lack of data. Any explanation may be proffered, but until there is actual data about the singularity preceding the appearance of our Universe, no explanation will always be better than any.
Consider two identical universes, one with God and the other without. If no distinction can be made between the two universes, then the existence of a deity does not hold any explanatory power.
This argument is incoherent, because it suggests one to think of two identical universes that are different from each other. It is impossible to be identical and different at the same time.
The posited consideration requires the assumption that we collectively understand enough about the universe to model its behavior in entirety.

Positing the existence of an otherwise identical Godless reality to show that God is not necessary in our reality is a circular argument. It requires the assumption that God is not necessary for all realities to prove that assumption.
This argument itself is a circular argument. It assumes that to show that God exists, one has to exlude from consideration all realities where God doesn't exist.

The argument involving two identical realities exemplifies that the claimed necessity of God, as well as claims that God is unnecessary, are bald and are presumed. To say God is or is not necessary requires more than lipservice. Since we can discard mere lipservice, we're left with the dilemma that each hypothetical universe is identical in all other respects. That means there's no experience or feature of reality that can stand to tell us the kind of universe we actually live in.
It is possible that the universe came into being on its own.
Before the universe existed, the laws of time, space, and causality may not have existed.
It is a completely speculative statement to say that the laws of time and space may not have existed.
If causality did not exist, the universe would never have been caused to exist.
The form of the parent argument contradicts itself. By explaining that the universe would not need a reason to exist, it gives a reason why the universe would not need a reason to exist.

Causality is not something that logically could fail to exist because it is an abstract concept like evil.  Evil is essentially that which opposes the all powerful being whether there is any manifestation of it or not.  The concept exists.  Whether it applies to anything is another matter altogether.

The cosmological argument rests on a premise that is unsupported: "whatever begins to exist must have a cause". This is an unsuppprted assumption. We know there are quantum particles pop in and out of existence with no known cause, and we know that natural laws break down at singularity. The universe began at a singularity so you can't assume laws of the current universe dictate its behavior. It may or may not be possible for a singularity to change state with no cause, so the argument fails.
The cosmological argument does not require a thing to begin to exist, but to exist at all.
Lack of knowledge of the cause of quantum particles appearing does not count as evidence that they are non-caused.
A vacuum is a very potent thing to create something. Modern physics shows that there could apear something out of vacuum.
A vacuum already implies the existence of space.

This claim cites a source that indicates that a high powered laser can create particles in a vacuum. The claim is saying that the vacuum is creating the particles. Non sequitur. The fact that power is necessary to create matter from energy should fill you with awe considering the amount of power used to create the universe.
Trying to explain the universe based on human experience alone is insufficient. At the time the cosmological argument began we had a very limited knowledge of how the world worked.
The laws of space and time did not exist before the universe was created, as neither space, nor time existed until the universe did.
This fact supports modal arguments that say the universe did not come into being on its own.

The axiom of logic that states that effects have causes that precede them in a chain of causation is independent of physical laws, and as such remains in effect regardless of the status of the universe.
We assume effects have causes because this is what we see. It is not an axiom of logic which allows us to assume a cause without providing a reason to do so.

We do not in fact observe all causes for all effects.  We do in fact assume causes for all effects because effects would be unintelligible/inexplicable without them (i.e. no reason, cause, or ground for them to be).  Accordingly, the law of cause and effect is necessary for intelligible science.  Therefore, it is appropriately an axiom of logic because without it the universe is unintelligible.
We have observed random events in the form of quantum mechanics. As we know random events exists, we know that there are events without a cause.
An event being random doesn't mean that it lacks a cause.
If events 1a and 1b are equally likely random events assuming event 1, event 1 may be considered a cause, but if a happens, that a happened, and b did not was not caused.
Quantum events do have a cause in the form of fluctuating fields and consistent, though imprecise, laws.
The causes of quantum events are partial, and insufficient to explain, or predict the event.

The universe does not need to be intelligible, and science does not need to be true. The evidence suggests that in general they are, and they have proven useful, but that science is convenient is not a logical argument that it exists.
If at any point nothing existed, then nothing would exist at all.
The universe could just be an illusion, i.e. it doesn't really exist.
In the entire history of observation there has never been an event that was not caused.
The problem of induction calls into question whether this means uncaused events have never or will never happen.
While this may be true, we cannot know it with certainty because we have not assessed every event that has ever occurred.
A steady state universe would also require a cause, or else be causeless.

If a creator of the Universe has always existed, it has existed in infinite time prior to the Universe. That which exists in the infinite past would need infinite time to reach the present, thus it never would.
"Infinite time prior" is nonsensical. It describes something that cannot exist, and is not a part of any cosmological argument.
God is typically understood to be outside time; to have created time. As such he has no beginning. He just is. See Psalm 90:2
Having God be outside of time requires us to have numerous assumptions on how that could work
It seems an event, even a thought, requires time. It's doubtful things of the scantest duration can happen or be caused to happen in a timeless ether.
The decision to create was co-incidental with the act of creation.

Using a Bible reference to support a cosmological argument seems incongruous. The Bible does not accurately describe the cosmos. In Genesis 1, the cosmos is water into which the sky is centrally placed, and two great lights are placed in the sky to rule day and night (the moon produces light).
Cosmological arguments commit the God of the gaps fallacy.

Any appeal to God as an explanation for some observation that lacks a scientific explanation is God-of-the-gaps reasoning. Therefore, no such observation can, in principle, support the existence of God, as it is likely that something just isn't well understood yet.

Any gap in understanding that is filled by God only creates a higher level gap - namely "How did God come to exist?" Using God to fill the gap is the equivalent of using "magic" to explain a process we don't understand.

In any explanation there is going to be something inconceivable, God is the better candidate for this position because when we accept God's powers then everything else becomes explainable but on naturalism we find inconceivable things all over the place.

God is also a better explanation than matter because God, being a supernatural being, has qualities which justify his inconceivable power to self-manifest and to be eternal. Matter on the other hand being inert and mindlessly subject to the laws of physics provides us with no reason to believe it is capable of generating its own existence.

The simplest matter, particles & the hydrogen atom didn't create themselves. They're organized energy. The force of gravity made the heavier elements inside stars. Some are inert, and some are very reactive.
God does not possess the qualities of something which was created because He doesn't have a beginning, He doesn't have moving parts and He is capable of manifesting His own existence.
A God which does not manifest in reality and is not evidenced by reality is indistinguishable from a God which does not exist.
This argument, while logical, is not commensurate with reality because there is in fact evidence of God's hand in the world in several phenomenona.

Mathematical improbabilities associated with the fine tuning of the laws of physics, the fine tuning of our planet and eco systems, and the immense unliklihood of mutations in genes leading to beneficial changes all provide data for which God is the best possible explanation.
While 50% of Americans still do not accept the theory of evolution, it is now also considered a fact by numerous national and international scientific bodies.
Thinking in probabilities, it is quite easy to understand how Earth ended up with life.

Routinely, people win state lotteries; it is in fact a common occurrence. While the odds of any one ticket-holder winning are astronomically against, as more tickets are sold, the chance that someone will win increases. There are trillions of planets in the universe, and as it happens, the right events happened to support life on Earth. Some planet(s) was bound to win, and it was this one (at least).

It is true that most mutations are not beneficial; some are harmful, many have no apparent effect, but occasionally some are good. It happens with sets of genes that have been mutating in parallel as well.
The evolution of wolves to dogs is beyond question.
This notion aligns with the fact that our DNA shows how all life on Earth is linked to together. While mutations are random, their selection is not.
The route of the laryngeal nerve in giraffes is powerful evidence of evolution.
This has been observed in the laboratory at Michigan State University.
This has been observed in bacteria that becomes resistant to antibiotics.
From a sheer volume of evidence standpoint, there is no other theory in science that even comes remotely close to having the the amount and variety of supporting evidence that evolution has.
There are hundreds of fossils of transitional species of hominids that preceded humans.

Perhaps a more valid statement would be to say there is no theory which has had more of its so called evidence turn out to be either false or an out right hoax. Furthermore no other theory has had its false evidence and hoax evidence remain in textbooks after being exposed to the extent that the theory of Evolution has.
Critique of Wells at talkorigins.

The above statement can be considered true only with a very sketchy use of the word evidence. That is to say if you lump hoaxs, evidence that later turned out to be false, and evidence which is used to argue for evolution but which is in actualoty is a non-sequitur as evidence then you can amass a large volume of "evidence".
This has been observed in the wing color of the British peppered moth.
Miracles healings, and the experiences believers have can be considered evidence of God's exist.
Believers automatically attribute things to God because they experience their life through that perspective. Subjective experience isn't reliable, trustworthy evidence.

All experiences are an aggregate composed of subjective experiences. If subjective experiences have no epistemological value then a collection of subjective experiences which we call objective experiences also has no value.

Believers in Naturalism also filter their experiences through their world view. They automatically attribute experiences to matter. The accusation of bias can just as readily be leveled at skeptics rendering it a meaningless claim.
A lack of an explanation is exactly that. It isn't logical to attribute everything unexplainable to God.

Intelligent design meets all the criteria required of a scientific explanation. Any argument which is capable of defeating intelligent design has unintended consequences if applied across the board. For example, it is claimed that Intelligent design is not a scientific theory because it invokes an unobserved force. Darwinian evolution also invokes an observed force.
This principle is too restrictive. It requires one not infer that God exists even if God does, in fact, exist and were putting forth every display of miracle to evidence that God exists.
The idea that scientific explanations eliminates God as the source implies that all God's work is inexplicable.
The same reasoning may be applied to a Naturalistic-Theory-of-the-Gaps rebuttal to the objector who has assumed without justification that there will be a future natural explanation of the phenomena.

Since the dawn of science, advancements continue to provide us with natural explanations for phenomena that only had supernatural causes before. At the same time, not once have supernatural explanations unseated scientific ones. Such a track record is plenty of justification for believing this trend will continue.
Supernatural explanations have unseated scientific ones in the cases of Eucharistic miracles.
There were no theories about miracles to overthrow.
None of the Eucharistic miracle claims provide the details of how they determined the the hosts were real flesh and blood, so we should take them with a grain of salt.
Supernatural causes are ruled out apriori in science and any and all evidence of the supernatural is ruled out by a kind of confirmation bias where any contradictory evidence is simply of ignored.

To accept this principle is to admit that one's lack of belief in God does not need to be based on a consideration of evidence. Instead, it implies one does not need to look at the evidence because, in principle, there can be no observation for which God is the best explanation.

Accepting Gödel's theorem is to accept the limitations of our knowledge, not our belief. Our belief can be founded on facts, mathematics, and beauty, as well as on provable evidence. Any proof that it is wrong, would invalidate our belief, but some beliefs, according to Gödel, are just that unverifiable.

Lack of belief derives directly from lack of sufficient evidence to make it appear likely to be true. Many atheists are former believers who came to the conclusion that the evidence does not justify belief.

To hold there is a lack of sufficient evidence for God implies one believes it is possible for there to be such evidence (i.e. observations for which inferring God as an explanation is not god-of-the-gaps reasoning). Therefore, one cannot hold to this and the initial principle that all inferences to God from observation are god-of-the-gaps reasoning.

It's possible for God to be the best possible explanation for observational data and if such data were present then to deduce God as a hypothesis would not be pasting a hole in science with God but rather arriving at God via a scientific method.
The ancient Greeks and Romans had Gods to explain many natural events they observed. Those Gods have been replaced by science.

Science has made an egregious philosophical error in claiming to have proven these Gods don't exist. There is nothing about understanding the physics of how the sky is blue that proves It's not an artistic choice on the part of God. Similarly there is nothing about understanding meteorology that proves there isn't an entity controlling these mechanisms.

Science may one day explain things that we currently have no explanation for other than "God did it," but science is equally likely to reveal new concepts and topics that seem inexplicable without God.
Past scientific discoveries have uncovered facts about the universe that are more difficult to explain without God.
The second premise of the Kalam cosmological argument, "the universe began to exist," was made more credible by the discovery of the Big Bang theory.
The numerous physical constants discovered by modern physics have made the fine tuning argument more compelling.

Even if true this claim does not disprove Gods existence because God by definition eludes the scope of science. Science could come up with a complete description of how the world is functioning, and the possibility still remains that God could have made it that way.
However, if true this would still undermine cosmological arguments as positive evidence for God, thus weakening the case for theism.

To say that science has explained some things previously attributed to God and therefore God is unnecessary for existence is a hasty generalization. Science would have to prove that God is not needed for the universe to exist before this argument is valid.
The claim that science will one day be able to explain the gaps is a post dated cheque. It's an empty promise.

The progress science has made in explaining the gaps can be compared to the progress Olympic athletes have made in extending human abilities. I could claim I'm going to jump over the moon one day, and I can give as evidence the fact that yesterday I was able to jump 2ft, and today I can jump 4ft therefore tomorrow I will jump over the moon. There is a limit to how high humans can jump, in the same way there is a limit to how much science can explain within a materialistic framework.

You wouldn't sell your house to someone and hand over the deed of ownership if they had given you a post dated cheque, so why should we believe the scientists when they say they will one day be able to explain how consciousness is produced as an epiphenomenon of matter, how life came to be, or how the universe originated?
The alternative is a homunculus fallacy, in which nature is explained in purely naturalistic terms, resulting in an infinite regress of causes.

An infinite regress of causes would result in a past-eternal universe and that concept runs contrary to observation. If the universe is dying, which is not controversial, it already should have died if it is the result of an infinite regress of causes.

It is reasonable to search for naturalistic explanations until a phenomenon is demonstrated to actually be caused by supernatural event. We have never observed anything to be caused supernaturally, we don't have the means to determine so, nor do we know if it is possible in the first place.

The premise "we have never observed anything to be caused supernaturally" may not be true. According to some religions, supernatural occurrences such as Jesus walking on water and Mohammad splitting the moon were supernatural events that were observed.

Saying we can’t know a supernatural event occured dismisses revelation a priori as a source of knowledge. It cannot be empirically verified (like all personal hypotheses), but it can be known through revelation. Infinite regresses however cannot be empirically verified either, so it would be inconsistent to claim on these grounds that it is more reasonable.

It is not reasonable to search for a naturalistic explanation for nature itself. Entities can be uncaused (or eternal), but not self-caused. A supernatural explanation for nature would be more reasonable.
One must demonstrate the absolute impossibility of an infinite regress of causality before dismissing it.
The simulation hypothesis holds that reality is simulated by an external being, and there is good reason to believe that such a being would be the classical God.
Within a simulation, origin notwithstanding, a non-human designer may be omnipotent, omniscient, for all intents and purposes omnipresent, and perfectly benevolent.
If humans can act as omnipotent etc., and humans are not gods, it would follow that gods would not be needed to explain various facts within such a simulation.

They would not be omnipotent (even restricting it to the simulation), by example they would not be able to bring an arbitrarily large number of beings inside the simulation, because of the limited computational resources.
As the laws of physics in the parent universe may be different from our own, and we do not know them, it is possible that our simulator's computational resources are not limited.
Humans already don’t know what precisely go inside their own complex simulations. There is no good reason to think it would be different for the designer who created our world.

Instead of thinking about the computer simulations, consider fictional worlds, which may be regarded as a sort of conceptual simulation. With respect to a story, the author is easily considered to be omniscient, omnipotent, omnipresent and timeless (outside of the time flow of the story).
This is begging the question. There is no reason provided to explain why a designer would be inherently benevolent.

God is God to me as Will Wright is God to the Sims; yet, even in that context, we'd be hard-pressed to call Mr. Wright omnipotent, omniscient, and omni-benevolent, even relative to the Sims themselves these attributes are vacuous.
They *may* be these things, but our universe does not appear as if it were designed or managed by one who is omnipotent and perfectly benevolent.
Kialo discurssion:     We exist within a simulated reality.
The entity simulating our universe is God (theological idealism).

There are three broad types of things that may be simulating our universe: a quantum computer in a universe such as ours (see Bostrom's ancestor simulation hypothesis), a classical computer in a classical universe, or a mind. We do not ultimately exist in either a quantum or classical computer, so we must exist in a mind.

An ancestor simulation or other simulation within a quantum computer would have to exist in a quantum world very similar or identical to ours.
