According to the law of indiscernibility of identicals, if our universe is likely simulated, then any identical universe is also likely simulated. So any quantum simulation must itself ultimately exist within a mind.

Rather, what would follow is that the world is equivalent to its simulation, and thus positing anything beyond the world to explain it would be unnecessary. Thus, it undermines the simulation hypothesis itself.

In order for a classical computer to simulate a universe it must contain as many states as the universe it is simulating, and thus be larger than it. A computer larger than our universe would be incredibly inefficient and impractical to build for any entity or civilization that isn't omnipotent. Therefore, we are not simulated in a classical computer.

A simulated universe could drastically simplify many aspects of the universe if the simulators were not interested in them; most stars could be modelled as perfect spheres with the properties expected of those stars without us being any the wiser.
A simulated universe/reality could be much smaller than the entire universe that we believe exists, such as a simulation of only our Solar System.
Even if we exist in some kind of a mind, there is no reason to call that mind "God".
Consciousnesses such as ours cannot be simulated in a computer, but only within another consciousness - a mind.
It is not likely that God would need a simulation of reality when it has the ability create reality.
The simulation could be created by a species not that much more advanced than humans.
Such a being wouldn't necessarily meet the classical definition of God (omnibenevolence, timelessness, simplicity, transcendence, immutability, etc).
Form fitting the term "God" to a system proven to exist does not make attached religious concepts of God true.
Any objectively provable "God" would disprove many if not most religious assertions about the nature of god.
Your mind of this moment, complete with memories, could have multiple instantiations over time or on different computers, with different owners or multiple owners. They are not the classical God.

It is hubris to suggest that only Omnipotence could simulate (or create) reality as we know it. It's possible that between man and God (should such exist) there could be any number of beings capable of such.

The simulation hypothesis seems to be untestable, which means it doesn't provide a reliable path to the truth about the existence of an entity simulating our universe, leave alone that this entity is God.

Any 'higher being' hypothesis is likely to be fundamentally untestable. If you take an ant after giving it all the training in the world, it still wouldn't be able to solve algebraic equations. For us to be able to test the existence of God we would need to be able to comprehend God's existence, which, for our brains, may well be physiologically impossible. Being untestable for this reason is not a reason to reject the hypothesis.

The only higher beings a human can meaningfully hypothesise are those they can comprehend well enough to describe the hypothesis, which suggests they should not be so incomprehensible as to be untestable for that reason. Hence, we can reject such hypotheses for not being well put.
The simulator would not have the personal awareness of each human being that the classical God has.

At least in the case of "personal awareness of each human being", if the simulator's mind is running on hardware comparable to what it's using to run the simulation, there's no reason it couldn't have such extensive knowledge.

The simulation hypothesis is currently a matter of debate itself. Evidence that its predictions from mathematics and theoretical physics are supported by observation is still missing, so it can't be used further than to claim "It may be a simulation". Even if it were true, the simulator might have finite computational resources, which would be incompatible with an omnipotent God.

There is no "good reason" to believe such a being would be the classical God. 
The statement also assumes the "classical God" in question is the Christian one,  (and not - say - the Hindu one), nothing suggests that humans are created in "his" image.

This argument is simply detracting from the semantics of the argument and not addressing whether the hypothesis actually supports the existence of a higher entity regardless of if it is regarded as a "classic God" or not.
In a debate over whether God exists, it's not mere semantics to point out that some nebulous "higher entity" is not necessarily God.
A very advanced civilization or computer programmer simulating us are not same as divine beings.This hypothesis does not give us good reason to believe in supernatural agencies or a classical God.
The simulation hypothesis is an independent hypothesis from the god hypothesis, and it does not support or detract from it.
The possibility of the universe being simulated has little to do with whether or not the simulator is 'God'.

Both hypotheses have far-reaching implications over an entire worldview if one believes in them, and for the hypotheses to be truly independent, those implications would have to (improbably) never interact.
This is conflating mutually exclusive hypothesis with independent hypothesis. Independent means one being true does not require the other to be true in order to be true.
The simulation hypothesis involves rationalising things outside the universe as if they were within the universe, there is no evidence to suggest this is valid.
Equally, there is no evidence to suggest that this is invalid, rendering this point moot.
There are good reasons to think a mind could not simulate a universe.

A simulation is a system that replicates certain desired features of another system without recreating it. A mind cannot replicate a system, but only imagine or consider one. Thus, a mind couldn't give rise to a simulation.
The observer effect implies that an uncollapsed wave-function could not exist in a mind.

All known minds are based in physical substrates, and there is good reason to believe all minds would be. Thus, suggesting a mind is simulating the universe only pushes the question back to an unknown universe serving as substratum to that mind.
Minds process information. But information requires some way to store it. A pure mind couldn't store information, as any stored information would entail something other than the mind.

If there is no God there is no rationality, there is simply a chemical reaction in your brain, if all that exists is material than if God didn't exist you wouldn't be able to know it. "Reason" is immaterial.
The assertion that reason is immaterial is completely baseless and is the entire basis for the argument here.
Even if reason were immaterial, there is no connection between this hypothetical immaterial reason hiding somewhere in our brains, and God, so this argument is a non sequitur.
Transhumanist arguments support the existence of God.
It is in the nature of all rational beings to perfect themselves. Therefore, God is probably a super-historical descendant of rational beings; or the ultimate expression of rationality.

The urge to perfect ourselves takes us to the uncomfortable conclusion that human goals are not commensurate. Should these be symbolized by the human mind, we will have the Gods as conflicting and warring psychological principles, rationality being but one of them. None of this is a cause for us to believe in an existing, non-mind dependent, God.

The suggestion that God is "probably a super-historical descendant of rational beings" is logically inconsistent. It would necessitate that, at some point, there was an authority superior to God, which would contradict God as being the ultimate authority and thus disqualifying Him as God.

Isaiah 44:6-8 describes God as "the first" and "the last", tying those two descriptives to His statement that there are no other Gods but Him, and then punctuating this statement with "I know not any." This suggests that God is, and always has been, without peer or superior.
Rationality is a product of evolution - our drive to survive to reproduce - we cannot infer the existence of any divine being from it.
Nothing falling under the label of "transhumanism" can be called God as the term is generally understood.

God is generally understood to be a supernatural entity; transhumanism is about technological enhancement of the human body, and technology in a naturalistic universe cannot produce supernatural effects.
We cannot know what technologies will emerge from a technological singularity, so for all we know it could very well produce supernatural effects.
Transhumanism and singularitarianism are different schools of thought, that are about different matters.

An ultimate expression of rationality - or an ultimate expression of anything for that matter - still has to give us a good cause for us to believe it is anything other than an abstract idea constructed in our minds.
Ontological arguments support the existence of God.
The logician Kurt Gödel formulated a modal ontological argument for God's existence.
Axiom 5 (Necessary existence is positive) is false, as modalities cannot have value, since they are purely descriptive. That is, it violates the fact/value distinction.
Descartes made an ontological argument for the existence of God.

Descartes was wrong, the fact that we can conceive of a perfect being does not make it real. Also his arguemnt is tautological, it asumes gods has certain charateristics and having such charcteristics proves he exists.
Version B of the argument has an fallacious conclusion. It should read is "Therefore, I have an idea that a supremely perfect being exists."
Version A of the argument makes the mistake of assuming that a person decides truth.
Existence is not a predicate. It speaks to the quantity of something rather than its qualities. That is, necessary existence is not an essential quality of anything.
This is not Descartes argument. He believed that the idea of the infinite could not be conceptualizable to the finite human mind. Therefore it had to have a source outside it. That source is God.

The ability to describe a thing, such as "a supremely perfect being," is not the same as being actually able to imagine or comprehend it. For example, I can describe "A perfect sphere with exactly sixty-three corners and eight faces," but I can't imagine or comprehend it. In the latter case, the thing I described is definitionally impossible. That's not necessarily true of the former, but it is the same kind of statement, and being able to make the statement isn't proof it describes a true state
The structure of the argument can be used to prove that any being exists. I can use the same argument to 'prove' that a universe creating meatball exists.
Properties can be contradictory, meaning that you cannot be maximal in both properties. As such, this argument is invalid.
"Maximally Just" is contrary to "Maximally Merciful".
Robert Maydole formulated a modal ontological argument for God's existence

The S5 axiom of modal logic states that necessary statements must be either true or impossible. For instance, if it can be shown that it's possible that 2x2=4 (such as by bringing 2 sets of 2 pebbles together and counting them), 2x2=4 must be necessary in all possible worlds, and thus true. God's existence is a necessary statement, so if it is possible, it must be true.

The definition of supremity used in the argument, that it is impossible for anything to be greater than a supreme being, is a necessary statement (since it contains the term "impossible"). If it is can be shown to be possible that it is impossible for anything to be greater than x, then it is impossible for anything to be greater than x, so a supreme being exists. Any supreme being would be considered God.
It is not known whether or not it is possible for a god to exist.
In the logical sense, anything which cannot be proved to be logically contradictory is "possible." It is known that God is not logically contradictory.

The first section of Robert Maydole's ontological argument, from the beginning to the 23rd step, proves rigorously that supremity is not self-contradictory, so it must be possible. This is all that's necessary for the rest of the argument to work.

The third assumption made in Robert Maydole’s Modal Ontological argument begs the question by failing to consider an assumption that would resolve the contradiction, and thus simply assume the conclusion.

In the PBC part of the argument, the contradiction arose between P([aS]) and P([a~S]). Since the original assumption was ?¬?x(Sx), we must consider that it is also ?¬P([aS]). If the contradiction could be resolved with this as a replaced premise (in place of premise 3), then the argument will fail. When you don't consider this at all, you assume that it is possible that a supreme being exists. I.e., you assume the conclusion and beg the question.
All claims require evidence. Saying "God is possible" is a claim. Since it has not been demonstrated that God is possible, the claim "God is possible" should not be accepted.

In terms of Platinga's argument it isn't sufficient to establish that God is logically possible. There are more constraints on the universe than logical or internal consistency, even if that internal consistency is that God is contradictory but still possible.
Although there is nothing logically impossible about an atom with 4000 protons, it is physically impossible.

There are counter-examples to the second premise made (?Y(P(Y) ? (Z)(??x(Yx ? Zx) ? P(Z))).

"Power tends to corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely." It would seem that a perfection (i.e. power) implies an imperfection (i.e. corruption). [1]

Absolute power is the only amount of power that does not corrupt at all, because one in absolute power has nothing to gain from abusing his power, only something to lose.

Example: If God exists, he would be considered to have absolute power, and also be considered to be the only perfectly un-corrupted entity in existence. However, the idea even works in relation to absolute monarchs, whose corruption was in general inversely proportional to the solidity of their reign.

Power corrupts not only in that it may be lost, or that one develops a thirst for it, although those are also factors, but in that it allows one to act unchecked. Consider for example how bored players in open world games often decide to play pranks, or outright murder the NPCs just because they can, an action that secures them no power.
The quote, "absolute power corrupts absolutely," is only an aphorism and has not been shown to be logically rigorous.
The Barcan formula (a crucial element of the argument) should not be accepted.
Alvin Plantiga has formulated an ontological argument.

A condensed version of Plantiga's argument:
(1 - DEFINITION) God is a being that either (a) exists in every possible world or (b) doesn't exist in any possible world
(2 - ASSUMPTION) Let's assume (b) is false.
(3 - CONCLUSION) Therefore (a) is true. This implies God exists.
It is unclear how a monotheistic God would be compatible with definition (1).
Hypothetical worlds in which the monotheistic God doesn't exist are trivially possible. Therefore the monotheistic God doesn't have necessary existence.
Assumption (2) is baseless. We could just as well assume that (a) is false, and conclude that God doesn't exist.
Beings cannot be defined into existence. It is possible that a being defined by (1) does not exist.

Plantiga's argument takes as a premise that if atheism were to be true, it would be true contingently, rather than necessarily. This is not certain and without this premise the argument simply shows the triviality that if something has necessary existence as part of its definition it either necessarily exists or necessarily doesn't.

A priori does not entail necessary. The parent assumes a priori arguments establish necessary conclusions in virtue of being a priori. This conflates a metaphysical notion with an epistemological notion
Necessity cannot be a great-making property, as it isn't a property, strictly speaking.

Given all the properties of some thing X, one can determine whether it is necessary, possible, impossible, or contingent by examining the two propositions "there is a possible world in which X exists" and "there is a possible world in which X does not exist". Based on the truth or falsity of the two propositions, the modal status of X follows.
If true-true, it is possible but contingent. If false-true, it is impossible. If true-false, it is necessary. (False-false cannot occur)
St. Anselm made an ontological argument for the existence of God.

Anselm's argument defeats the proposition that "just because it can be imagined does not mean it exists", due to the subject of 'being'. The greatest conceivable being not existing faces a blunt contradiction of its primary definition of 'being' vs a state of nonexistence.

The argument assumes classical Greek notions of causation; which are demonstrably false.  It has never been the case that a single cause has led to a single effect, and it is always the fact that multiple causes lead to multiple effects.
The syllogism's third premise--to exist is greater than to not exist--has issue.

"Greatness" is left ambiguous so as to equivocate its use to correlate the attribute of existence to the definition of God implicitly. Regardless of how greatness is defined, a thing is not intuitively better for existing--disease would be better as only an idea; fantasies no longer exist at all upon being realized, as by definition it loses its critical defining quality--and so the premise that "existing is greater than not existing" remains unsubstantiated.
Intuitively, something that is great already as a concept would become even greater by existing.

St. Anselm's proof (3rd premise) incorrectly treats existence as a property that can be predicated as part of a thing's definition; existence is better treated as a quantifier, as in first order logic.
One can imagine a being with all God's other properties, this does not make it exist.

The primal characteristic of an inconceivable being (that is, the being that results by thoughtfully pursuing the greatest conceivable being) is that it exists: that is the definition of a 'being'. Therefore, to Anselm's argument, imagining this being implies that it can, and philosophically does, exist.
The idea of 'A being greater than B' is not given a proper definition within the argument. Therefore it's unclear whether definition 1. is logically consistent or not.

It is not possible to imagine the greatest thing, because we can always imagine something greater than that, in the same way that it is not possible to imagine the highest number, because we can always imagine a higher one.

The claim falsely equates "maximal greatness", a qualitative measure, with "maximal magnitude", a quantitative measure. 

It is true that a maximal magnitude cannot exist, so we use the term "infinity" to represent this imaginary concept. However, maximal qualities can exist. There does exist a maximally great "blue"... a blue that is unadulterated by any other color.
Aquinas rejected Anselm’s ontological argument. He held that God’s existence is “self-evident in itself” but not “self-evident to us”.
The definition of God is not a being which nothing greater can be imagined.
God is defined as the ultimate being, this is not necessarily the same as the ultimate imaginable being

The greatest imaginable being would likely have all the properties included in the classical definition of God, so if the argument shows that the greatest imaginable being exists then it follows that it would be God.
That isn't the argument used in the proof, if the argument is changed, the proof is changed.
If God does not exist, and so is nothing, then we can easily imagine a being greater than God.
This proof would only support the existence of something that nobody could imagine something greater then, that thing need not be God in the traditional sense.

To follow Anselm's argument, God as a "being than which no greater can be conceived" undermines any ability for God not to exist. The primal characteristic of a being that is greater than which any other can be conceived is that it *is*. It's being is essential to its definition. Therefore, this being must exist.
Anselm's exact point is that any being that you can imagine as "greater than God" is, in fact, God.
Existence is not a property, let alone a better-to-have property. Things that exist are not better than things that don't exist.

Multiverse theory logically concludes with a supreme God. If all logically possible things are real, and it is logically possible to have a God over all the multiverse, then at least one multiverse contains the real God of the multiverse.
Classical theism traditionally involves the claim that God is necessary, which in modal language means existing in every possible world.
Claiming that some multiverse contains a god does not suggest that this multiverse contains a god.
God is a necessary being. Necessary beings cannot fail to exist in any possible world. Therefore, if there is a universe in which God exists, then God exists in all possible universes.

If there are universes in which God exists, there are universes in which God does not exist. It is impossible to know for sure which kind of universe we are in, and therefore this argument cannot be used to prove that there is a god in our universe.
God does not exist inside of the universe, but is transcendent to it. Therefore the conditions inside of any universe are not relevant to the question.

If all logically possible universes exist, all logically possible Gods exist. If all logically possible Gods exist, at least one of these gods would possess all the traits of the God of Classical theism, including existing in all universes.
This is a non-sequitur. Just because God exists in some universes, it does not follow that he does not exist in some universes.

If there are multiple possible universes, that does not imply that there are also multiple possible multiverses or that universes within a multiverse can interact in a way that supports a god of a multiverse.
If all possible universes exist, there is no reason to assume, that universes can't interact with each other. Theoretical models indicate that it's mathematically possible and therefore should exist.
Robust refutations of ontological arguments for the existence of God have reduced ontological proof for God to little more than the subject of parody.
Kant provided a refutation of ontological arguments.

This is how ontological arguments go:
(1) (Partially) define God as having certain properties.
(2) Use these properties and certain assumptions.
(3) Arrive at the conclusion that God as defined by (1) exists.
However (3) is not the conclusion that God exists in the actual world. A hidden assumption in the argument all along is that God defined by (1) exists. Therefore the conclusion is the mere tautology: if God exists, then God exists.

Kant's objection doesn't apply to Plantinga's modal ontological argument  since that version of the argument doesn’t assume that existence is a property or perfection. See Questions on existence and certainty and Kant’s Critique of the Traditional Arguments for the Existence of God

A condensed version of Plantinga's argument
It is implicitly assumed that the being defined by (1) is real.

Kant believed that we needed an intuition from the object to give us knowledge of existence, which the concept alone could never give. His claim that existence is not a property is based on his model of perception and experience, which is problematic in a number of ways and not widely accepted by philosophers in the present day.
Ontological arguments for the existence of God misunderstand the emptiness of the universe and ascribe that emptiness the name God. This is basically the Primitive Buddhist position.
Ontological arguments require that 'existing' is a quality that must manifest to be 'maximal'. That is to say that it refuses a concept being sufficient; it confuses the conceptual and the actual.
A quote from the same article claims that ontological arguments are not persuasive.

Ontological arguments go one step further than asserting the existence of something, and assert a relationship between that thing and something else. They are not an argument for any being's existence, rather an additional, equally unsupported claim about what that being might do in their spare time.

It is reasonable that in a finite material universe there are things that have the greatest properties among others. However it is impossible to conclude that "one" sentient entity is the owner of all this greatest properties.
None of the ontological arguments rely on or conclude with any action taken by God, or any relationship God has with a specific thing.

Any ontological argument offered in support of this claim, and this god, are being used in support of a number of assertions, not just about the existence of something, but its nature and its habits. This is a major distinction between deism and classical theism.

It is more parsimonious to assume that the God argued for in the ontological arguments is the same God concluded by the cosmological and teleological arguments. Therefore, we can reasonably conclude that the God of the ontological arguments did create the universe.

The ontological argument for the non-existence of God also exists. (1) If a God exists, it exists in every possible world (a premise from ontological arguments); (2) It is possible that God does not exist; (3) (from (2)) there is some possible world where God does not exist; (4) Therefore, God does not exist in every possible world; (5) Therefore, God does not exist
Premise 2 is false. Also the argument is logically invalid because premise 1 and 2 contradict each other, therefore the conclusion cannot follow.
Teleological arguments support the existence of God.
The complexity and precision found in nature and in living organisms indicate God's existence as the creator of all things.

If we apply inference to the best hypothesis to an attempt to explain the origin of the complex specified digital information found in DNA we find an intelligent mind is the only cause for which we have observational experience as minds are known to create information.
We know from our uniform and repeated experience that minds are capable of producing information.
DNA is a digital code where 4 nucleotide bases code for genetic information such as amino acid sequencing.
Observational data does not support the ability of random processes to produce information.

Inference to the best hypothesis is a scientific method used for historical sciences and employed by Darwin for his theory in which what we know from our uniform and repeated experience about cause and effect relationships is applied to events in the past in order to find the most plausible explanation.

The argument commits the black-and-white fallacy, also known as a false dilemma by claiming that either God or dumb luck created DNA (see the video), without justifying why these are the only possibilities.
Abiogenesis is one possible explanation for the existence of DNA that is neither random chance nor an intelligent creator.
Abiogenises is unfalsifiable because although there is currently no explanation how it occurred it can never be proven that future findings won't discover one.

It is often claimed that unfalsifiable hypotheses have no scientific value. Abiogenises should be rejected by those who use this argument to reject intelligent design because they are both unfalsifisble in the same way.
Both an accepted and a rejected hypothesis of abiogenesis holds predictive and scientific value.
Abiogenises theories have not made any predictions which came true.

Abiogenesis is falsifiable - all the possible reactions in historical conditions could be explored to conclude that there is no natural route. James Tour shows how given what we know now abiogenises is implausibe.
To the contrary, progress has been made in this area of research, bringing science slightly closer to the answer.

"Researchers at the Medical Research Council Laboratory of Molecular Biology reported that they had rewritten the DNA of the bacteria Escherichia coli, fashioning a synthetic genome four times larger and far more complex than any previously created."
Whether abiogenesis can be considered falsified only gives further support to the idea that abiogenesis is falsifiable.
This claim goes no where. If abiogenises has been falsified it should be rejected and if it is unfalsifisble it should also be rejected.
Abiogenises is a theory which has the evidence stacked up against it.
Abiogenesis is yet to be proven. We can make amino acids, but we have not yet demonstrated the mechanism for inanimate matter to become an animate cell.
James Tour shows how the complexity found in organic chemistry required for abiogenesis isn't possible by chance, even given massive time spans.
Tour's powerful arguments have gone largely uncontested. A few have attempted to debunk them but these are easily answered and don't even deal with his main contentions.
Dr. Lawrence Moran offers a detailed refutation of Tour's arguments.
Scientific consensus does not support the claim that "abiogenesis has substantial evidence of implausibility."

It is not reasonable to present the opinions of scientists as something which should be accepted like some kind of scriptural decree. Rather the logic, evidence and work of scientists should be presented and assessed for its own merit. To do otherwise is to commit the appeal to authority logical fallacy.

Social science shows how conformity causes intelligent people to do things and give answers they know to be wrong simply in imitation of the group. Scientists are human beings too and are not above this.

The video earlier presented assumes that the first life form was like a modern unicellular organism. We now know that the first life form was unicellular, RNA based simple organisms that were only able to metabolize and reproduce.
RNA organisms created in labs have only ever been able reproduce 10% of themselves.
Many viruses, such as measles are RNA based, yet are able to reproduce.

The reason why the video assumes that the first life form was like a modern unicellular organism is because there is no other life form we know of which is capable of reproducing its self. The idea that the first forms of life could have been simpler remains conjecture because there is no evidence indicating what these simpler forms could have been or if such a thing is even possible.
The intermediary steps suggested for the formation of the first life forms are little more than just so stories because they lack evidence behind them and lack detail.
Since there is as much evidence for God creating life as there is for abiogenesis neither one should be believed.
Claiming that position X is as good as Y and therefore Y is better is irrational.
This is not true as there is good evidence to suggest an intelligent mind created life.
We know that an intelligent mind can arrange matter in purposeful ways which would be impossible by chance.
Abiogenesis is likely.
The universe, due to it's gigantic size, has a lot of habitable planets, meaning that the chance of at least one having life is likely.
If you roll 6 dices, the possibility of guessing all of them right is 1 in 46656. But if you roll the dice 46656 times you are likely to guess correctly at least once.
The statistical modelling allows for the size of the universe and large time spans and still it's mathematically implausible for life to come about by chance.
A mind can create and increase information.
Evolution can increase information, and it is possible for natural processes to create information.
The black pepper moth is a good example of evolution.
God is the best candidate for this designer.
We know that a mind capable of producing life would need to be exceptionally intelligent.
We know that a mind capable of producing life would need to have immense power over matter.

We know from philosophy that a mind capable of producing life would need to be beyond space and time.
A mind which creates life would also create the world, it would therefore need to exist separate from the world and hence transcend matter.

Abiogenises is not an alternative to chance because it relies on chance.
A black and white fallacy occurs when a proponent of an argument states that there are an X number of possibilities without justifying why there aren't any other possibilities.
It has not been demonstrated that a theory exists for which chance is not a critical component, so the accusation of a black and white fallacy is empty.
Given appropriate conditions, complex information develops with high certainty given sufficiently long time.

Just because DNA and other types of digital codes share one thing in common, information, this doesn't mean they share something else in common, an intelligent creator. This is commonly know as the false analogy fallacy.

The accusation of a false analogy is unjustified. For it to be a false analogy the differences would have to be more significant than the similarties. This is not the case with the coded information in DNA and that produced by human minds.
A false analogy takes place when one asserts that since A and B have X in common, they also have Y in common, where A is DNA, B is a digital code, X is information and Y is a designer.
This is as invalid as stating that since DNA and other digital codes both have information and DNA looks like a ladder, therefore other digital codes look like ladders.
The way human cells work (and how DNA is copied) makes cancer possible. It is unlikely that god would intelligently create cells this way
Considering something as created, and therefore needing of a creator is begging the question circular thinking.
There are no known causes to explain 'the complex specified digital information found in DNA'. There are only hypothetical explanations, and more than one of those.
A mind is the only explanation backed up by observation. Minds have been observed creating information, natural processes have not.
Genetic mutations occur by breaking information not by creating it.
Genetic mutations come at a cost because they break information.
Estimates place the information contained in the human genome to only 4 MB. Algorithms produce novel digital information of greater complexity.
These algorithms don't mimic conditions which genetic mutations face.
The mutation selection mechanism can only select for functional advantage. Algorithms however, can select for changes which are closer to the desired result despite not offering any advantage yet.
Evolutionary algorithms almost universally select by fitness, i.e. functionality, not for closeness to a predefined code.
This video explains a simple evolutionary algorithm where selection is only on functional advantage.

The textbook Introduction to Evolutionary Computing defines a general schema for evolutionary algorithms with selection only on fitness, and provides two examples where fitness is defined from function.
The algorithm devised by Dawkins (1986) worked nothing like real evolution as it selected letter by letter, essentially having the entire sentence pre-specified. (P. 9, 2005)

Whether algorithms mimic conditions is irrelevant to the claim that "the only cause in operation which can explain the origin of complex digital information is an intelligent mind"; as the claim deals with how such information could develop, not the particular conditions of the early planet.
Said algorithms are produced by humans so such an example is further evidence for the need of intellegent design.
Whether humans initially implemented the algorithms is irrelevant to whether the only known process requires intelligent minds.
Machine-learning algorithms develop novel code and results which the original developers did not intend.
Algorithms are processes that exist independent of human minds. Human minds can discover them.
There are evolutionary algorithms which produce competent digital organisms with more information than the human genome.
This is the God-of-the-gaps argument, as it says " we don't know how DNA came to be, therefore God made it come to be." Also known as an argument from ignorance.

It's not an argument from ignorance in this formulation. It's an argument based on what we do know. It's an inference to the best hypothesis based on what we know about the cause and effect relationships capable of producing coded information.
A God of the gaps argument would be one in which the claim is merely that a natural process could not have done it therefore God must have done it without any additional evidence or premises.

A god of the gaps argument states that since we do not know of an alternative explanation presently, God must be the explanation. God of the gaps does not involve the much stronger antecedent of rejecting all possible natural processes.
In this form of the arguement an extra premesis has been added which states that we know intelligent minds are capable of producing information and we know of no other cause that has this capability.

The following claim of the Stephen Meyer is provably wrong: "If you're a computer programmer, you know that if you start randomly the sections of functional code, you're gonna degrade that long before you come up with a new program or operating system."
Genetic programming offers a domain representation of programs in which every random change yields a new functional program.
Error-correcting codes permit random changes to decode to functional programs, even if the number of such programs are relatively small.
Genetic algorithms involve random changes to programs which produce increasingly good programs as generations progress.

Life in our universe would be impossible if any of a number of laws, constants, and initial conditions were changed even unimaginably slightly. This implies the strong probability that the universe was created for the purpose of harboring life (fine tuning).
Several laws, constants, and initial conditions exhibit a high degree of fine tuning.
The initial entropy is very finely tuned.
The cosmological constant is finely tuned.
The gravitational constant is highly fine-tuned.
The relative strength of the electromagnetic force and gravity is finely tuned.
The universe's mass density is finely tuned.
The universe's expansion rate is finely tuned.
Some interpret biological structuralism to support a creator, as they argue it requires physical constants to be fine tuned to enable the life forms we see.

According to process structuralism, biological systems would be a bit like crystals, in that they're likely to form and propagate wherever conditions are right (instead of only in individual, random circumstances).
Given what is known of the conditions for life on Earth, it is not possible to definitively claim that life would not emerge if conditions were different.

Purpose-based inductive reasoning is useful. For instance, it is far more likely that a log cabin in the woods resulted from a man chopping down trees to build a home, rather than a series of nearby trees falling in a very specific pattern.
This is known to be the case because natural objects can be compared with objects that have been designed.
If all things were designed, the cabin would be a single cabin in a world of other cabins, and there would be no non-designed objects to compare the cabin to.

The existence of humans making such things as log cabins is common and not extraordinary. Thus, positing humans to explain a log cabin is not a large leap. Positing a supernatural being to explain certain aspects of the universe is not comparable.

The problem with this line of thinking is that you still need to explain where the human came from. The reason the log cabin was likely constructed by a man chopping down trees is because there is evidence of the existence of a man, but there is no evidence for the existence of a God.

Even if a structure was discovered in the middle of a desert which was thought uninhabited, or on an uncolonized planet, it is still more rational to conclude that at least one sentient creature lives there than that the structure formed by random chance.

The primary flaw in this argument is that we are trying to ascribe the existence of a partially complex object by claiming the existence of a significantly more complex being. This raises the question of the origin of the creator which is an infinite regress.

The parent claim is asserting that the universe needs a creator because it is finely tuned, not because it is complex. Thus, God being complex does not mean he requires a creator even if the parent claim is accepted.

Proposing an explanation for some data doesn't require an explanation for that explanation. When arguing that a certain death was a murder rather than an accident, one doesn't need to explain the murderer's diet, place of birth, and current living conditions before making the claim.

Why doesn't that explanation need an explanation? If one suggests that complex things need a creator, you need to explain why the creator doesn't need a creator, otherwise you have created an infinite loop which means eventually "something" comes from "nothing", thus circumventing the need for God at all as a possible explanation.

This analogy is not appropriate because there is irrefutable evidence for the existence of murderers, making the existence of murder a likely possibility and the origin of the murderer irrelevant. The existence of God however has not been irrefutably proven, hence the origin of God is key if the hypothesis that God exists is accepted without irrefutable evidence.

The classical God is a disembodied mind. Since the universe already contains at least 7 billion other minds, and has contained many more over its lifetime, God is clearly not significantly more complex than the universe.

Many religions consider God to be omniscient,  omnipotent and omnipresent. Each of these qualities requires the God to be at least as much and possibly significantly more complex than the universe which is predicted, controlled or embodied by God.
God as classically defined is perfectly simple. Knowledge, power and location do not require complexity if they are absolute and unchanging. God is not relative to the universe.

A hypothesis about (eg.) "a mind containing X amount of knowledge, which is magically perfectly simple" is necessarily more complex than a hypothesis about "a mind containing X amount of knowledge", so defining God as perfectly simple is only a further complication for all relevant purposes.

The initial conditions at the beginning of the Big Bang were much simpler, and are the true comparison when talking about the creation of the universe. Additional complexity that arose later was emergent, while God is supposed to be eternal.
The initial conditions at the beginning of the Big Bang were not simpler than the later universe, at least if "simple" is defined as "high entropy," because of the second law of thermodynamics.
The probability of a complex creator is much lower than the probability of a life-permitting universe with no creator.
The arguments related to the Ultimate Boeing 747 Gambit provides some insight into why a complex creator is less likely than no creator.

In terms of probability, P(life-permitting universe and sentient designer) < P(sentient designer) < P(life-permitting universe). Of course P(life-permitting universe given sentient designer) is very high, but we have not been given the existence of the designer, that is what the debate is about.

The relevant probabilities are P(life-permitting universe|designer) and P(life-permitting universe|¬designer). According to the Likelihood Principle, if the former is more likely than the latter, then that counts as evidence for the existence of a designer.

What we have for certain is a life-permitting universe, and we are estimating the probability of the designer. 
Let Designer be D and Universe be U
1. P(D|U) = P(D ? U)/P(U)
and 
2. P(¬D|U) = P(¬D ? U)/P(U)
since the P(U) term is common in both 1 and 2, the higher of  P(D ? U) and  P(¬D ? U) determines which is more likely.
formulating in terms of P(U|D):
P(D ? U) = P(U|D)*P(D)
P(¬D ? U) = P(U|¬D)*P(¬D)
P(U|D) >> P(U|¬D)  does not automatically lead to P(D|U) > P(¬D|U) if P(D) << P(¬D)
It's not obvious that P(D) << P(¬D), at least to an extent relevant to this discussion.
P(D), or more specifically P(D|k) where k is our background knowledge, is raised significantly by other arguments for God's existence, as well as historical and anecdotal evidence.
In the original claim U is considered to be  the same as K in this claim and therefore P(D) doesn't change because of any other information, they have already been factored into the formulation.

Given physical calculations involving the life-permitting ranges of physical constants, P(U|¬D) seems to be vanishingly small - so much so that any realistic prior value given to P(D) still works for this argument.

Just one initial condition of the universe - the mass and energy distribution of the singularity - is fine-tuned to a precision of 1/10^(10^123). No intellectually honest non-theist would claim that the prior probability of God's existence is significantly lower than that, especially considering that this mind-boggling improbability is raised multiplicatively with many other similarly large figures.

Even if P(U|¬D) is extremely small, considering that a designer is vastly more complex than the universe designed by said designer, P(D) is also extremely small, unless one believes in a designer of the designer, which then becomes an infinite regress. If D' is the designer of the designer, P(D) = P(D|D') + P(D|¬D'). Also P(D') = P(D'|D'') + P(D'|¬D'') and so on.

The Likelihood Principle only claims that the data counts as evidence - that is, it raises P(D) (and thereby lowers P(¬D), since P(D) + P(¬D) = 1 by the law of the excluded middle) - not that it necessarily demonstrates that the hypothesis is the more likely one, or P(D) > P(¬D).

Complexity does not necessarily reduce the chance of something simply existing without a creator. Informed theists argue that the universe was created not simply because it is complex, but for more specific reasons.
The traditional concept of God is not inherently complex.
An intelligent mind is complex, and God is supposed to be an intelligent being.

My existence in our universe would be impossible if any number of laws, constants, and initial conditions were changed even unimaginably slightly. Following the logic of the above statement, it would imply the strong probability that the universe was created for the purpose of harboring me!

The reason the above statement suggests the universe is created is that there was only one "shot" (an assumption) at the universe and we got one that supported life - ie that we were exceedingly lucky. Your version is clearly different because there were many opportunities to have you or someone like you. Once we assume the human race, unlikely individuals existing is very likely (it is unlikely anyone will win the lottery but people often do). The two are different cases.
As a member of the set of "life", the argument is expected to apply just as well to you as to any other creature or to life as a whole.
A theist would typically agree that the universe was made for the purpose of hosting you, in a sense, since God has an individual purpose for everyone.
We cannot calculate the individual probabilities of each combination of these parameters, so we cannot compare the probability of our universe to the other possibilities.

For example, it could be possible that the elementary charge of the electron had another value that the one we observe in our universe. But we have no way to know which other values it could have had, neither the individual probability of each of these values.
Knowing the exact probabilities is not necessary to intuit that they are very low.
Human intuition is not reliable for knowing about something that we do not have access to and have no idea about.

Suppose the universe was created for the sole purpose of creating life, our lives specifically. It is just as likely that humans, or some other race, advanced technologically far enough at some point in the future to crack time and dimension travel and go back before the Big Bang to make it happen ourselves knowing that we wouldn't ever exist without it, as it is that there is a God. We could be our own gods by creating a time-loop paradox. The fact is, there is no way to know yet.

The earth is 1 trillion cubic kilometers in volume, and humans live in is 298,000,000 cubic meters of that space. This means that humans live in 0.03% of the planet and that 99.97% of the planet is uninhabitable. If the universe was created for the purpose of harboring life, it would be better designed to do so. Almost all the universe is uninhabitable, almost all the world is uninhabitable, and until very recently, life was brief and painful.
Our galaxy is a very small portion of our universe, meaning that the majority of the universe is uninhabitable for humans. This suggests that the majority of the universe was not designed for life.
It doesn't matter that most of the universe is uninhabitable; what matters is that the habitable portion is large enough to support humanity.

This misunderstands the parent claim. It doesn't just say that the conditions appear "fine tuned" specifically for Earth, but that a small change in the constants would render 100% of the universe uninhabitable. The fact that we can live anywhere at all in the universe requires explanation.
It's possible that the constants actually have only one possible value, which would mean the universe couldn't be tuned for life or anything else
As far as we know, the universal constants are constant. There is absolutely no evidence to suggest any other value is possible. Therefore, variations are not probable

Asserting that variations are not probable because we are aware of no evidence to suggest other possibilities is a non sequitur. One could as easily say, "We have no evidence to suggest that the universal constants must necessarily have their known values, therefore variations are probable." 

Neither position is warranted.

The possibility of having only one possible set of constants does not imply the plausibility of such a universe. We have no warrant to reject the possibility of other values for these constants without evidence that such a constraint exists.

The initial quantities of the universe, such as the mass/energy distribution and the entropy of the singularity, are also very finely tuned - but there is no obvious reason to believe that the contents of the universe could not have been different.
The constants referred to are dimensionless, meaning their value doesn't depend on any other value or measurement. It's unclear how these values couldn't be different.

No argument has been given for the logical impossibility of a different set of physical laws. In the absence of such an argument, our default assumption should be that since a physically different universe is conceivable, it is possible.

This does not refute the finely-tuned relationships between the constants that are required support life. In fact, with only one chance to get it right, the fact that the universe supports life would be even more miraculous.
Life adapted to fit in the environment, rather than the environment being made for life.
Life could still have adapted to differences in the universe.

There are other known sets of laws of physics congenial to life, that have significant difference to our own, including ones with an entire fundamental force missing and these lie in the tiny region of laws of physics we're able to conceive of and simulate.
DNA, RNA, and proteins made up of the top four most common elements in the universe, excluding noble gases, meaning life used what it had available to be made.
People are bad at understanding probabilities, and this is formalised as the Lottery Fallacy. The chance of me winning the lottery is astronomically small, but every week or so someone has a big win.

The problem of fine-tuning isn't based on popular understanding of probability, but on formal probability such as the Likelihood Principle and Bayes' Theorem. See here for an in-depth explanation of the logic behind it.
The fine-tuning argument carries the implied proposition that the universe is designed for life to exist, rather than assuming that life exists as a result of adapting to the universe.
With an infinite amount of time (including whatever existed before time started), and an infinite number of universes, even low probability events become quite likely.
Claims that derive conclusions from infinite time and space are indefensible and overly dependent upon unverifiable assumptions.

An unlikely event still requires a mechanism. Infinite time is only useful in having monkeys compose Shakespeare if the type writers have ink or if the moneys are bashing keys. There has never been a demonstration of how proteins could form before any protein existed.

It's not neccessary for life to be based on proteins, esspecially in world which would be different from our. Therefore for any universe's laws / constants etc. there could be some matter, which could create life.
This is shear speculation as there is no observational data to suggest it to be true.

Our organism is functioning on a basis of really probabilistic mechanism since cells are moving quite randomly and when they randomly appear in good place certain procces happens. It is somehow controlled for avoiding critical conditions and aiming good ones, but it's still higlhy probabilistic. Therefore even highly complicated mechanisms could work on probabilistic basis.

This con doesn't address the parents assertion that random chance can only bear fruit where a mechanism exists to throw the dice so to speak and that there has been no demonstration of how a protein could form before any protein existed.

The probabilities that govern biological systems sit within the range of likely events given the odds involved and the frequency and volume of opportunities for them to occur. This is converse to protein forming before protein existed which is neither statistically likely to occur, nor is there any explanation of how it could have a mechanism to arrange the proteins.
The process of the first formation of proteins was first explained over 50 years ago.

The universe is so unimaginably immense, has existed and will exist for such a huge amount of time that it's not statistically impossible for the conditions for life to exist at least at some point of the universe, at some period of time.

The argument from fine-tuning isn't concerned with the likelihood of life existing within the universe, but with the likelihood that the universe would exist in such a way that it permits life at all.
There is no contradiction between believing that the universe was fine-tuned to permit life to exist and that life arose naturally within the universe and adapted to its environment.

The fine-tuning argument's conclusion that the universe was created to support life is what is contradicted by the idea that life exist by the sheer size of the universe, and ability of natural adaption to occur.
The purpose of the universe is the conclusion of the fine-tuning argument, not any of its premises.

The fine-tuning argument refers to constants and quantities that, if changed, would not allow for the formation of stars, matter, or complex chemistry, or else would result in near-instant heat death or collapse of the universe. It's clear that no universe such as these could support any form of life.

The origin of these physical constants and the origin of the physical forces they apply to is unknown, there could be a common as yet undiscovered constant or variable controlling the values of these constants which can explain fine tuning without resorting to God.

The fine tuning could stem from the theory of multiple/infinite daughter universes posed by quantum physics: there could be a universe with any configuration of forces, and the chances are one of these would have the correct values for our observable universe to exist as it does, as unlikely as it is
This assumes that the values of the fundamental forces are assigned probabalistically, of which there is no evidence
This assumes that the daughter universes theory is true, which has no evidence

Arguments hinging on evidence that may be discovered in the future are exceedingly weak. The claim could be made that it's possible we'll discover a faraway planet with the entire New Testament carved into its side, so God almost certainly exists. We can't investigate arguments like these because we don't have the hypothetical evidence in front of us.
Although a shared constant may lessen the amount of fine-tuning required, it would not eliminate it, since such a constant would itself be arbitrary and thus need to be finely tuned.

Our current understanding of physics partially supports this claim, however our current understanding is incomplete and physical behavior if the constants were outside the goldilocks zone can only be extrapolated based on our incomplete understanding.
Fine-tuning arguments can be explained via multiverse theory, without resorting to God as the source of order.

Multiverse theory attempts to resolve the origins of the universe by allowing random chance to compensate for the lack of a creator, but it fails to explain the source of the multiple universes. The question of a creator still remains.

Multiverse theory and anthropic reasoning can successfully explain why the laws of nature permit living beings to exist, but cannot explain why the laws of nature are so simple and elegant, since the vast majority of possible worlds with intelligent beings have extremely convoluted and arbitrary natural laws.
We only know about our own universe and therefore have no frame of reference for how simple and elegant our universe is.

Other sets of natural laws are conceivable, and those are often very complex. This is all that's required for them to be considered possible worlds under modal logic, which serves as our frame of reference to judge this universe.
if they are conceivable they are presentable, and they have not been presented.
Intelligent life living in a universe with less elegant and more arbitrary laws could just as well ask why they lived in a world with that specific arbitrary set of laws rather than another.

If an infinite multiverse existed, then not only would implausible beings like Santa Claus and the Easter bunny exist, but so would every pagan/animist god and goddess. Therefore not only is a multiverse lower probability than virtually every religion, but belief in it entails beliefs in gods.
Pagan gods existing in causally disconnected universes are irrelevant to our lives, and as such their existence can be safely ignored.
Some of these gods may be very powerful and able to travel to different universes such as ours.
Depending on how disconnected they actually are, if they have followers in this world, they are influenced by these Gods, and warrant attention.

Santa Claus and the Easter bunny are only implausible within our universe. Their existence in other universes, where they may be perfectly plausible and probable, doesn't count as evidence against the multiverse theory.
No system has been proposed that would result in randomized laws, constants, and quantities in a multiverse.

Although pseudo-random events seem to be common within our universe, due to unpredictable events and chaos theory, this would not apply outside of our universe without a similar system in place. We can't assume that randomness is the default state without reason.
Perfect randomness may be a concept that could only exist within a mind.
There is no theory in physics that explains how physical laws themselves would change or come into being, and so we have no basis on which to assume that this would happen at random in a multiverse.

It could be argued that this would be outside of the jurisdiction of physics, since physics deals with the results of physical laws, not the laws themselves. No amount of understanding of physics can conclude *why* physics exists.
By contrast to the multiverse, the god of classical theism would have the means to create and change physical laws due to its omnipotence.
The low amount of life found in the universe so far suggests that it is not particularly hospitable to life.
That the universe should be so vast while also being so uninhabited, argues against there being a god. If God exists, there should be more life, or less universe.
The universe could be so vast so that the life that is there has a place to grow into.

The vastness of the universe is almost exclusively gulfs of space that are so vast that as far as we know we may never be able to traverse them. This is not an environment suited for life to "grow into".
We don't have a good grasp on how much of the universe is inhabited.
The space we consider as empty may be bursting with life in parallel dimensions.
We know that we haven't found life anywhere we've looked for it, and have looked in a lot of places.
We don't yet have the technology to say with absolute certainty that any given planet or moon is lifeless, especially outside of our solar system.
If there is life there, it's nowhere near the level we are at.
The technology of an alien civilization may be unrecognizable to us.
A creator may not specifically prefer civilized technological life.
From this, one would necessarily conclude that God hates us. Although it seems consistent with other information, it's not a popular position.
It's unclear how not having a specific, individual preference for something necessarily implies hatred.
I don't always prefer pizza to burgers or vice versa, but that doesn't mean that I hate either or both.
We don't yet have the technology needed to detect civilizations like ours from interstellar distances.
To date we have only discovered fewer than 4,000 exoplanets, which is a minuscule number compared to the expected amount.
1 in 4000 is a speciously low hit rate for a god.
The universe being so vast and relatively uninhabited is not an argument against God's existence. At best it is an argument that you would have created the universe differently than God did.
The universe may be infinitely large and contain an infinite number of inhabitants.
We can destroy all life on our planet. If God favors life, He would not keep all eggs in the same basket.
If the universe has an infinite number of inhabitants, there couldn't even conceivably be any more. A God who only prefers a large number of inhabitants would therefore be satisfied.
There are levels of infinity, some are quite bigger then others, for example, the set of real numbers includes the set of natural numbers.
Uncountable infinity cannot be reached from countable infinity by addition or multiplication, which is what would occur if the density of creatures in an infinitely large universe increased.
Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel shows that adding to or even doubling the number of inhabitants filling an infinitely large space doesn't actually increase that number.

Uncountable infinity refers to sets that can be separated into infinitely smaller amounts, such as the set of all rational numbers between 1 and 2. It doesn't apply to counting whole entities, such as living inhabitants of a universe.

This doesn't apply to all infinities. For instance, there are as many even integers as there are all integers, because the even integers are defined as being any integer multiplied by 2 - despite it intuitively seeming as if there should be only half as many even integers.
The presented example does show the problem of density, the number of even integers is clearly less dense then the number of all integers.
Certain measurements imply that the curvature of the universe is flat, and a flat universe would likely be infinitely large.
If the universe is Euclidean, which is the simplest shape that fits with its flatness, then it is infinitely large.
All a flat universe implies is that it is expanding in different places. It is still finite in size from moment to moment.

The world is flat enough that we can, for almost all purposes, treat it as flat, but is still a sphere, it's just really big, this is how integers work, by dividing the data up until there is local flatness, the same thing could be true of the universe, we might just be to small to see the curves.
Curvature gets smaller at smaller scales, but doesn't disappear completely. This doesn't fit with the data - namely, that absolutely no global curvature has been detected in the universe.
The data may not be precise enough to answer this question.

The universe is not infinitely large. It is expanding at the speed of light, but it not infinite. We know this because we know that at the time of the big bang, all of space and time was limited to a single point.
The size (infinite or finite) of the universe is currently unanswered by cosmology. It hasn't been proven by the existence of the Big Bang.
Even if the universe had an infinite number of inhabitants, that would not explain the lack of density of life.
The universe does not appear to be fine tuned for life. It appears to be better tuned for making black holes.
In the context of this argument a hospitable universe is one that supports life, not necessarily produces life.

The anthropic principle observes that, for conscious beings to wonder about the possibility of their existence in the universe, conscious beings must exist in the first place. Therefore, asking such a question is pointless because the fact of asking it implies a positive answer.
The many-worlds interpretation may be real, and, by the anthropic principle, would explain why we observe a universe like ours.
The many-worlds interpretation relates to quantum interactions within our own physics, and contains no mechanism for different physical laws or constants to arise.
The universe may be cyclical or branching, and that, by the anthropic principle, would explain why we observe a universe like ours.
The multiverse may be real and, by the anthropic principle, would explain why we observe a universe like ours.
Even in a multiverse scenario, it still needs to be explained why values for these constants that are life-permitting are actually possible.

Leslie pointed out that some of the finely tuned constants must each satisfy multiple constraints to have a life-permitting value, and it is highly coincidental that for each constant, these constraints all "line up," being completely satisfiable by a single value.

The anthropic principle doesn't explain why we observe not just a universe that can be observed, but specifically one where scientific study of physics is possible and fine tuning can be observed. A universe with observers would still be unlikely to have this latter trait.
The laws of physics are simple enough to apply in practice.
If the laws of physics were not stable over time, physics would be much more difficult.

If the universe was chaotic enough that the scientific study of physics was impossible, theists would attribute humanity's continued existence despite that chaos to the grace of God, rather than inventing "fine-tuning"; thus an argument for God's existence that ignores the anthropic principle would exist either way.
The anthropic principle doesn't have any explanatory power.

The ability to ask a question doesn't factor into whether the question is meaningful. I can ask why my parents got together, even though if they hadn't I wouldn't be able to ask such a question - there is still a meaningful explanation for their getting together.

The anthropic principle wouldn't explain why any particular parents got together to produce a particular child, but it would explain why the necessary preconditions were met for someone to be present to wonder about their origination.
The fact that we can know a certain event happened only gives us certainty that it happened, not why it happened. The latter is what the fine-tuning argument is concerned with.
"Why do I observe the sort of universe I do?" is answered by the anthropic principle. Namely, that if the universe were significantly different, there wouldn't be anyone to ask the question.

The anthropic principle, when used correctly, only applies to scenarios where there are many possible spaces observers could occupy, but only a few wherein observers could actually come to exist/survive. For instance, it's pointless to wonder why we find ourselves on a planet with liquid water, rather than another planet - if there were no liquid water, we couldn't exist. The same doesn't apply here, where no probability spaces other than our universe are known to exist.
If the universe is a one-off event, it is not coherent to apply probabilities to it, as it is incoherent to apply probabilities to one-off events.
There are good reasons to think there may be other universes.

The anthropic principle explains why we observe a universe capable of supporting our existence. If the universe had not been capable of supporting our existence, we wouldn't observe it. Thus, it has some explanatory power.
The anthropic principle (at least in a single-universe model) does not mean that fine tuning requires no explanation.
In the analogy of Leslie's Firing Squad, one finding out that all the bullets missed and one is still alive does not make it irrational to wonder whether the marksmen missed on purpose.

In the case of us and the universe, "still alive" isn't an apt analogy. The analogy is more akin to our mother being put in front of the firing squad before we were born. Then, our existence requires that she survived.

The argument claims something that is simply not known. We have only one universe and we only know a very small part of it. We simply don't know what life would look like in a universe different than ours. It is an argument from ignorance to say that life would be impossible if the constants were changed.
It is reasonable to say that, given everything we know about life, it would be highly improbable if molecules or atoms couldn't exist.
As there is only one universe we will ever know about or examine, no notion of probability can be applied.

Probability requires some notion of the distribution of the relative probabilities of the possibilities. Yet with only one data point (the universe as we know it) no justified estimate of the probability distribution can be educed and thus no justified estimate of probability can be made.
Probability requires comparing against a space of alternative possibilities, yet we have no way to know that there are or could be alternatives since there is but one universe.
Alternative possibilities do not have to have actual existence or potential for probability to be relevant.
In a deterministic universe, if a coin comes up heads the possibility that it could have come up tails does not actually exist, and yet it is still meaningful to apply probability to coin flips.
We can create simulated universes. One can argue that we have already simulated very simple simulated universes through cellular automata.

Conway's game of life shows that life like phenomenon can emerge from radical different "laws of physics". The hostility of similar laws to our own in no way extrapolates to laws distinct from our own. As such it's possible that most laws pass the level of congeniality to life, and we just exist in an island surrounded by hostility.
Even if more than one life-permitting set of constants exists, they are still vastly outnumbered by non life-permitting sets. Thus, this does not help much to explain fine tuning.

Proving the universe has a purpose or was "maximized by some agent" does not prove the existence of a classical theistic God. It merely proves the existence of "some agent", which does not need to be God, or that the universe has a purpose.
An agent that can maximize some quality about the universe would have to be transcendent and enormously powerful, if not omnipotent.

Arguments for design or the watchmaker analogy are fallacies. Human design, which is the only design we know of, is inspired by nature and uses natural phenomenons. It's a sophistry to then conclude that nature is designed.

The watchmaker analogy was a particular design argument, not a general category under which all design arguments fall. Even if it is fallacious, it doesn't follow that all other design arguments are fallacious too.

The DNA structure within a living organism reads as a highly complex computer code of four chemicals ordered and structured for specific instructions to the cell. If source code requires a coder and DNA is a source code, then DNA had a creator.

The similarity of DNA to computer code is a simile, not a metaphor. Hydrogen and oxygen combine chemically in ways that cannot be realized using computer code, and thus chemical reactions cannot be used to conclude that God exists as a programmer or creator of DNA code.
For all known models, it is almost impossible for life through natural processes to have originated and evolved in only four billion years.
The prevalence of DNA sequences which code for functional proteins is estimated to be 1 in 10^64. This creates a search space too large for mutations to navigate in amount of time earth has existed.

Multiple mutations may take place simultaneously in different parts of the DNA, largely independent of each other, thereby reducing the number of generations required to observe the complexity or perceived sophistication of modern DNA.

This implies that random mutations occur with a uniform distribution across the available search space. It is reasonable to expect that environmental conditions accentuate which changes are likely to be occur, thereby reducing the breadth of mutations that will be observed to take place.
This is an argument from personal incredulity.
Genetic evidence and numerous fossils have been found and dated which corroborate the current theories of the origin and evolution of life starting around 4.5 BYA.
Though almost impossible to occur on a lone planet, it was inevitable to happen eventually.
The universe, as known now, is at least 11 billion years old and estimated to be almost 14 billion. This gives life a lot of time to appear in the universe.
There is around 10^24 planets in our observable Universe and possibly more in our unobserved universe, up to infinite, increasing the overall chance of life eventually occurring.
While we still don't know how life began, evolution is 100% proven and accepted as a scientific consensus.
Macro evolution is not proven, only micro evolution. To consider micro evolution proof for macro evolution is an unjustified extrapolation.

The overwhelming majority of possible gene mutations would offer no benefit, some of which would be deleterious and the vast majority of which would be nearly neutral. This makes it incredibly hard for random mutations to offer benefit.
That just means evolution would take a long time to offer benefit, which it does.

Evolution is about the chance that a gene gets passed on. The chance means that if a species had a population of ten, had a 1/4 chance of surviving to adulthood, and had an average of four children, a gene that increased its survival to 1/3 would take an average of three generations before it means only one more offspring would survive to adulthood than usual.
This is one of the reasons why we evolved sexual reproduction, which produces more variation between generations and in a less deleterious fashion than mere random mutations.
Macro evolution faces major challenges as there are numerous examples of mutations having a limit to how far they can go before they become detrimental.
Evolution is not for the maximum, it's the bare minimum. Yes, mutations may or may not be detrimental, but once they become beneficial, natural selection then gets to act on it.

It's generally thought that natural selection acts on isolated traits however natural selection acts on organisms not on isolated traits. This limits the ability of natural selection to select for traits because organisms have many traits and the combined impact of the other traits likely has more impact on the fitness of an organism then any single trait.

This also means if an organism had multiple good traits and its brother had multiple bad traits, the first would be even more likely to have offspring than if it were just one trait. This would also mean when the second dies, more than one bad trait becomes less likely to reproduce.

The selection process for applications to a mathematics course must act on students, not traits like mathematical ability, but we would nevertheless find that students at a highly competitive maths course are much better at maths than the average person on the street, suggesting that this kind of limitation on selection processes is not very limiting.

Michael Bergmann (p. 4-5) successfully explains how a person's belief can be justified through nonpropositional evidence, even if all the propositional evidence is against them.
