P(S|T) / P(S) is not much more than 1 (i.e. true positive beliefs are not much more likely to be selected for than positive beliefs in general).
There is a correlation between true beliefs and survival-producing behaviors. Therefore, true beliefs are more likely to be selected for than false beliefs.
Intuitively there are many situations where incorrect beliefs lead to unsatisfactory behaviors.
A hunter-gatherer picking berries in the woods who ate a berry, falsely believing it was not poisonous, could not make the same mistake twice.
A baseball player who held incorrect beliefs about where the ball was would have a very difficult time successfully hitting a fastball (skeptic.com).
A surgeon with incorrect beliefs about human anatomy and disease would make life-threatening mistakes during surgery (skeptic.com).
Stephen Law argues that "conceptual constraints" link survival-producing behaviors with true beliefs more strongly than with false beliefs.

This argument assumes a logical connection in the brain between beliefs and behaviors. Evolution has no reason to favor brains whose beliefs are logically connected to their behaviors. It only cares about the behaviors.

A brain structure where seeing food when hungry triggers the true belief that eating is required to avoid starvation and the behavior of eating the food is no more likely to be selected for than a brain structure where seeing food when hungry triggers the false belief that trees are lizard people in disguise and the behavior of eating the food.

Language (e.g. English) is a stimulus-belief-behavior relationship and process that cannot be implanted by evolution. As most people learn a language and communicate with others, it follows that beliefs and behaviors must be related in at least this case. As we have no reason to consider this a special or anomalous case, it follows that stimulus, belief, and behavior must be related.

There is a true sense in which behaviors are caused by beliefs. My belief that my child is endangered (e.g. I hear it's frightened cry) causes me to try to protect it (I don't yet know what I need to do to protect it (maybe defend it, maybe heal it, maybe carry or lead it away: whatever is needed). P(T|S) = P(T) * P(S|T) / P(S), where: P(T|S) = probability that a positive belief is true, given it was selected for; P(T) = probability that a positive belief is true; P(S|T) = probability that a positive belief is selected for, given that it is true; P(S) = probability that a positive belief is selected for.

This implicitly assumes that evolution selects for specific beliefs, i.e. that we are born with a hardwired list of things to believe are true. This is very unlike how human brains developed, and very unlike humans, so is not relevant to human rationality.
P(T) is very low (i.e. the vast majority of possible positive beliefs are not true).
For every true positive belief about a topic, there exist a vast number of false positive beliefs about that same topic. Thus, the vast majority of possible positive beliefs are not true.
There is one true belief about the number of states in the United States (50), but many false beliefs (1, 49, 309612, 4, 80, etc.).
There is one true belief about the Earth's shape (the Earth is [roughly] spherical) and many false beliefs (the Earth is flat, the Earth is cubic, the Earth is a truncated icosahedron, etc.)
Some true beliefs only have one corresponding false belief (e.g. "Penguins exist" vs. "Penguins do not exist").
Therefore, P(T|S) is low (i.e. the probability that a positive belief is true, given that it has been selected for, is low).

This argument assumes that evolution selects for individual beliefs; insofar as our cognitive faculty is about our ability to gain new beliefs, true or false, by interacting with the world, this argument toes not relate to our cognitive faculties.

There are many forms of teleology, including notions like purpose and meaning but also directedness, about-ness, representation, intentionality, function, final causality, and tendency, each of which may be utilized in independent and mutually reinforcing teleological arguments.
Teleological arguments are god-of-the-gaps arguments. This makes them a kind of argument from ignorance.

Some things have meaning, order and design. Many things do not. The teleological argument for God's existence makes the mistake of assuming that the traits of some objects must belong to all objects. That assumption is not justified.
That the universe has purpose is the conclusion of the teleological arguments, not one of their premises.
Most teleological arguments neither assume nor require that all objects exhibit teleology.
Arguments from intentionality require only the existence of intentional representation, not other forms of teleology, for their premises.
Arguments from consciousness require only the existence of consciousness, and not of other instantiations of teleology, for their premises.
Arguments such as the Fifth Way argue merely on the basis of any observed teleology that the ultimate, transcendent ground of existence is intelligent.

Such arguments need not be independently conclusive about the existence of God, but rather may function as part of a series of arguments for predicating divine attributes to whatever is at the foundation of existence.
Just because we don't know if certain things have meaning, order or design, doesn't mean they don't have one.

A purpose (the central pivot of teleology) is a purely man-made concept that doesn't exist per se, apart from how we see and define things. By definition, a purpose is something one wants to achieve, so the definition alone presupposes a conscious agent, making teleological arguments circular. Simple examples: a clock or a book has a purpose because it is man-made (made to achieve something); a rock or the moon don't since they didn't come about to achieve something.
Teleological arguments based on the existence of specific things are nullified if natural explanations are discovered for those things.

Charles Darwin refutes the Teleological Argument. "The old argument of design in nature, as given by Paley, which formerly seemed to me so conclusive, fails, now that the law of natural selection has been discovered."

Richard Dawkins refutes the Teleological Argument. "Natural selection is so stunningly powerful and elegant, it not only explains the whole of life, it raises our consciousness and boosts our confidence in science's future ability to explain everything else"
The assertion that science will one day explain everything cannot be disproven and is therefore not a scientific claim according to many.

The mutation selection mechanism lacks the power to generate novel organs and body plans. This short comings in this theory are widely acknowledged by leading evolutionary scientists rendering the ideas presented above a myth and misinformation. youtu.be
Appealling to intelligent individuals as an argument is a logical fallacy known as an appeal to authority.
Saying that an argument is valid because an intelligent individual makes it is a logical fallacy. Citing an argument made by an intelligent individual is not.

The Theory of Evolution doesn't cover the entire scope of the teleological argument.  Arguments like fine-tuning via the cosmological constant or nuclear force, the strength of gravity etc, cannot be answered by evolution, because evolution has organized matter as a presupposition, but without these features, there is no organized matter.
A creator God could have planned the use of mechanisms such as natural selection in order to get the intended result. Thus the discovery of natural selection does not fail the argument of design.

Many teleological arguments are from the complexity and diversity of life. These arguments have been disproven by the discovery of evolution, which can explain the appearance of life without a divine designer.

Evolution does not explain the appearance of life - rather only how it changes and adapts. The appearance of life is referred to as abiogenesis. At present there is no single generally accepted model for abiogenesis.

given what we know of the world before, and after that point, this argument seems equivalent to the famous 'missing link' argument, while this is something we need to work on, it seems that in order for simple facts to be accepted by some, we must map out the location of every proton from the start of the universe to present.
This is assuming macro-evolution is indeed true, which is, itself, an unverifiable theory based on conjecture and estimations.
The unprovability of science is a myth based on a failure of our education system to properly communicate the scientific method.
There are multiple sources which contradict the idea that macro-evolution is an unverifiable theory.

Both sources are biased towards a particular outcome, and are thus unreliable.

The BBC piece itself admits that current research methods into evolutionary science are yet incomplete to fully determine how distinct species can somehow transition into an entirely distinct species.

Biological evolution, if true, still requires that the laws of physics and chemistry be in a very particular form. If they were even slightly different, evolution would likely be impossible. So that evolution is even possible implies a teleology to the natural order.
This would also imply a designer who needs a designer and so on and so forth.

This isn't necessarily true. If the laws of physics or chemistry were different, we may have simply seen a different form of love evolved to function in the universe as it would be under different circumstances. There is no way to evaluate the probability of this being plausible or implausible.
The particularity of forms do not imply or necessitate "purpose" or teleological meaning.
The absence of a presently adequate explanation is not reason to assume there is no adequate natural explanation. Every explanation we currently have was true and adequate before we understood it.

The fact that natural explanations have been found for some phenomenon is not a reason to believe that all phenomenon will one day have natural explanations just as a cancer cure which works in many cases can not be considered effectice for every case . The only possible proof would be to establish natural explanations for everything.
The assertion that everything will one day have natural explanations cannot be disproven and is therefore not scientific.
Here John Lennox's arguments come into play. A natural explanation based on laws is unsatisfactory unless we know how those laws were put in place.
Equating cosmological constants to laws dictated by minds is a false equivalence. Natural "laws" are not dictated rules that must not be broken. They are observations about the natural world.
So far such natural explanations have not been found (i.e. modern evolutionary theory and the precise assignation of the values of the fundamental forces)

The discovery of a natural explanation is irrelevant for the existence of a designer. In other words: The teleological argument is not nullified by such discovery. An explanation of a Ford car in terms of Henry Ford as inventor and designer does not compete with an explanation in terms of mechanism and law, as professor John Lennox points out.

This argument does not follow because "natural explanations" and "teleology" are not mutually exclusive. Natural explanations can only answer the question, "How?" but teleology addresses, "To what end?"
Axiological arguments support the existence of God.
The ontology and existence of logic cannot be justified in a naturalistic universe.
The laws of logic are immaterial.
The statement "No matter exists" would be true and logical if matter did not exist; therefore logic cannot depend on matter.
The laws of logic cannot be changed by altering any physical substance.
The laws of logic require a mind to exist; they have no reason to exist in a universe with no minds.

The laws of logic are rules for correct thinking. Thinking requires a mind. It is unlikely in a naturalistic universe that laws for correct thinking would exist platonically, waiting for minds that might or might not appear.
The minds that conceived of logic are the minds of humans (or, in a more basic sense, animals). Patterns however don't require a mind to exist.
Logic was not invented by humans; it was discovered and used by humans.
Humans could not have made the law of the excluded middle irrelevant to our universe. They discovered the law, they did not create it.
That law is not a feature of the universe, it only codifies a pattern observed in various instances in the universe. The existence of such instances does not require a mind.
Humans could not have made the law of non-contradiction irrelevant to our universe. They discovered the law, they did not create it.
Logic codifies patterns. Logic itself is a system made by humans.
The statement "there are no minds" would be true and logical in a universe where no minds exist.
The laws of logic would exist even if human or animal minds did not exist.
In the early seconds after the big bang, the statement "No human minds exist" was true and rational. However, no human existed to have a mind capable of processing that statement.
Without minds to contain the sentence "no human minds exist" the claim was meaningless, rather than logical, true or rational.

If it is rational to believe that a mind-dependent entity must exist even if human or animal minds do not, then it is logical to assume that some other mind exists.

The objection assumes that no other types of minds exist, which begs the question of the discussion. God is not human; it is plausible that a concept can exist in the mind of God, even if humans do not exist.

That is at the very least baseless and at most completely incorrect. What would be justified to say is that patterns existed, not logic. Logic was invented later by humans to codify predictions regarding patterns of nature.

If the brain was not designed by a creator then it was not designed for thinking, but rather is a by-product of chemical and physical reactions in the brain. There is no logical reason to trust such a random and unguided process to give an apparatus capable of understanding reality. Therefore we should not trust it if it is claiming atheism.C.S. Lewis on Reasoning to Atheism
The contradiction between a naturalistic world and the certainty that we experience through logic is a falacy, since logic itself is not certain, nor truly objective.

The naturalistic view can contain a mind, and through self assuring entropic development, a consciousness. Consciousness itself is closely resembling an entropic process of self-modification like DNA evolution.
There's no need for any additional mystic or supernatural quality to explain the existence of consciousness.
AI investigation will eventually be able to explain the rise of conscioussness.
In The Emperor's New Mind, Penrose proposes that consciousness can never be modeled by a Turing machine. This includes modern AI systems.
This is not only speculation, it is a "science of the gaps" argument. In other words, "we don't understand this, but someday, science will be able to fill in the gaps of our knowledge".
In The Emperor's New Mind <en.wikipedia.org>, Penrose proposes a very plausible explanation for the apearence of conscioussness.
AI researchers, philosophers, computer scientists and other experts deny the plausibility of the thesis contained in The Emperor's New Mind.

Such a naturalistic consciousness would necessarily be deterministic, and any conclusions derived from that consciousness would be the product of naturalistic biochemical reactions and non-directed processes; more akin to a cosmic Plinko game than rational thought. 

If true, then the conclusion reached in the parent claim should not be assumed to be true, as the claimant could not have come to any other conclusion regardless of the evidence.
The fact that no supernatural explanation is required does not mean that such consciousness is deterministic. Quantum mechanics are not supernatural and are not deterministic
It has not been shown that quantum events are non-deterministic. Some interpretations, such as the De Broglie–Bohm theory, have deterministic implications.
Natural biochemical reactions are not deterministic, they derive from a great deal of chaos and randomness.
If the parent claim is true, then consciousness is the product of chaos and randomness, and would produce random thoughts, not rationality. Therefore our reason could not be trusted.

"Chaos" and "randomness" in a naturalistic universe merely imply that too many variables exist to be tracked by humans or our tools. Neither chemistry nor physics are random; they behave according to well-established principles which permit us to understand our universe using the tools of science.
Our explicit conceptions of the laws of logic may transcend a naturalistic universe, however they have derived, implicitly, from a naturalistic universe.

The predictability of the universe is sufficient for utility codifying a system of logic. As intelligent beings evolved the use of patterns was favored as it aided in survival, therefore giving rise to more and more complex logical systems.
Evolution leads to diversity; yet we see one uniform law of logic across the universe. The law of non-contradiction is not true for one species but false for another.
It is not the usefulness of the law of non-contradiction that evolves, but rather the ability to apply it, which not all things have.

This system would necessarily prefer survival over truth. Natural selection of logic would allow an entity to believe a beneficial lie rather than a harmful truth. Such an entity would have no reason to believe that his thoughts (including the claim above, or this claim) were true.

While people do believe in some beneficial lies over some harmful truths, the subset of beliefs that are part of the system we call logic do not share that trait (in other words those are cherry picked ideas for the sole purpose of inducing truth).
Correct reasoning often does help in survival.
Extrapolating that if a tree bears one fruit that isn't poisonous the other fruits are probably not poisonous either can aid in eating safer foods.
Correctly predicting the direction a predator is going improves the chances of escaping.

Understanding that if an individual predator is in a given place it is not in another place improves the chances of not being in the same area as a predator (consequently being at a lower chance of getting preyed upon).

If the belief that "correct reasoning often does help in survival" is false, but beneficial to survival, then that belief would be selected and reinforced. On materialism, we have no way to rise above our programming to determine whether this is or is not true.
While this is true in the examples given, it is irrelevant to the point. A false belief that was beneficial would be selected and reinforced in exactly the same way.
An ability to properly interpret our environment does not necessarily imply an ability to determine truth about abstract and metaphysical claims.
The fact that these ideas are empirically verified to hold true is sufficient to establish that they hold true.

If the parent claim is true, then we have no reason to trust our empirical verifications. These would be evolved beliefs and subject to the same filter of natural selection, which favors survival, not truth.
If logic developed through evolution, then it is necessarily true that it could have developed differently than what it did. This would mean that the law of non-contradiction could have been false.
Our utterly unthinking ancient ancestors displayed behaviours consistent with logical thought. Human's "laws of logic" simply codified these responses into rules.

This argument acknowledges that logic can exist, even if all human ancestors are "unthinking"--for otherwise, the claim that the unthinking ancestor's actions were logical would either be false, or meaningless.

Therefore this claim supports, rather than rebuts, the parent claim.

The claim talks about the predictability of the naturalistic universe giving rise to the possibility of logical thought. It therefore rebuts the claim that logic is not possible in a naturalistic universe.

Logic can itself be conceptualised in differing ways. For example the "law to exclude the middle" can be written as: (P??P) or (P|P)|((P|P)|(P|P)). A different approach to the world would have led to a differing representation of a transcendent rule, derived from the same observations of nature.
This addresses the conceptualization of logic, not the ontology of logic. The conceptualization of an entity does not explain why or how that entity exists.
But that is what logic is: conceptualization. Patterns on the other hand don't really require an explanation, they can just be.
There are aesthetic arguments for the existence of God.

There isn't any reason a priori to expect the world to be fundamentally beautiful - however, if it was created by a perfect God, it would almost certainly be. As such, the fact that we exist in a fundamentally beautiful universe counts as evidence for a perfect Creator.

The Likelihood Principle states that if some observation O is likely under hypothesis A and less likely under hypothesis B, then O counts as evidence for A over B.

The existence of a fundamentally beautiful universe (O) is likely assuming a perfect creator (A), and less likely assuming the absence of such a creator (B).

There exists in the claim a fallacy of Affirming the Consequent. Allowing that God would probably create an ordered (a.k.a. "elegant") universe, it cannot be concluded that an ordered universe was necessarily caused by said God.

This demonstrates an argument from rarity. It conflates the probability of causation with the plausibility of explanation. By analogy, it is like arguing that the winner of the lottery must have cheated, due to the low probability of any given person winning.
It's possible that the human conception of "beauty" adapted from experience of the outside world, and so it would be natural for humans to consider nature "beautiful."

Many things not visible to early humans - such as planets, nebulae, and galaxies, or the microscopic structures of many materials - are still considered beautiful, despite humans having no time to adapt to them and come to see them that way.
Our value of these other structures may be evolutionary spandrels.
The universe is not fundamentally beautiful - for example, life is impossible in 99.99% of the universe, and millions of people die every year because of natural disasters.
From a distance, the violent scenes of the cosmos are extremely beautiful, and since no life is at stake, they are not horrifying, yet remain awe inspiring.
Much of the world isn't beautiful - for example, the atrocities committed by man and animals.
Even the case of the vast majority, but not all, of the universe being fundamentally beautiful is very unlikely without assuming intentional design.

God gave men and animals free will, including the freedom to defile natural beauty. The works that God is solely responsible for, excluding those sullied by free creatures, are fundamentally beautiful.
Natural disasters or infections are not works of free creatures, but they are not beautiful. Which means God, if he exists, did not create a fundamentally beautiful universe.
Natural disasters may wipe out much moral evil, and so may have the beauty and awe of divine justice.

During natural disasters, many heroic acts are done, which are beautiful in their own right, and only possible in such dire situations, thus natural disasters can be made beautiful by acts of heroism.
There is no particular reason a priori to expect natural laws to be elegant or beautiful, or even so accurately described by mathematics. Yet, they are elegant and beautiful.
Intentional design by a perfect God could account for such elegance. As such, the fact that physical laws are mathematically elegant counts as evidence for a perfect Creator.
There is not sufficient evidence for intelligent design.
Aesthetics are subjectively pleasing, and something being found aesthetically pleasing doesn't necessitate it being made for personal appreciation.
Elegance in the parent argument isn't being used in the aesthetic sense. It's not just pleasing to the eye, it's mathematically balanced and coherent.
The fundamental laws of our universe are extremely elegant, whereas the vast majority of possible sets of natural laws are incredibly arbitrary and complex. This suggests maximization by some agent.

Elegance in scientific theories is an illusion.
We, as pattern finding masters, project the elegance into these equations and modify them to fit our aesthetic values.

We can't arbitrarily "modify the equations to fit our aesthetic values" because they still have to describe objective reality. If Newton's second law were mathematically different (e.g F = ma + 0.001), there would be no way to legitimately simplify the equation into the much more elegant (and real) F = ma.
A complex and baroque set of natural laws, or even an ineffable and indescribable nature not governed by such laws, could just as well be seen as beautiful, so this beauty does not need explanation.
A priori, by the Occamian principle, we should have every reason to expect simple (and therefore elegant, beautiful) sets of natural laws to be more likely than complex ones.

If aesthetic judgments have objective truth, there must exist an objective standard or anchor point to justify them. Such an aesthetically perfect, objective, and transcendent anchor would be considered God.
Many atheists have an aesthetic distaste for the idea of God; the description of God as "aesthetically perfect" is thus in dispute.
Aesthetic judgements do not have objective truth, and indeed the subjectivity of taste is widely attested.

There is no thing necessitating objectivity in aesthetics. Indeed art, literature or any other thing that exhibits or conjures beauty is subjective in appreciation. One may fail to find beauty even where a billion others succeed, no known physical laws deny the possibility.
A difference in appreciation of art need not be grounded in mere difference of opinion. It may just as well be a consequence of some sort of defect in the one person over the other.
Moral arguments support the existence of God.
C.S. Lewis reasoned from universal experience that universal law exists and thus, a universal law-giver exists.
For a universal Moral Law to exist, there must be a sort of 'order' in the universe. This order in the universe is what dictates humans acting/reacting according to the universal Moral Law.
CS Lewis's third premise ("If there is a Moral Law-giver, it must be something beyond the universe.") is unsubstantiated.
Laws can be from internal sources. Many laws that affect the United States were written after its foundation by its citizens.
Morals cannot be dictated by matter, space or, time.
By definition, morals deal not with what is but what ought to be.
CS Lewis's second premise ("If there is a universal Moral Law, there is a Moral Law-giver") is unsubstantiated.
Laws do not require lawgivers.
Lewis doesn't explain why moral laws require a law-giver, even though there are other laws that are not dependent on minds. Laws of Physics, for example.

This is an equivocation of the word "Laws". Natural laws are simply descriptions of what would happen in nature under the given circumstances. The moral law describes what should happen under the given circumstances. The two are not equivalent.
The moral law is prescriptive, and we have no other example of a prescriptive law without a law-giver.
Morality certainly isn't descriptive, in that it doesn't describe human behavior. Almost every moral realist will agree that humans break the moral law more often than they follow it.
"If you don't eat, you will die" is an example of a prescriptive natural law.
If someone does not value their life, they won't have a reason to "follow" this. The statement itself doesn't force someone to put value on their own life.
the law does not force someone to follow it, it merely enacts consequences.
This is equivocation. The moral law isn't (necessary) one which enacts consequences for actions, but only prescribes the right actions to do regardless of its results.
ignoring moral law has consequences, just as with physical laws, like guilt, lack of depth of experience, lack of social progress, and social estrangement.
This is only an example of a true if-then statement, not a law.
all laws are if-then statements, if it is not consequential it is a definition, not a law.

To be an inherent pull towards following any sort of universal Moral Law, there must be a sort of 'order' to the universe. This order implies a force or being with greater complexity to implement this order. As a starting point for understanding this force or being that implements order, God can be assumed.

Lewis is pushing back against the supposed absence of objective moral law in an atheistic universe. However, he fails to provide objective morals in a theistic universe. In his view, God is creating the law. The laws are conceived of entirely in the mind of God, and hence subjective. The only difference between God's subjective morals and human's subjective morals is that God has enough power to enforce his morals (might makes moral right).
The unchanging and universal moral law still suffices as an explanation for our experience, even if it is "subjective" from the perspective of God.

Lewis does not argue that God creates the law by His divine subjectivity or His will to impose them. That view is associated with nominalism and theological voluntarism, which Lewis rejected in favor of something more like Christian Platonism.

The argument that God's morals are subjective does not apply if God is of a different kind and mind than us. If we are created rather than begotten (that is being of different, more limited kind merely resembling the creator) then our perception of available morality is not going to be equal to that of God.
Non sequitur; there is no more logical connection in "God is of a different kind and mind than us, therefore morality is objective" than in "the sky is blue, therefore the moon is made of stilton".
The moral argument for God's existence is not sound as it presupposes that objective moral laws exist, which has not been demonstrated.

The existence of objective moral laws has been persuasively defended by many philosophers, including many philosophers who are not theists, such as Russ Shafer-Landau, David Enoch, and Michael Huemer.

In support of premise (1), Lewis argues that we all have within us the sense of right behavior and character. There is a sense of “oughtness” that presses upon us. He says, “human beings, all over the earth, have this curious idea that they ought to behave in a certain way, and cannot really get rid of it.” [Mere Christianity p 8]
The moral laws that apply to human beings should not be confused with a "Universal" moral law, which applies to everything.

Applicability to everything is not necessary for a law to be objective. The statement "water is a liquid at room temperature and sea level pressure" is objectively true, despite only applying to water. This type of objective truth is all that is necessary for the moral argument.

There's a difference between prescriptive and descriptive laws. Those set by a law giver, like the ones passed by the legislative branch, are prescriptive, while the ones humans develop through observation and analysis are descriptive. As the laws of nature scientists have discovered are descriptive, it would be invalid to deduce that a law giver must exist.

Various basic human instincts such as responsibility (and other similar instincts such as gratitude and awe) are implicitly theistic. Being responsible is universally considered a virtue. This raises the question, to whom are we responsible? Is to ourselves (like appointing your chief accountant to audit your company)? To one another? By analogy with Aquinas' 5 Ways we can trace back the chain of responsibility to God the Judge before whom we are ultimately responsible.
Morality is a purpose given to us by a creator.
In the same way that a clock that doesn't tell the time is a bad clock, a human who doesn't live a life of love and compassion is a bad human.
A clock that doesn't tell the time is only subjectively a bad clock according to (a subset of) humans. In the same way, even if God did exist, that would not make morality objective.

Being created for a purpose is not warrant for the goodness of that purpose. Building a gun to kill does not make it a moral good for that gun to fire and kill even though it does what it was designed to do.

A gun being built for murder and then being successfully used for murder does make it a correctly functioning, and therefore "good", gun, even if it doesn't justify the moral actions taken by the human using it.
Under this theory, manmade purpose isn't identical to morality, only Godmade purpose is.
This doesn't solve the is/ought problem and therefore doesn't explain morality as understood by human nature. The fact that humans were given a purpose doesn't mean their purpose is "correct".
This claim is completely unsubstantiated.
All morality is necessarily situational. Take a moral pronouncement and you can derive both a situation where it's justified and an alternate situation where it is not.

Most theists reject moral absolutism (that certain actions are always either right or wrong, regardless of situation). Moral realism (that the rightness or wrongness of any given, situational action is objective) still holds, and is all that is needed for the moral argument to work.
Morality is sufficiently explained by evolution and the relationships between individuals. These objective features do not require a God.

Morality can be both situational and objective. Water is a liquid at certain temperatures/pressures and a solid at others, but the definition of water is still objective. In the same way, "it is wrong to do x in this situation" can still be a statement with an objective truth value.
If there isn't a standard morality, then there is no need to qualify any action by its context, because all things would be acceptable across all situations.
Moral relativism holds that actions can be considered right or wrong, but that such a judgment depends on the context.
Agent relativism states that the morality of an action can only be determined by the person taking the action.
Agent relativism isn't intuitive or held by many people - for instance, we still consider a murderer to be wrong, even if the murderer thinks that murder is morally permissible or even obligatory.

Under agent relativism, since moral framework is decided entirely by the individual, individuals should be able to change their moral framework whenever it's convenient to them or they have a whim to. In reality, people don't treat morality as if it's subject to their own whims in such a way, and will deem it right to adhere to it even when it's inconvenient.

Under agent relativism, morality is only motivated by internal beliefs, not by any external motivators. However, there are many examples of people's views of morality being changed by external motivators. For instance, imagine a man who believes that poor people deserve to suffer for the choices they make, but changes his mind after spending time with a poor family and coming to care about them. This scenario would not be possible under agent relativism.

Agent relativism isn't supported by the human instinct to justify one's own actions based on moral standards. For instance, if someone steals, they will attempt to justify the theft by saying that they need the stolen thing more than the original owner does, rather than simply saying that stealing is morally right to them. This implies that morality is based on something outside of the agent.
Speaker relativism states that moral statements are true or false only according to the one who makes the statement.

Speaker relativism isn't intuitive or held by many people. For instance, if someone says that murder is permissible, we intuitively believe that they are wrong, rather than just stating a truth about their own moral framework.

According to speaker relativism, when a claim is made, that claim is referring to the moral framework of the speaker. As such, when two people disagree about morality, they are speaking about two separate frameworks - and, as such, do not have shared meaning. Without shared meaning, real disagreement is impossible. Intuitively, this is not what moral disagreement is.

If one person says that planes fly through the air, and another person states that they don't, believing the word "plane" to refer to a woodworking tool, then the two people don't truly disagree because they aren't referring to the same thing.
All forms of moral relativism fail to account for the general agreement amongst all of humanity of basic moral principles.

If you listen to people, God has been for, or against whatever happens to be in their best interest at the time. If one is looking for humans determining for themselves what is moral without the application of reason, they thus need look no further then a theist.
The selfish nature of humanity does not disprove the existence of God. It only proves that many theists are selfish or insincere. The flaws of mankind are distinct from the existence of God.
Those that follow God-free, logic-based moralities are much better behaved, and consistent than theists do in no small part to fundamental foundational problems with theism.

Theistic sources are contradictory, allowing one to choose morals convent for them, rather then to be consistent, or good. For example, the bible argues both for and against slavery. It is impossible to be good when what is good isn't even consistently defined.
The horrible practice of the gospel of wealth is an example of theistic indiscretion.

Since the ability to determine whether a person who claims to follow some moral code actually does is limited to him being honest, there is no reliable method to evaluate what every person does in relation to the moral code he claims to follow.
There are as many moral arguments against the existence of God.

Many theists base their belief in God on good in the world, while the stories in their religious texts tend to depict the Gods of classical theism as selfish evil tyrants with bad attitudes, short tempers, lust for death and destruction, and a general disregard for the value of anything other then themselves, even when those same texts defined such Gods as being good no matter what they do.
The Christian God is depicted as slow to anger and rich in mercy.  Jonah actually complains to God that he is not nearly vengeful enough. (Jonah 4)
God's justice and wrath against immorality is not evidence that God is an evil, selfish, tyrant.
The god of Abraham is described as genocidal. Genocide is immoral. Therefore, moral arguments for the god of Abraham are invalid if they are based on omnibenevolence.
According to Exodus 11-12, God committed genocide against the first born of Egyptian households.
According to Genesis 6-9, God was the first entity to commit genocide, thereby inventing the practice.
The "genocides" depicted in the Old Testament were God's punishment against evil people for their immorality. As such Genocide is not intrinsically immoral.
Hitler's attempted genocide was punishment for his perceived evil nature of Jewish people, yet it was still immoral.
Many of the genocides attributed to God are actually commanded by humans (such as Moses), and carried out by humans, not God.
In the particular case of Amalekites (1 Samuel 15) God is unambiguously responsible for the genocide.
In their historical contexts, it is likely that the biblical accounts did in fact intent to attribute these commands to God.
In many cases where God does not explicitly order the genocide, he encourages it or does nothing to stop it. This still makes God complicit in these genocides.
If God does not exist, there is no basis upon which to affirm objective moral values and duties. Therefore, talking about the morality of God is meaningless.
There are no arguments against God from the existence of morality.

In Plato's Socratic Dialogue "Euthyphro," it is proved that morality cannot feasibly come from a god, and thus must either exist or not independently. Thus moral arguments for god are all based on a shaky standing.

If God commands actions because they are right, then morality isn't grounded in God but instead supersedes him. But if actions are right because God commands them, then morality is arbitrary, as it is subject to the whims of God.
Morality isn't arbitrary because God is defined as being perfect, or maximally great.
Many ontological arguments use God's perfection/maximal greatness as a premise to prove His existence.

Without a measurement to use, there is no maximum, or minimum. If morality isn't arbitrary due to God's greatness, there must be an objective yardstick for God to be the top of. If there is such a yardstick, then God is not the measure of morality. If not, then, once again, morality would be arbitrary.
Measurements can be based on similarity to a given reference (such as the nature of God's mind), without a need for an "objective yardstick."
The concept of a "reference" is functionally identical to the concept of an "objective yardstick."

One point of reference is insufficient to create a system of measurement, as what is being measured is unknowable. For example, if God is the only reference for morality, then if someone was stupider, or less wise then God, if they preferred cheese more, or ham less, they would be just as immoral as a murderer, or a rapist.
Morality is relative, not absolute. Not every difference from God would have to be equally immoral.
Without a measuring stick, it is impossible to tell which aspects of God matter for the measurement of morality, and which ones don't.
A second point of reference isn't necessary to determine what is being measured.

Scientists can compare the relative sizes of the Earth and the Sun without getting confused by the fact that the Sun is hotter than the Earth, or concluding that the size difference must therefore be greater than what is physically measured.
This is because measurements of size already exist, as does it what size is that is being measured. One doesn't measure the size of the sun by merely asking how different is is from the earth.
The only comparison here given is one where an existing scale already exists.
Morality isn't subject to God's whims because God is necessary and unchanging.
If morality originates in God's nature rather than His command Euthyphro's dilemma is avoided.
The concept that "God and morality are the same thing" is literal nonsense, equivalent to saying "this potato and the pythagorean theorem are the same thing".

The claim isn't saying that God and morality are the same thing, it's saying that morality is defined in God's nature. The word "apple" is defined in the dictionary but this doesn't make the word "apple" the same thing as the dictionary.

Linguistic prescriptivism is disfavoured in English, even by the publishers of major dictionaries, so although there is a definition of the word "apple" in the dictionary, it is not true that "apple" is defined by the dictionary in a sense that equates to the supposed function of God's nature for morality.
Equating the "nature" of a mythological creature (God) with the definition of some other concept (morality) is similarly nonsensical.

"Morality originating in God's nature" is served by one of the dilemma's hypotheticals, that "a thing is good because God willed it," and is therefore a concession that the Euthyphro dilemma is not a "false dilemma."

According to the "God's nature" response to the Euthyphro dilemma, the statement "a thing is good because God willed it" is simply not true. A thing is good because it's in God's nature, and God in turn wills things that are in his nature.

The Euthyphro dilemma can be reframed as: something is part of God's nature because that thing is good, or that something is good because it's part of God's nature? In the first case, the goodness derives from something apart from God's nature, and in the second case, God's nature (and goodness defined by it) becomes arbitrary.

If God is omnipotent, then His nature, being something He has power over, is still subject to His whims. If God is not in control over His nature, then morality still supersedes God. Thus, Euthyphro's dilemma still holds.

God never changed his nature to be what it is now. Instead, God has always had his current nature and has simply never changed it. Thus, his nature has not been shaped by his whims and is not subject to his whims.
Euthyphro's dilemma could be regarded as a false dilemma.
One could keep asking why is whatever moral standard considered such moral standard in an infinite regress.
Euthyphro's dilemma could be applied to any objective moral standard.

"is what is morally good commanded by [objective standard] because it is morally good, or is it morally good because it is commanded by [objective standard]? "
Well since it is an objective standard, the answer is the latter. So no, Euthyphro's dilemma does not at all apply to objective moral standards, because it does not create a dilemma.
Things could be bad because if other people did them, it would bring harm to one's self.
Things could be good because people with certain traits do them, or bad because people with other traits do them.
Things could be good because they bring about a desirable end for the individual.
Things could be good because they bring about a positive end in the aggregate.
Things could be bad because if you don't do them, you will be punished.
It seems highly unlikely that neither Socrates, not Euthyphro, both great thinkers, one on either side of the debate, saw this supposed problem while they were discussing this dilemma.

'Objective' may be interpreted to mean either 'mind independent' or 'factual', while 'subjective' may mean 'mind dependent' or 'mere opinion'. 

Now it is a fact that I have a mind, but that fact is dependent upon my mind, so it is objective in that it's factual, but subjective in that it's mind dependent. Hence, there is ambiguity.

“The human mind has no more power of inventing a new value than of imagining a new primary colour, or, indeed, of creating a new sun and a new sky for it to move in.” C.S. Lewis - The Abolition of Man

The fact that you can track the evolution of religion to what we currently have suggests that it is a human construct and that no such power/presence exists.
The fact that religion by definition is a human construct does not disprove God in the philosophical sense.
The classical god supposes that god would want humans to know about its existence, so there should be one accurate religion not many contradictory religions
The idea of the divine permeating culture is evidence of a common origin from a divine creator rather than invention.
A tendency for creatures to believe in God is exactly what we'd expect if God created humans to believe in Him.
Atheists exist which is not what we would expect if a god existed
A free will allowing God would allow atheism to exist.

A different order of events is even more likely. Sentient beings, having the idea of supernatural being, assign natural phenomena they cannot explain to that being. So God is at least equally or even less likely the consequence of ignorance about nature, He is rather a cause of supernatural explanation of the puzzling phenomena. Why would anybody invent God to justify ignorance? Any ignorance should remain just a simple ignorance, no need for God.
It is reasonable to believe that people invented God to answer many questions about our universe. People don't like unanswered questions.

In order to survive, we have evolved the ability to conjecture a cause to a phenomenon, even with incomplete data, as evidenced by our ability to come up with answers at all, but sometimes, this system gets it wrong.

Not related. I never argued against assigning a cause to a phenomena. My claim is about the rank: 1. unexplained phenomena causing the idea of God or 2. already having the idea of God, then assigning unexplained phenomena to Him. We are well aware of ignorance, no need to assign a particular ignorance to God. "I don't know who took my wallet - wow! - it must have been God!" Second option is thus more probable.
Although humans like answers, this does not blind them to questions, we are naturally curious, and defiant, and will generally only fall back on an easy answer if we can't find a better alternative.
There is a stark difference between questions relevant to everyday survival, and function, and questions we want answered, but aren't easily applicable to our life.

Modern theological arguments (teleological, moral, ontological, cosmological) arrive at the existence of a God deductively, by revealing a situation that could only be properly explained by something we'd call a God, not by seeing unanswered questions and proposing a God to explain them.
The fact that different unrelated cultures have developed ideas of God, divinity or transcendence is an argument for a diferent origin to those ideas other than cultural heritage.

Materialism, and the study of matter, has produced consistent understandings of physics, biology, mathematics and technology all over the world. In contrast, belief in god, as well as beliefs about his intentions and values, vary from person to person and between the hundreds of religious sects worldwide.

It follows that physicalism, as a heuristic, yields a more objective, robust and useful explanation of and approach to the universe and our place within it.

Scientific progress doesn't rely on physicalism in the sense of rejecting all non-material claims, only the belief that the material world follows knowable rules. Belief in or rejection of God has no relation to that.

Bertrand Russell's teapot analogy asks if one imagines a teapot was in orbit around the sun, would we consider the fact that it's very small, or perhaps that the sun blocks it from view, be reasons to believe such a teapot exists? 

Russell was employing Occam's heuristic within this analogy by asking is a thing which cannot be observed, measured or seen to have any consistent or reliable effect on our lives, worth believing in for any reason other than mere self-consolation?"

Throughout history god has been cited as the cause for mental illness, the weather, viral and bacterial infection, volcanic eruptions, it was only because certain people preferred physical, measurable explanations of these phenomena that the human race now has facilities for psychology, forecasting weather and natural disasters as well as modern medicine.
Citing unexplained naturalist phenomenon is no more reliable of an explanation for unknown causes than that of direct intervention.
Occam's razor only applies to testable ideas. Since there are no tests available for or against a god's existence, Occam's razor does not apply to god claims.

Occam's Razor can apply to an untestable hypothesis. It is based on the principle that a simple hypothesis is more testable and therefore more useful than a complex hypothesis. If a hypothesis is so complex as to be unfalsifiable, the Razor says that it should be discarded.
Applying Occam's Razor to claims in favor of a god's existence means that those claims should be discarded since they are not falsifiable.

Occam's Razor has nothing to do with testability whatever, and is in fact most decisive where we do not have recourse to empirical tests.

For example, the hypothesis that "toys come to life when they are not being observed, but then return everything to exactly the position that it would have been once humans can directly or indirectly perceive them" is not testable, but we reject it because the rival (but empirically indistinguishable) explanation is simpler.
The classical theistic definition of a god is testable. Therefore, Occam's razor can be used.

Occam's Razor supports other forms of monism, such as nondualism, idealism, panpsychism or computationalism just as well as it supports physicalism, because conscious experience is the only thing that we know for certain exists. Physicalism requires the assumption of new entities which are being perceived yet still 'exist' outside of perception.

Occam's razor prefers the simpler theorem. It a simple explanation that an infinite omnipotent created the universe. A far more complicated theorem is required in order to explain how the universe (and physics itself) could come into existence in the absense of God.

God, and other superstitious hypotheses like giants or fairies, appear much simpler to the human mind than a truly rigorous understanding of complexity, such as Kolmogorov complexity, would merit them. Only by this human failure of perception does the parent even appear plausible.

The theory of God's existence requires you to make a number of assumptions:
1. assume God exists
2. assume him to be powerful enough to create the universe
3. assume that he wants to do so
Any theory of the origin of the universe will require the pre-existence of at least something. Even naturalistic explanations such as the big bang start with presupposing some laws of physics.
It is true of both naturalistic explanations and the God explanation, that any theory of the origin of the universe will require pre-existence of at least some thing.
Laws of physics are testable and demonstrably true. God's existence is not (or has not been).
God creating the universe is less simple according to Occam's Razor. To explain the universe from a non-theistic point of view requires one less thing to explain.
Removing God from creation does not remove one fewer explanation, but removes the most simple explanation, thus contrasting Occam's Razor.
As long as there is no extensive understanding on how a god would need to be in order to be able to create, god can not be classified as a simple explanation.

The application of Occam's Razor prefers fewer variables. In theism, the only variable behind the universe is the will of God. Without theism, there can be many variables and brute principles which lie behind the operation of the laws of physics and the origin of the universe.
All of the variables that exist without theism also exist with theism. Theism only adds another variable.
Theism unifies diverse things under one single variable, the will of God. This is simpler than having a large number of "brute fact" variables without a unifying source or explanation.

Occam's Razor only holds in the case of equally strong competing explanations. There are good explanations of the existence of God, which, if they are stronger than the explanations of his non-existence, invalidate Occam's Razor.
Occams razor works everywhere we're trying to explain observations.
Occam's Razor is just a useful heuristic and should never be used as the final arbiter to decide which theory is to be favored.
It's purpose is as a means of deciding which of available solutions should be favored.

There is no known way to calculate the probability of any metaphysical statement. Therefore, probability can't be effectively used for metaphysical study, and other forms of reasoning (like logical deduction) are required.

Because of uncertainty in our own reasoning abilities, we can be in a position of regarding in principle a priori positions as more or less likely.

For instance, prior to its more rigorous proof, most mathematicians regarded Fermat's Last Theorem as much more likely to be true than not.

Metaphysics places itself outside measurement and examination. Thus it is unfalsifiable, by definition a fallacy, therefore unworthy of reasonable consideration when hypothesising real explanations for anything.
Physicalism is supported only by Occam's Razor, whereas theism is made even more probable by other factors.

There is no contradiction between God's existence and the created order operating along physicalist lines, and most evidence we have for physicalism (above all, its success in guiding scientific hypotheses) concerns its being true of the world in which we are in. Therefore, most evidence for physicalism is not evidence against theism, even if theism is incompatible with more strict versions of physicalism.

Probabilities and evidence are largely irrelevant to the question of God's existence. If you agree that the world exists, and that change occurs, then that is all the evidence that Aquinas' First Way requires to logically demonstrate God's existence.
If probabilities and evidence are largely irrelevant to the question of God's existence, that means there is no debate. But such debates exist.
An omniscient being who wants to be noticed should be impossible to miss, so to even merely lack belief rather than disbelieve should require ample evidence that such a God exists.
If God does exist, then he is a terrible communicator. This would seem to undermine the theistic notion that he cares about people and wants them to be able to know, love, and worship him.
God is impossible to miss except when people are blinded by certain socially constructed habits of thinking which are hostile to Them.
One can just as easily assert that God's non-existence is obvious except to people blinded by certain socially constructed habits of thinking.
God does not reveal himself in order to give people the free choice of faith. In other words, God is running a simulation to distinguish those who believe from those who don't.
God has no reason to reveal himself to people that he knows will reject him anyways.
Classical theism says nothing about divine desire for being noticed, so divine hiddenness is not an argument against the classical theism.

Atheism is traditionally the absence in belief in deity.  If atheists, instead, accept a belief with no proof (even in the non-existence of deity), then they have essentially become a religion which cannot prove their own claims.
Many atheists, while perhaps quite doubtful, will concede that God may exist, and they would change their minds if sufficient proof was observed.
A religion is more than a simple assertion on a single topic (dictionary). Belief in God is not a religion. Belief in the non-existence of God is similarly not a religion.
Atheism encompasses all people who do not believe that a deity exists. That includes gnosticism and agnosticism.
The assumption that gnostic atheists can't adequately substantiate their position is unwarranted.
Many gnostic atheists claim that conceptions of God are incoherent (either with themselves or with each other).
The absence of evidence is not evidence of absence.
Absence of evidence when evidence is expected is evidence of absence.
If your neighbor never buys dog food, never walks a dog, and you never hear any barking, that's evidence they don't have a dog.

There could always possibly be information that one isn't aware of, or that isn't obvious.  For example, it is possible that (heaven forbid) the owner locks the dog in their basement, never to be seen by the world.
Absence of evidence is not proof of absence, and the parent didn't claim it was. Of course you can think of situations where evidence is absent yet the neighbor still owns a dog.

Let X be any proposition, and E the proposition 'There is evidence in the world that X is true'. 
3 assumptions:
1)"evidence is expected": given X is true, it is more likely that E is true than false: P(E|X) > P(not E|X). Therefore P(not E|X) < 1/2
2)"evidence is absent": P(not E) ? 1
3)It is possible that X is false: P(X) < 1
Proof:
1)Bayes' theorem: P(not E|X) = P(X|not E)*P(not E)/P(X)
2)Using the assumptions and algebra: P(X|not E) < 1/2

The claim assumes that we have sufficient knowledge to know when evidence is expected. A neighbor that never buys dog food, never walks a dog, and from whose house you never hear barking may in fact own a dog... that still lives at their parent's house on the other side of town.
Evidence is expected exactly when it is expected (from your perspective, when you expect it). The claim assumes you have sufficient knowledge to know whether you expect evidence or not.
The parent of the above claim conflates "evidence is expected" with "evidence should be expected"
The lack of evidence for the existence of a deity is the evidence of non-existence, "absence" implies that something or someone was present and some point.
Our knowledge of the existence of something cannot be justified by our senses alone.
One can indeed know of something's existence by senses alone; knowledge of existence and comprehensive understanding of identity are complimentary but distinctly separate issues.
It can be justified by senses and the processing that goes on in the brain.
Even if it is true that evidence available to the senses is not a sufficient condition to know something exists, that does not mean it is not necessary.
A priori, the existence of God is improbable.
Out of a myriad of possible scenarios contradictory with God's existence, God is just one possible case. That puts God at a lower than average a priori probability of being real.

This is a misapplication of statistical reasoning. With billions of persons in the world, it is highly unlikely that precisely this small subset of persons would collaborate on this discussion; yet here we are.

It is absurd to say that two plus two cannot equal four because the odds of the correct answer being four out of an infinite number of integers is (literally) infinity to one. Yet that is an exact analog to the argument presented here.
Something being the case does not mean that a priori (ie. without specific information) it is not highly unlikely.

It is highly unlikely that I am in any specific galaxy in the universe, yet I am in the Milky Way - which is only likely given certain a posteriori information [for instance information about me or about humans].

Two plus two are known to equal 4 a priori, since they are part of a framework that follows logically from a priori conditions in Math. Taking any two random symbols representing quantities between -infinity and +infinity however makes it quite certain that the results will not equal four. And that is a lot more analog to the argument presented.
At least this discussion is likely to have people in it, since it is linked to a network that makes it likely (ie social network). The existence of God has no such reasons to be believed a priori.

By the Occamian principle, more complex hypotheses are penalised in proportion to their complexity. Compared to a purely physical universe described by the equations of physical laws, the God hypothesis is incredibly complex, and therefore incredibly improbable.

This is a subjective claim, since all priors are ultimately subjectively obtained. Proof: Invert any series of iterated Bayesian belief updates. The initial prior was assumed rather than deterministically generated and therefore is not objective.
No statement with the word 'God' as a subject or predicate can be meaningfully made (such as 'God exists') because the word 'God' is not meaningful.
"That which created the material universe" provides a referent to the term "God"

The proposition "the universe was created" is a meaningless proposition because "created" in this proposition refers to creation ex nihilo, which has no existing referent. Therefore, referencing that which took a meaningless action provides no referent to the word "God"
The word 'God' refers to a concept that is defined by its valid functional role within a conceptual scheme.
God has been identified by Christian Apostles as the Father of our spirits, and hence the term has direct and obvious meaning.
God is that which acts upon the material universe to impose (or organize into) a Higher Order (logos) upon that material reality.
This is a primary quality. It describes what "God" does
God is both immanent (encompassing or manifested in the material world) and simultaneously transcendent (independent of the material universe).
The quality "transcendent" precludes the possibility of an existent referent to provide meaning to the word "God"
"immanent" and "transcendant" are mutually exclusive concepts, thus logically precluding a potential referent object from existing to give meaning to the term "God"
these are not primary attributes. They do not provide a referent for the word "God"
"Divine simplicity" provides a referent to the term "God" Divine simplicity means that the "qualities" of God are identical to the Being of God.
This does not provide a referent for the word "God" It is a secondary(descriptive) attribute.

This descriptor implies that secondary (descriptive) qualities are primary(what a thing consists of and what it can do) qualities - exclusively for a single object (God). This is absurd. Therefore, it does not provide a referent to the word "God"

Philosophical arguments support the existence of God, the non-existence of God, and the concept that any attempt to prove or disprove the existence of God is futile. Therefore, philosophical arguments are not a reliable means to support the existence of God.
By logic, the universe shouldn't exist, but it clearly does, so one cannot depend on philosophical arguments to prove the existence of God.
Philosophically the existence of the universe is compatible with God's existence.

Philosophical arguments are reliable and are not reliable. The evidence is down to interpretation depending on whether you believe in the evidence or not. The existence of God is purely down to the individual.
More things are plausible than true. Supporting something with a philosophical argument is not the same as establishing its likelihood of actually being true.
Many philosophical arguments do not merely establish possibility but yield likelihoods or can be amended to yield likelihoods.

If God created humans and all that humans are conscious of, it is fair to reason that he may have allowed for no manner by which his existence could be either proven or disproved by the humans he created.
Philosophical arguments can support anything that you want to be true by using the right words and rhetoric. Masters in such discussions in ancient Greece were called sophists.
In the logical arguments for God's existence, God is always defined such that the conclusion of the argument can be ''God exists''.
The observation that a definition is tailor-made in some way does nothing to show that the definition is a bad one, or that an argument is unsound.
The tacit assumption seems to be here that since God is defined as such, therefore the definition is haphazard. This simply does not follow logically.

Philosophical arguments are often confused with rhetorical arguments. Sophists were masters of rhetoric, they were not philosophers. Rhetoric can be used to support unsubstantiated claims through use of fallacy, philosophy contrarily relies on internal and external consistency, and therefore excludes fallacy.

We can't prove that a proof was or was not created just before we observed it. Meaning that any information about any subject will for eternity have the propensity to be false, this paradoxical state renders the same as to the proofs and lack of proofs of God. The BoP becomes irrelevant in a paradoxical debate as clear as this one.
It is too general to discard philosophical arguments as evidence, based on the diversity of views they propound. It is possible that some arguments stand up to scrutiny, while others do not.
Sound arguments that undermine skeptical arguments against the existence of God provide support for the existence of God.
Sound philosophical arguments for the existence of God provide evidence for God's existence.
An analogous argument would be that since accountants and frauds both use numbers but have different outcomes, therefore mathematics is unreliable. This obviously does not follow.
Philosophical arguments which support the existence of one God would also support the existence of many Gods, hence undermining the classical depiction of the monotheistic God.
Philosophical arguments support the existence of the Roman and Norse Pantheons, which are widely believed to not exist.
While the existence of Roman and Norse Pantheons is not consistent with some theologies, there are others which it is consistent with.
For example, the Srimad Bhagavatam talks of one supreme God who us functioning under Him an assortment of demi-gods who over see the running of the material world, sort of like engineers.

There are people who believe in demi-gods and that they co-exist with a supereme God. An inclusivist or syncretistic approach would allow these demi-gods to be known by different names and stories in different cultures.

For example, the bhakti tradition of India holds that God exists and is known by many names in different cultures and that He empowers demigods to over see the material affairs of the material world while He remains aloof in His spiritual abode. These various pantheons such as the Norse and Greek gods might be these same servants of God understood by different names and stories.

The classical arguments (the cosmological, contingency, ontological, and moral arguments) for God's existence would only allow for the existence of a single deity that is common to the general monotheisms.
Classical arguments don't hold more weight than others.

The claim "At least one God exists" is separate from the claim "If at least one God exists, only one God exists" and is supported using separate evidence. An argument for the former claim is not rendered unsound just because it does not prove the latter claim.
This is not true of Aristotles first mover argument, also known as the argument from contingency.
The original cause has to be one because if it were a committee nothing would ever get done as we know from experience.

Successful businesses generally structure things so there is an executor who can make final decisions should other forms of decision making fail. This resolves impasses and keeps the business running smoothly.
Multiple people with equal power sometimes reach an impasse. A disagreement among God's would result in chaos. This is not commensurate with the world we observe which is ordered and predictable.

Everywhere in nature, we see predators optimised to catch prey that are in turn optimised to not be caught. If the order in nature came from a divine source, this would seem a clear example of the kind of impasse the parent asserts we do not observe; the god of rabbits and the god of foxes disagree about whether foxes should be able to catch rabbits, and their designs express this conflict.
Agnosticism holds that the lack of evidence makes it impossible to know whether God exists.
Like Russell's Teapot, claims about God's existence need to be proved before they are believed. The burden of proof lies with theists.

There is not enough scientific evidence to prove that leprechauns do not exist, nor that unicorns and the flying spaghetti monster do not exist.  If your standard for acceptance of a given belief is simply a lack of scientific disproof, then you must also believe in leprechauns, unicorns, the flying spaghetti monster, and any other ridiculous thing that I might want to suggest. This is why there is a burden of proof before things must be believed.

Unlike creatures like monsters and leprechauns, the existence of God is a universal, or nearly universal belief, which transcends cultures and history. While this itself does not prove its truth, it provides a stark contrast to purely fantasy constructs.

Fictional characters such as monsters and leprechauns are universal and transcend culture and history as well.  Though descriptions vary, nearly all cultures have monsters and various fantastic creatures in their folklore.  The idea of God does not stand in stark contrast to these other fictive constructs.
There is no single universal notion of God. Instead there are multiple different and incompatible notions. This variation occurs because the concept of God contains pure fantasy elements.
Theists do not make positive claims to know of the non-existence of leprechauns or flying spaghetti monsters.
Atheists do not make positive claims to know of the non-existence of god.
Theists have accepted the burden of proof and provided evidence for the existence of God.
There is reasonable evidence supporting the existence of God.
There are probabilistic reasons to believe that God exists.

The Modern Synthesis of Evolution implies that it is highly likey that intent was present for the creation of animals because the alternate "random" mutation of genes detailed in evolutionary theory makes the evolution of organisms as complex as they are highly improbable sciencedirect.com witpress.com (from www.kialo.com)
The concept of "specified complexity" is disputed.
Creationism is unscientific. This argument ( 8. in this article) comes from a misunderstanding of evolutionary biology.

The evolution of organisms as complex as humans is necessitated by the anthropic principle; the possible worlds where nothing intelligent enough to observe things as we do evolved, do not include any observations of how complex or simple life on Earth is.
The Kolmogorov complexity of the God hypothesis is very high.
Kolmogorov complexity is used in Solomonoff induction, a formalisation of Occam's razor.

Kolmogorov complexity seems unrelated to the types of complexity that makes something unlikely to appear by random chance, usually argued to be specified complexity, irreducible complexity, or fine tuning.

The string "4c1j5b2p0cv4w1x8rx2y39umgw5q85s7" has more Kolmogorov complexity than "abababababababababababababababab" according to the article, yet if a random generator produced something looking like the latter string rather than something looking like the former, I would have more reason to suspect the generator's string wasn't actually random.
The algorithm for producing the second string is shorter and simpler than that for the first string. This is what kolmogorov complexity refers to, not the chance of being randomly produced.
Factors that affect the likelihood of something appearing by random chance aren't relevant to God's existence, as he is posited to be eternal.
Being eternal - and thus having always existed - and appearing by random chance, are contradictory.
The Kolmogorov complexity of the universe is not necessarily high. If this is true, then even if God must have a higher Kolmogorov complexity than the universe his own complexity is not high.
The universe may be completely describable by the program "create a world that maximizes the fraction of people (soul/body composites) that freely choose God."
Our universe very plausibly doesn't maximize the fraction of people who choose God.

As a sentence in English, this is a simple "program", but it relies on complex concepts that a human listener already understands. A turing machine does not know what most of the words in that sentence mean.
Kolmogorov complexity is provably uncomputable.
Historical evidence supports the existence of God.
There is historical evidence that Jesus Christ existed, thus there is historical evidence that supports the existence of God.
Jesus' disciples, who were witness to his life and miracles, identified him as being the Son of God. (See Matthew 16 verses 13-17)
Rather then reports of witnesses, what is provided is hearsay in the form of posthumously written texts.
This testimony is only of a man performing some kind of miracles. There are many examples of miracles and other forms of magic being faked throughout history.
People today fake divine power and deeds on YouTube and Christian television shows.

Even in cases where faking miracles is not intentional, a person's actions can be exaggerated and distorted by those who tell and retell the episode.
Even in the information age, people people are still deceived by rather obvious and well known gimmicks (for instance the leg extention "miracles", which are not miraculous at all).
Nothing of Jesus' life that was written about him during his alleged lifetime has survived to this day.

The disciples never wrote their own accounts of their experience of Jesus. The earliest copies of the books we now call the Gospels date to decades after the occurance of the proported events, and were not authored by the men whose names they are title after.
The idea that "God has made himself known by entering into the world as the person Jesus Christ" is an unfalsifiable claim.

The Bible itself gives the conditions for falsifying the claims of Christ in 1 Cor 15:12-19.  If Jesus did not rise from the dead, Christianity is false.

"17 Unless Christ was raised to life, your faith is useless, and you are still living in your sins. 18 And those people who died after putting their faith in him are completely lost. 19 If our hope in Christ is good only for this life, we are worse off than anyone else." (CEV) Read this passage on BibleHub.
The existence of Jesus and the truth of some of his miracle claims are historical claims, and as such can be falsified.

The existence of a man who claimed to be the son of god, and the fact that god sent the earth himself in the form of his son, are two distinct claims, with drastically different standards of evidence.
The fact that someone made the claims can be falsified, the truth of the claims cannot.
It's not clear why these particular historical events can't be investigated historically in the same way as the rest of the past.

Whether the man Jesus existed can be ascertained with a sufficient degree of certainty. Whether he was the son of God and performed miracles, and there are many historical accounts of miracles that were never proven, is another issue.
Just because someone witnessed something they did not understand at the time of it happening and declaring it a miracle, does not constitute prove that it really happened.
Eyewitness accounts are incredibly unreliable. 1 2 3
Alternative attempts to explain the accounts of miracles and the resurrection of Jesus are unsatisfactory to this day.
The Bible is not a historical record. It is no more evidence for Jesus than Marvel comics are for the existence of Spiderman.

To my knowledge, all Marvel authors claim Spiderman to be fiction.  In Contrast, authors of the New Testament cannon writing about Jesus claim him to be nonfictional.
