There is no evidence that Jesus Christ was a god.
Jesus is not a theistic god in the classical meaning of the word.
Many Christians are classical theists, and they believe that Jesus is, in a nuanced way, a theistic God in this sense.

Many people throughout history have claimed to be prophets, messiahs, gods, or otherwise, or been labeled so by others, but this does not make such claims true, regardless of the amount of people who believe it.
Passages from the Bible support the divinity of Jesus Christ.
Jesus Christ presented extraordinary evidence of his divinity by resurrecting from death. (See 1 Corinthians 15:3-8)

Not having witnessed Christ's resurrection ourselves, that event is itself an extraordinary claim requiring extraordinary evidence - even fairly strong evidence could reasonably be taken as insufficient.
Resurrection stories and claims of witnesses are not uncommon at that time in history. Attis of Phrygia, Horus, Krishna, etc are other such figures.

The Bible identifies Jesus as being present and involved in the creation of the universe. See Colossians 1:16–17, John 1:1-5.

Jesus performed miracles and taught that they evidenced his divinity.

Jesus might have been a sorceror whose magics appeared divine but were not actual miracles.

The Bible identifies Jesus as being the judge of the living and dead. See John 5:26-27, Matthew 25:31-46.

Jesus Christ did exist, but there was a council (The First Council of Nicaea, in 325AD) that decided on whether Jesus would be portrayed as human or divine (was concluded as divine). Therefore the existence of Jesus provides no direct proof of the existence of God.

Even if a human being named Jesus actually existed at this time, preached, and was crucified, this is not evidence for the existence of God. Because these events are possible without requiring a supernatural God.

Jesus' deity must not be taken solely on faith. There is evidence of the deity of Jesus.

Jeremiah 31 establishes others won't die for your sins. "But every one shall die for his own iniquity: every man that eateth the sour grape, his teeth shall be set on edge." This is confirmed by Ezekiel 18:4 "The soul who sins will die." Jesus could not die for the sins of others according to God.

The Vedas tell many histories which have in many ways have been verified by archeology. Searching for Vedic India outlines many examples of Vedic teachings and histories being corroborated by archeology and science.

Vedic teachings cannot be corroborated by archeological evidence alone because Vedic arguments often provide metaphysical interpretations of historical events that are beyond the scope of archeological evidence.
Archeological evidence for events in a story does not prove the veracity of the story because works of fiction often reference historical events.

We accept the vast majority of meaningful human knowledge without scientific evidence, particularly in the case of social knowledge. This truth criterion would eradicate almost all perfectly useful knowledge.

We accept the notion that the physical human body in front of us is a person, not on the grounds of objective evidence from physics, chemistry or biology, but rather on the grounds of what Daniel Dennett calls the "intentional stance" in human perception; no actual evidence, but socially necessary. Wilhelm Schmidt's extensive analysis of documentation on pre-literate peoples contains evidence of monotheistic beliefs among a wide range of peoples.

Where Schmidt does treat tribes with less monotheistic beliefs, it is in the context of comparing them to the similar but more monotheistic mythologies of their neighbors.
According to the linked article, Schmidt's thesis about the monotheistic nature of the primeval religion is historically untenable.

Although Schmidt's overall methodology, data, and theses need to be corrected by the most recent research, this does not negate the documented evidence of monotheistic beliefs among the peoples surveyed in his work.

"What would a general rational person believe, given the arguments and evidence available?" is a question that can be answered. It is the standard sort of question addressed by scientists and philosophers.
Having no proof of God's nonexistence, at least his existence cannot be dismissed as a clear false.

Red herring fallacy: This argument bears no direct relationship to its parent claim. The truth value of the parent claim is unaffected by this claim's truth value, so even when this line of reasoning is sound, it can't be used to prove its opposite proposition is true.
Looking for empirical evidence for God is a category mistake, because an immaterial God cannot be observed, tested, and controlled.

If we accept that empirical evidence can conclude that God doesn't exist in this way, then we would also have to accept that we should conclude the immaterial mind doesn't exist, even though we know it does exist.
Positive evidence is not needed for belief in God.
Belief is subjective, and is not relevant to a discussion regarding the objective ontology of an entity (e.g. God).
For the belief in God to be justified, it needs something that justifies it. The evidence is one of the grounds for justification that theists lack.

Belief in the existence of God can be, and often is, held with no justification in regards to the truth of that idea. That is however not a reasonable stance and does not provide justification for the existence of God.

An inmaterial God cannot interact with physical world. There is not empirical evidence for abilities of interacting with the physical world without being a material thing made by atoms. You can't interact with atoms if you are not made by elementary particles.
Modern Prophets of Jesus Christ have restored the truth that God is a physical Being. Doctrines of immateriality or incorporeality were invented after the Bible was written and are not authoritative.
Gravity is a force and it does not seem to have a material existence. It is action at a distance. We don't know what gravity is but we know that it is.
Photons (and subatomic particles) interact with the physical world and are not made of atoms.
The classical God is claimed to have multiple effects on the physical world, therefore observable evidence of its existence is rightfully expected.
Psychosomatic reactions are a material body's reaction to an immaterial thought.

Since God is a spiritual entity, there is enough evidence for his existence in the fact that we feel his presence in our hearts and acknowledge it as such through terms like the Holy Ghost. Feeling him is tantamount to seeing him.
Deriving a conclusion about the existence of a spiritual entity from a premise about the existence of another spiritual entity is circular and entails infinite regress.

Many others do not share this subjective feeling of "God's presence," and may in fact have equally strong subjective feelings that God is an illusion or fantasy. Neither subjective feeling counts as evidence for or against the existence of God.
This claim assumes that "everyone feels God's presence" is a fact when the feeling of God's presence is not clearly defined.

The "feeling" of god is anecdotal.

Anecdotal evidence is a place to start a hypothesis, but if it cannot be tested and validated it holds no philosophical or scientific weight. This is a known logical fallacy known as Hitchens's Razor:
"What can be asserted without evidence can be dismissed without evidence"

This argument is irrelevant because of its materialistic or positivist bias: it assumes evidence can only be physical and anything else is anecdotal. This needs to be proven before it can be used as evidence. Stating it is not enough.

It's not a matter of bias, but rather to work inside the realm of possibilities. It could be stated "I feel this shouldn't be proved" as a response to your argument and it would be just as true as the "I feel god exists" argument because we can't discuss objective truth over feelings. Note that if an assertion is not proven to be false doesn't imply on it being proven true.
Logical positivists argue that "one can not speak about causality on a meta-physical level". Therefore this argument is invalid.
Logical positivists would also argue that such concept of God (purely metaphysical) is empirically unverifiable and therefore meaningless.

Logical Positivism's central tenet has been shown to be self-contradictory. The philosophy holds that "only statements verifiable through empirical observation are cognitively meaningful." (See link.) 

As that statement is not verifiable through empirical observation, the Logical Positivist cannot hold that statement to be meaningful.

Empirical evidence could not prove the existence nor the nonexistence of God, it could only prove the existence of physical things that you could feel and experience such as tables and chairs and the wind. Love or friendship are examples of things that cannot be proven with these methods.

While it might be true that it is impossible to empirically know or prove the existence of love between people, the behavior of the suspected lovers is knowable, and behavior is commonly accepted as evidence of internal emotional states.

Love and friendship are abstract concepts. God, if He exists, is an actual entity; otherwise actions like "praying to God" would be as nonsensical as "having tea with the abstract concept of friendship".

Yet there is empirical evidence for friendship, often found in the actions of friends. Same goes for love. The existence of evidence contradicting the expected actions of a friend or a god are evidence against their existence.

There is no distinction between the idea of immaterial and nonexistent. The immaterial (concepts, ideas, descriptors, abstractions) is at best descriptive of things, but cannot rationally be claimed as existent.
Theism is a set of rational claims to God's existence
Being subjective does not exempt something from existence. Love, courage, skepticism, doubt, etc. are all said to exist because they are known and understood properties of the human experience
If "immaterial" equals "nonexistent", then only physical objects exist. This is an absurdly restrictive meaning of "existence", as it excludes, among other things, all thought and emotion.

One can rationally come to differing conclusions. Only a person with the ability to access all the information in the universe could come to a singular absolute truth with no alternative possibilities

An idea can be, and in fact many times is, transformed into a material object. For example, the idea of a flying machine ultimately turned into an airplane. Therefore ideas exist as they're the proven source of later built objects.

If the universe is stated to have been created by god (which is how god is defined in this conversation), and the universe is material, this claim cannot be logically sustained. 

The universe is stated to be material evidence of god, redefining god so there can be no material evidence for a god constitutes an admission that the god, as defined here, doesn't exist. 

In this context the "immaterial" and the non-existent are the same thing.

If God can speak to one's mind, that would be empirical evidence. If God can perform miracles, that would be empirical evidence. If there is no possible empirical evidence of God, then it differs from "God" as defined in this debate, which would be omnipotent and therefore capable of providing empirical evidence.
If God created this reality as a test to judge our faith, then real evidence of his existence would be deliberately made hard if not impossible.
The evidence might originate from the enemy of the God, or might be placed as a temptation.
One of the crucial concepts in Bible is concept of snake which deceives Eve, and Satan as the tempter. It is possible he would provide false evidence to trick people
Any evidence that does not suit the believer in God might be interpreted as false evidence provided by enemy of the God.
Most definitions of a god see it as the creator of everything. The "enemy of god" would be created by god itself. Therefore, the god would hide itself and not actually be hidden by someone else.
Neither the existence of the enemy of God nor God himself have been established let alone a talking snake.

It is difficult to believe in an all knowing and almighty God who has an enemy and that this loving God allows us to be tricked by him. There are simpler and less convoluted explanations for things being as they are.
The Bible records that miraculous events by Jesus Christ rightly credited to Him were not to be credited to him openly. (Matt. 8:4)studylight.org

A just God could not possibly condemn us for not believing in him as he is doing such a good job in concealing the evidence for his existence. And yet we are told he does indeed condemn us for infidelity.

While conceivably possible, this no more makes God's existence likely despite a lack of evidence than the hiddenness of the wizarding world of Harry Potter makes it likely that said wizarding world exists in real life under our noses despite a lack of evidence.
An arbitrary, eccentric and quixotic "hiding" God is neither just nor compassionate and so not worthy of worship.
"An absence of evidence is not evidence of absence"; it is a non sequitur to argue that a lack of evidence necessarily implies a claim is not true.
An absence of evidence is evidence of absence when we have good reason to expect evidence if there was no absence.
When there is an absence of evidence of X, as a rule, "It seems like there is no X, but really there is an X" is less rational to hold than "It seems like there is no X, and there really is no X."
Most empirical evidence against God derives from an absence of observations of God. A lack of identified evidence is not a positive argument for the non-existence of God.
We have been unable to measure or observe God as they are largely not perceivable with our senses.

Consider the claim, "There are an even number of electrons in the universe." If there is no good reason to believe this, it would be absurd to then conclude that "There are an odd number of electrons in the universe."

However, if one considers the claim "there are exactly 10^80 electrons in the observable universe", given without a good reason to believe it, it would not be at all absurd to conclude that "the number of electrons in the universe is not exactly 10^80".

Seeing as science never answers a question to it's full extent, every conclusion opens a new question ad infinitum. In this sense, it is impossible for science to prepotently disregard that God may exist within infinity.
Science disregards many claims, due to the existence of better explanations. In fact science only regards claims when there is evidence in the first place.
The evidence of the non-existence of God is relative to our time, it may be the case in the future the evidence prove this thesis as incorrect.
Empirical evidence once indicated that the earth was flat.
Empirical evidence from nautical measurements, aerospatial measurements, and outer space observations indicates Earth is and has always been spheroid.
It also may be the case that such evidence never comes up. One cannot appeal to potential future evidence for present questions.
Both the arguments and the counter-arguments on God has been around for thousands of years.
Absence of evidence does not entail evidence of absence.
There are unknown unknowns, Undecidable problems and Open problems that are known to contain impossible or very difficult requirements.
There is no reason to believe any of those problems admits a solution, and until proper evidence is presented, any proposed solutions must be considered suspicious.
Elementary particles existed apart from us being able to generate the evidence.
Absence of evidence is evidence of absence when the evidence should be there.
The parent claim is merely that the non-existence of God is compatible with the lack of evidence, not that the lack of evidence is positive evidence for God's non-existence.

While a lack of empirical evidence is expected on an atheist position, on a theist position the lack of evidence may or may not be expected and thus could serve to undermine one's epistemic confidence in theism.
On interpretation, an absence of empirical evidence could be consistent with either the existence or the non-existence of God, and thus does not significantly contribute to one view or the other.
The God of classical theism is by definition transcendent, immaterial, and incomprehensible, and as such we should not expect the existence of God to be detectable by empirical investigation.

Since empirical evidence by definition entails the observation of that which is contingent, material, and comprehensible, we should expect that a purely empirical construction of the universe would exclude God.
It is the task of philosophical metaphysics, not empirical science, to interpret the significance of empirical observations.
The term empirical definitionally excludes questions of pure logical or theoretical interpretation, and as such God qua purely logical concept would be excluded from empirical evidence.
This does not entail that God could not perform miracles that might be interpreted supernaturally.

While an a priori commitment to naturalism might predispose one to favor even untenable or hypothetical naturalistic explanations, documented and scientifically inexplicable miracles may still strengthen epistemic confidence in theism.
There is an abundance of documented miracle claims that resist naturalistic explanation.
Second sentence of the abstract: "the vast majority of these miracles occur in the third world and lack medical and scientific documentation" - there, a natural explanation.
Since the medically documented reports from western countries were treated not as a statistical sample but rather as case studies, survivorship bias does not apply.
A supernatural interpretation would not be evidence of a God, and this claim does not discount the parent claim
This does not entail that God is not detectable at all, as there may be other forms of evidence besides empirical evidence supporting the existence of God.
It is irrational to make a single claim about a God that is incomprehensible.
A god that is transcendent, immaterial, and incomprehensible is identical to a god that doesn't exist.
This logic would also apply to the empty tomb. The absence of the body could be consistent with natural causes rather than miraculous causes.
Many of the empirical pieces of evidence of the non-existence of God is derived from instances where there should be divine intervention.
A God that is good and all powerful cannot allow suffering, there should therefore be intervention and there isn't in very numerous cases where it is objectively necessary.

If, as Christianity teaches, freedom of will actually exists, then God cannot override one's free will to force them not to rob, rape, or murder. Suffering therefore is not God's fault, but the fault of those who choose to walk away from His precepts.
Mankind without freedom of will is incapable of love. A society of these robots could never do anything of moral significance for good or ill.

For God to be "good" he must, if free will is a "good", allow other beings to take actions that are not "good".  He can still be good and all powerful if he ultimately works towards a good end even if he allows non-good behaviour..
The concept of "goodness" is unintelligible without evil. Evil (technically, the deprivation of good) must have at a minimum, the potential to exist for goodness to be meaningful.
The concept of "goodness" does not have to be intelligible in order for people to have the best possible life.
Being God good he would want to impede the freedom to harm.

When an action infringes upon someone's free will, that person's free will is already compromised. Therefore, without free will being jeopardized any more than without His interference, the outcome of the situation could be improved by God's action.

The identities of the actors here are important.

God grants free will to both the aggressor (A), and the victim (V). It is not clear what would obligate God to revoke A's freedom because A intends to use that freedom to violate V's freedom.
This claim is subjective; it assumes that one has infinite knowledge to understand when divine intervention is objectively necessary.

Infinite knowledge is not necessary to understand when suffering could be avoided by an omnipotent and omniscient being - it takes at least some basic empathy, and at most: knowledge of the direct outcomes.

Most people would assume that the death of a child would be "unnecessary suffering". However, had that child's name been Adolf Hitler, his premature death might have saved the planet much more "unnecessary" heartache. Humans do not have sufficient knowledge to understand what changes small events will make over time.

We do not know whether God is working even now to minimize suffering in the world. The loss of one's child might seem an unbearable pain; however, the survival of that child might have indirect outcomes that would cause far greater evil to materialize.
God often chooses not to rescue, which would require interfering directly with a sinner's free will, but to redeem.

God did not intervene in perhaps the greatest sin of all, the fall of Adam that brought every other sin into the world, but rather chose to send Jesus into the world as a sacrifice to redeem mankind to himself. This permits man to choose--freely--whether he wants to be redeemed, or to continue in his rebellion.
Our will is deterministic, therefore God can determine outcomes without infringing on any freedom of will.

A God that is all-good must necessarily bring about the greatest good. Personal difficulty and trials are known to build character and foster personal growth, and may be better for the individual in the long run than deliverance from all suffering.

Knowing the existence of God or any spiritual rules could detrimental to its own purpose. If its purpose is to teach behavior, the fact that giving rules make the 'teachings' automatically ungenuine, as a rewarding punishing relationship. One become good because one wants reward and no punishment, thus one is conditionally good instead of being naturally good. Which, if God allows himself to be known, does not help the said human condition of being sinful by nature.
This claim is subjective, and assumes that the claimant can accurately identify when divine intervention should take place.

The burden of proof for any non-trivial claim rests on the claimant. A claimant who asserts that "the moon is made of marshmallow" should not expect readers to accept the premise without supporting evidence.

In public discourse the burden of proof (BoP) is not always on the earliest claimant wiki. For those espousing the original premise: "God Exists", the BoP is best defined for the believers to prove it for the discussion here. However, where other assumptions rule (ex.: the proof must be "empirical" or "scientific"), the BoP shifts to those claimants.
The claim is not that the evidence must be empirical. Simply that the evidence that is empirical is consistent with God's non-existence. Which is also not a positive claim.
If this thread is merely about the consonance of empirical evidence with atheism, then invoking the burden of proof to request evidence is irrelevant.

If the request for evidence is a request merely for empirical evidence and not for other kinds of evidence, then indeed the burden of proof does shift to the non-theist to demonstrate why other kinds of evidence must be excluded.
Since much of the evidence for theism is non-empirical, requesting such evidence inorganically changes the subject from empirical evidence to other kinds of evidence, which belongs in another thread.
Lack of evidence for a claim, when evidence for that claim is actively being sought, is indeed an argument for the opposite.
Claiming that God does not exist because we have not found evidence for his existence is committing the fallacy of arguing from ignorance.
An all-powerful God by definition would be capable of keeping their existence hidden, assuming that doing so is in the best interests of ultimate morality.
A claim can be deemed irrational, but without falsifiability it can not be claimed false.
Even if the non-existence of God is consistent with empirical evidence, it may not be the best or most likely interpretation of the evidence.
Empirical evidence can neither prove that God does or does not exist.
God is defined as transcendent, meaning that He exists apart from the universe, which is beyond the scope of the natural sciences because they observe the physical world.
Empirical evidence cannot indicate the non-existence of morality, rationality, beauty, and other metaphysical concepts such as a deity.

This is a false analogy. A being such as a deity is different in kind from abstract concepts such as morality, rationality or beauty, and whether God exists is a different-in-kind question from whether morality, rationality or beauty "really exist".
The concept of a non-physical being is the same, for all practical purposes, as the concept of a non-existent being. They are indistinguishable.

And yet the God concept includes the notion that he has created and then directed the workings of the physical universe. That there are physical effects to the existence of God. The burden of proof is on the believers to demonstrate these empirical claims.
Then it'd be difficult/impossible to detect such an entity, without using science.
Issac Newton claims that while "gravity explains the motions of the planets, it cannot explain who sets the planets in motion.”

According to the Einstein's theory of relativity, planets are in free fall in the gravitational field created by the other nearby objects when they move around the stars. So there is no need to have any entity that would set the planets in motion.
Asking "Who set the planets in motion?", or "Who caused the big bang?" begs the question and assumes without justification that there must be a prime mover.
Empirical evidence could trivially prove that God exists through the direct observation of God's actions such as miracles.
If God were to appear in physical form, God's existence could be proven by observation.
God already has appeared in physical form in the Christian belief, through Jesus Christ.
Insofar as this still opposes the idea that "empirical evidence can neither prove that God does or does not exist", this doesn't oppose the parent.

God's existence could be tested through prayer. If one were to pray for something to happen, and what was prayed for happened, the observation of a prayer being answered would support the existence of God.
Even the direct observation of miracles would be inconclusive as proof of God's existence.
Even the empirical observation of a genuine miracle could be naturalistically rationalized.
Documented, medically inexplicable healing miracles could yet be rationalized as false diagnoses or intentional fabrications.
Personal encounters of God in bodily form could be rationalized as hallucinations.

While truly conclusive proof for anything beyond "cogito ergo sum" is not really possible, sufficient miraculous evidence could make the existence of God as empirically-supported as, say, the theory of gravity, or the idea that the Earth is round.

Empirical evidence need only indicate a conformity to or break from theoretical expectations to be useful. The lack of empirical evidence for God indicates that the world exists without the influence of an ultimate metaphysical being.
A lack of evidence does not indicate that something is irrelevant.
For example, an expert criminal may not leave any evidence, but it would be incorrect to argue that the criminal does not exist because its effects have not been detected.
This example begs the question by assuming that there is some underlying effect that has been detected, namely the heist of an important object which triggered the investigation in the first place.
The existence of Jesus Christ provides evidence for the existence of God.
